<FIRST>r a PM-LenientSentence     04-18 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lenient Sentence,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outrage over Judge's Refusal To Jail Immigrant Wife Killer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enraged by jealousy, Dong Lu Chen smashed his
wife's skull. He was tried and convicted _ and placed on five
years' probation by a judge who agreed with defense arguments that
his guilt was mitigated by his traditional Chinese values.
   The result was a tempest: denunciations by groups representing
Asians and women; threats by the local chapter of the National
Organization for Women to file a complaint with the state
Commission on Judicial Conduct, charging the judge with ``bias and
prejudice''; an announcement that prosecutors would review the case
for grounds of appeal.
   ``There's just no basis for a judge to give this kind of
sentence based on a culture. There is a role for cultural
considerations in some instances, but not in a case where a man has
killed his wife,'' said Margaret Fung, executive director of the
Asian American Legal Defense and Education Fund.
   Chen, 51, could have been sentenced to five to 15 years on his
second-degree manslaughter conviction.
   Chen, his wife, Gian Wan, and their two teen-age children came
to New York from Canton, China, three years ago and found life
difficult. According to testimony, in order to get a job the former
farmer had to leave his family in New York and go to Maryland where
he worked for eight months as a dishwasher.
   When he came home during those months, Chen's 41-year-old wife
refused to have sex with him and he suspected she was seeing
another man.
   In a tearful confession, Chen told police that on the morning of
Sept. 7, 1987, he accused his wife of infidelity. She did not deny
the allegation. Enraged, he attacked her with a hammer in their
Brooklyn home and crushed her skull with eight blows.
   At Chen's five-day, non-jury trial, Hunter College
anthropologist Burton Pasternak testified that the Chinese hold
marriage to be sacred. The defense expert said a Chinese man could
``reasonably be expected to become enraged'' upon learning of his
wife's infidelity.
   However, a spokesman with the Chinese consulate in New York, Yao
Shan Vhou, said that in today's China such rage would not justify
the crime, and a husband could be charged with murder.
   ``If he killed a person, he must be held responsible for it.
It's only common sense,'' the spokesman said.
   At the March 30 sentencing, state Supreme Court Justice Edward
Pincus said Chen had already spent enough time in jail for the
killing _ 18 months _ and said cultural considerations warranted
the light sentence.
   Pincus noted ``the effect of his wife's behavior on someone who
is essentially born in China, raised in China and took all his
Chinese customs with him to the United States.''
   Chen's ``cultural background ... made him more susceptible to
cracking under the circumstances,'' Pincus said.
   While some Asian women interviewed gave Pincus credit for trying
to be sensitive to foreign traditions, all agreed his leniency
showed he was misdirected and had no understanding of modern Asian
law and culture.
   ``We were really alarmed by the sentencing and the image it
sends to non-Asians _ that Asian cultures sanction wife killing,
which is not true,'' said Monona Yin, co-chairwoman of the
Committee Against Anti-Asian Violence.
   Ms. Yin and others said the sentencing sent a potentially more
harmful message to immigrant women _ that the U.S. justice system
won't protect them.
   Feminist leaders said adultery cannot justify reducing the value
of a life.
   ``It was unjust and it degrades women's position back to no more
than a commodity that could be bought or sold or done away with,''
said Doris Koo, director of the civil-rights organization
Asian-Americans for Equality.
   Last week, Pincus' clerk said the judge would not talk about the
case. Earlier, Pincus told New York Newsday that Chen ``is not a
loose cannon. ... This guy's not going to do it again and he has
suffered.''
   Pincus also said the state probation department recommended
probation because Chen had shown remorse.
</TEXT>
