<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CandyWreck     04-18 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Candy Wreck,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>M&amp;Ms Won't Melt in Your Hand, But How About on Asphalt?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREMEN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a chocolate-lover's delight, but a
big headache for everyone else when a candy-ladened tractor-trailer
overturned on U.S. 6 spilling 15 million pieces of M&amp;Ms.
   ``There was candy everywhere,'' said Police Chief Jim Brown.
   It took a dozen teen-agers almost eight hours to collect the
42,000 pounds of candy, including 11.1 million pieces of plain M&amp;Ms
and 4.1 million pieces of peanut candy, said Brown.
   The accident occurred early Sunday when an eastbound van crossed
the center line and struck the tractor-trailer, state police said.
   No serious injuries were reported.
   Brown said the cleanup began at daylight and continued until
mid-afternoon. The teen-agers were hired by the trucking company's
insurers at $10 an hour to pick up the individual and family-sized
packages, many of which had broken open, he said.
   ``Everybody munched on some candy as they went,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
