<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--FewerFrills     04-18 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Fewer Frills,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan to Cut Frills for Foreign Dignitaries' ``Working Visits''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So that it can accommodate more of the foreign
dignitaries who want to visit, Japan will suggest that they forgo
imperial ceremonies and banquets in favor of ``working visits,'' a
Foreign Ministry official said.
   Japan cannot invite more than eight foreign dignitaries a year
if each is honored with ceremonial events at the Akasaka State
Guesthouse and black-tie banquets at the Imperial Palace, the
official said Monday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Dignitaries of more than 40 nations want to visit Tokyo, and
Japan will welcome them for ``working visits'' if they agree to
dispense with the ceremonies in favor of ``practical talks,'' the
official said.
   The government was expected to approve the new system at today's
regular Cabinet meeting, he added.
   He said Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey, due Sunday for a
four-day visit, would be the first foreign guest under the new
system. Haughey is to meet Emperor Akihito, but no court banquets
or ceremonial events are scheduled.
</TEXT>
