<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WinerySlayings 3rdLd-Writethru a0404 04-18 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0404,0963</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accused Winery Killer May Have Left Apologetic Note</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The note...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with details
on when note was found. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ```Forgive me...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLEN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apologetic note was left in the car
of a winery worker before he allegedly slit the throats of his
three young daughters, court documents revealed Monday.
   The FBI, meanwhile, joined the hunt for Ramon Salcido, 28, who
was charged with four counts of murder and three counts of
attempted murder in Friday's rampage, which left seven dead.
Authorities said he may have fled to Mexico and acknowledged they
will have a tough time finding him.
   The note, written in Spanish, was found inside the
blood-splattered 1979 Ford that Salcido is believed to have been
driving before it was discovered abandoned in San Rafael Friday
afternoon.
   Police believe Salcido cut his daughters' throats later that
evening, killing two of them, at a garbage dump 15 miles north of
San Rafael.
   ``Forgive me God, but this law made me do it,'' said the note,
which was written in Spanish. ``We could live better, me and my
children, but what can I do.''
   Officials could not say what ``this law'' meant, but Salcido was
reportedly upset by a child-support court order last week.
   The note was filed in federal court Monday in support of the
FBI's request for an arrest warrant charging Salcido with unlawful
flight to avoid prosecution, which was granted by U.S. Magistrate
Frederick Woelflen.
   An FBI affidavit said investigators believed Salcido had escaped
to Mexico.
   ``We will finally locate him and get him, but it's hard work to
do that,'' said FBI spokesman Chuck Latting.
   Authorities assume Salcido went south ``because he's a Mexican
national. We know that last Christmas he visited Mexico. In
absolute, total honesty we have no indication which direction he
went,'' Latting said.
   ``I would be very surprised if he hung around. He could still be
in Sonoma County as far as we know.''
   Salcido, who comes from the Mexican state of Sinaloa, was
described by some acquaintances as friendly and well-mannered, and
by others as a paranoid cocaine user prone to violent outbursts.
   The slayings began with the deaths of his wife, his
mother-in-law, two of his wife's sisters, and one of his
co-workers. Two of his daughters, Teresa, 1, and Sofia, 4, were
found dead at a garbage dump Saturday.
   A third daughter, 3-year-old Carmina, was reported in stable
condition Monday at Petaluma Valley Hospital with a slashed throat.
Her grandfather, Bob Richards, visited her Monday and both were
protected by armed deputies.
   Salcido was charged with four counts of murder Monday in the
slayings of Mrs. Salcido, Teresa, Sofia and the co-worker. Murder
charges have not been filed yet in the other three killings.
   Salcido was also charged with three counts of attempted murder
in the attacks on Carmina, another co-worker and the co-worker's
wife.
   Although photos and descriptions of the 5-foot-9, 180-pound
Salcido have been circulated to California airports and border
guards, Sonoma County Sheriff Richard Michaelsen theorized that the
former Grand Cru winery worker hasn't strayed far from the murder
scenes in the lush wine-producing county north of San Francisco.
   ``My best guess is that he's laying low. We're assuming he's in
our county or in Marin County,'' the sheriff said.
   ``He may be holed up waiting for the media attention to ease up.
... Anybody who happens on his path is in extreme danger,''
Michaelsen said.
   Latting acknowledged that Salcido is believed to have extensive
contacts within the Hispanic community.
   ``It makes it tough,'' said Latting. ``I mean it's hard, dirty
work.''
   Salcido came the United States as an illegal immigrant, but
apparently became a legal resident after his 1984 marriage to the
former Angela Richards, who was a U.S. citizen, immigration
officials said.
   Grand Cru winery owners offered a $5,000 reward for information,
and another $10,000 was allocated by Gov. George Deukmejian on
Monday. Sonoma County Supervisor Janet Nicholson said she will ask
the Board of Supervisors on Tuesday to chip in $20,000 ``in hopes
that he (Salcido) will be apprehended before harming someone else.''
   Meanwhile, county residents have been unsettled by the killings.
   ``People are real scared around here,'' said Dorothy McCann, a
store clerk who lives in Glen Ellen with her boyfriend. ``We have a
loaded gun in the cupboard. People are just looking at each other.''
   The Los Angeles Times reported that the Salcido marriage became
severely strained after Salcido told his wife, three days before
her death, that he had been ordered to pay substantial child
support to an ex-wife in Fresno County _ a woman Angela Salcido had
known nothing about.
   ``Now I can get an annulment,'' next-door neighbor Steve Nielsen
quoted her as saying.
   Val Hansen, owner of the Valley of the Moon bar about a mile
from Salcido's dingy, one-bedroom home in Boyes, said he used to
see Salcido come in for a beer a couple of times a week.
   ``He was always nice, `Hello, how are you?' That sort of
thing,'' Hansen said. ``He never caused any sort of trouble. ... He
was always upbeat.''
   Hansen said Mrs. Salcido seldom came to the bar with her
husband, but sat primly at his side when she did. ``They never
fought or even bickered, maybe it was almost too perfect,'' he
recalled.
   Brian Mann, a clerk at the Boyes Hot Springs Food Center, said
Salcido told him he married Angela four years ago because she got
pregnant.
</TEXT>
