<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-IRA     04-18 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-IRA,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Challenges Report Clearing British Soldiers in Gibraltar
Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International today questioned an official
finding that cleared British soldiers in the shooting deaths of
three unarmed IRA members in Gibraltar. It said the inquest jury
acted on incomplete evidence. Amnesty noted that Spanish police,
who were involved in tracking the three to the Gibraltar border,
did not testify. It also cited conflicting testimony.
   Britain has faced persistent questions over the March 6, 1988
killing of Irish Republican Army members Mairead Farrell, Daniel
McCann and Sean Savage by a military unit believed to have been
flown in from Britain.
   The shootings stirred an international controversy.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office said it saw the
Amnesty report, which was published today.
   ``As far as we are concerned the whole matter has been fully
considered (by the inquest) and we see no grounds for opening up a
fresh inquiry,'' said a spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The inquest jury ruled 9-2 in September that the killings were
lawful.
   Amnesty, a London-based, worldwide human rights organization and
winner of the 1977 Nobel Peace Prize, demanded anew that a judical
inquiry be made in the killings.
   Its report said the inquest in Gibraltar failed to allay
suspicions of ``an official policy of deliberate planned killings
of suspected members of armed opposition groups.''
   Amnesty sent three observers to the inquest, led by Stephen
Owen, a lawyer and ombudsman of British Columbia, Canada.
   Owen said in an interview Monday that he was not accusing the
British of stepping beyond the law. ``I'm saying doubt remains that
has to be resolved.''
   Amnesty said the inquest in the British colony of Gibraltar was
conducted properly and that the verdict reached fairly, but was
based on ``evidence which from the outset was incomplete.''
   Britain said it acted on information the three were armed and
planned to set off a car bomb in the middle of tourist-packed
Gibraltar, on the southern Spanish coast. The IRA, which is
fighting to rid Northern Ireland of British rule and unite it with
the Irish Republic, acknowledged the three were members sent to
Gibraltar ``on active service.''
   Testimony showed, however, that the three were unarmed; no bomb
was found in their car, and according to witnesses, at least two of
those killed appeared to be trying to surrender when shot.
   The government said the officers feared the agents might have
remote-control devices to explode the car bomb.
   Amnesty complained, ``Details about government policy, the
planning of the operation, and the quality of the intelligence were
not revealed.''
   It said Spanish police testimony could have helped establish
whether the three were known to be without guns or explosives.
   Much forensic evidence was destroyed ``because standard
procedures were not followed,'' and the state pathologist was
denied adequate post-mortem facilities and ballistics reports, it
said.
   The report added:
   ``Most of the key independent civilian eye witnesses were
discovered by media journalists and not by the police. ... The
organization is also concerned that discrepancies between
witnesses' testimonies had not been resolved and that many
questions remained unanswered such as ... from what exact position
the soldiers had fired, and whether the suspects had made attempts
to surrender.''
   It noted that police in Northern Ireland were accused before of
killing when they could have made arrests and said, ``The inquest
has again failed to alleviate public concern that these suspects
were killed rather than arrested.''
   Two weeks ago, British trial lawyer Hilary Kitchin, who also
observed the inquest, wrote that it fell short of international
legal standards and raised questions about the legality of the
killings.
</TEXT>
