<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FusionFallout     04-18 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Fallout,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harsh Fallout Doubted From Premature Fusion Announcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A premature claim by Georgia Tech scientists that
they created low-temperature fusion shows that researchers must be
careful about announcing their findings.
   ``There is a lot of pressure to advertise oneself in this
increasingly competitive world where research money is hard to come
by,'' said Dr. Arnold Relman, editor of the New England Journal of
Medicine.
   ``The public doesn't know what to think. There's a lot of
cynicism about science, a lot of time being wasted.''
   The Tech scientists' claim, the second such that was withdrawn
within the past year, has not prompted the school to put a tighter
rein on what its researchers announce, said Thomas Stelson, Tech's
executive vice president.
   ``We are fundamentally an open institution,'' he said.
``Academic freedom is a sort of a sacred issue. A faculty member
can do whatever he wants. We do not centrally review the hundreds
of papers that go out of here each year nor do we intend to.''
   The ``cold fusion'' claim was retracted two days after the
announcement when the researchers found there may have been
problems with instruments.
   ``My wildest guess is that it won't make any difference,'' said
Joseph Ford, a physics professor known as a dissident voice on the
faculty. ``The individuals who submitted (the experiment) have
something of a track record. I don't think most people will pay
much attention to the fact that they jumped the gun.''
   He said the school may have a temporary public relations
problem, especially because the announcement follows the premature
claim that Tech researchers had produced a metal alloy that could
function at record-high temperatures. Those results in
superconductivity could not be verified by other researchers and
the project was dropped.
   ``But alumni are not going to quit giving and agencies are not
going to quit funding,'' Ford said.
   He said the fact that the admission made the front page might
discourage others from jumping the gun.
   ``But if people wish to be reckless or careless, nothing
prevents that,'' Ford said.
   Officials at the National Academy of Science in Washington,
D.C., declined to speculate on what effects on the school might be.
   Stelson said Georgia Tech has a strong program in areas related
to the experiment and that the announcement should have no effect
on it.
   ``We have a good technical background and we would like to
contribute to this area,'' he said.
   The process of peer review is intended to find faulty methods or
reasoning that might render an experiment or discovery invalid
before the results are presented.
   While not foolproof, it substantially reduces the likelihood of
having to retract announced results.
   The discovery of cold fusion was announced March 23 by
scientists at the University of Utah. The process is seen as a
potential for cheap, clean and virtually inexhaustible supply of
energy.
   The Utah announcement sent scientists scurrying to build their
own versions of the process.
   Five Georgia Tech scientists led by James Mahaffey, using what
they knew from press accounts and computer bulletin boards, came up
with what they thought was a duplicate process.
   After a press conference announcing their work, it was
determined that problems with some equipment put the results in
doubt.
   ``We thought we had it all calibrated right but we found out
that one instrument was more temperature-sensitive than we
thought,'' Stelson said. ``We have new detectors. We're in the
process of checking them out in some detail.''
</TEXT>
