<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Arrest     04-18 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Arrest,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Arrests Man Who Left Phone Number, But Find No Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secret Service agents arrested a 37-year-old man
who called the White House to claim he could breach security
surrounding President Bush's visit Monday, and then left his
telephone number.
   Richard Gregory of Clinton Township was taken into custody at
Selfridge Field Air National Guard base as the president arrived
there to fly out of Michigan, said Jim Hughes, head of the Detroit
Secret Service office.
   Gregory had called the White House earlier Monday.
   ``He stated that he had a theory about how to penetrate the
security around the president. But in that theory, it involved a
man wearing a business suit and carrying a cellular telephone that
would actually be an explosive device,'' Hughes said.
   Gregory left his car telephone number, and police used it to
trace information about him, Hughes said. Officers were on the
lookout when Gregory arrived at Selfridge Field's main gate.
   ``When he was apprehended at the main gate of Selfridge, he was
carrying a cellular telephone. He had a briefcase also,'' Hughes
said.
   An ordnance squad from the base found no explosives after
examining the telephone and blowing apart the briefcase with a
water cannon.
   As Gregory arrived at the base, about 25 miles northeast of
Detroit, the president was arriving at a different gate, and was in
no danger, the agent said.
   Bush traveled to nearby Hamtramck to announce economic
incentives for Poland, speaking before about 4,000 people in this
largely Polish community.
   Agents have no idea why Gregory called the White House, but
treated him as though he were a threat to the president.
   ``When he called the tune, we played it,'' Hughes said.
   Gregory faces federal charges of interfering with a Secret
Service agent's duty. He later was questioned and detained by
Secret Service officials in Detroit and had not been formally
charged Monday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
