<DOCNO> AP890418-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Nahalin     04-18 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Nahalin,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Initial Army Report Finds No Premeditation In Border Police Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAHALIN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli army investigation
into the slayings of four Arabs during a raid by border police
indicates an ``excessive use of firearms, faulty planning and bad
execution.''
   The army on Monday released its preliminary findings of the
bloodshed Thursday in the village of Nahalin, four miles southwest
of Bethlehem.
   Villagers said two police snipers, firing from a second-story
window, killed three young Palestians and wounded several others.
   The International Red Cross denounced the raid.
   Although the initial army report was critical of the border
police, it denied allegations that the police had acted with
premeditation.
   An army spokesman said last week that the paramilitary border
police entered the village before dawn to apprehend residents
suspected of having thrown stones at Israeli cars. He claimed the
police opened fire when rocks were thrown at them.
   Villagers gave a different version.
   They said the raid began 5 a.m. as 22 jeeploads of border police
conducted house-to-house searches and fired indiscriminately as
many residents emerged from dawn prayers during Ramadan, the Moslem
holy month.
   ``They shot at anything that moved _ dogs, donkeys, people,
cars,'' said Naim Shakarneh, whose brother Subheh was among those
killed.
   The villagers said the worst violence occurred outside the
Azawieh mosque when worshipers heard the gunfire, ran into the
streets and began hurling rocks at the police.
   They blamed three deaths on two policemen who they said fired
from a building across the street from the mosque.
   Fatmeh Ibrahim Abu Mor, 28, who owns the building taken over by
the two officers, said they ordered her to let them in, went to a
window on the second floor ``and started shooting.'' She said after
the police left she found more than a dozen cartridges on the floor.
   Residents said the three Palestinians were killed within 20
yards of each other _ one on the roof of a low building, another
near the mosque and the third in the street beside a rock slab.
   The fourth Palestinian was killed in a cemetery across the
street from the mosque, according to the villages.
   Doctors at Jerusalem's Makassad Hospital said a fifth victim was
brain dead.
   It was one of the deadliest single incidents since Arabs in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip began an uprising against Israeli
occupation in December 1987.
   Rajah Shehadeh of Law in the Service of Man, a West Bank
affiliate of the Geneva-based International Commission of Jurists,
called the Nahalin raid an act of ``willfull killing and bodily
harm.''
   He said Monday the group appealed to signatories of the Fourth
Geneva Convention, which deals with the protection of people in
occupied areas, ``to meet their clear obligation.''
</TEXT>
