<DOCNO> AP890418-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-18 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baby boomers move over. Three guys in their 20s
are talking about their generation and promising to ``end the '60s
in your lifetime.''
   ``Let's make nostalgia a thing of the past!'' is the rallying
cry of the National Association for the Advancement of Time, whose
members say they're tired of the boomers' cultural agenda.
   ``There's so many of them. If they want to live in their past,
that's fine _ but they're forcing ME to live in their past,''
gripes Bruce Dillenburg, 29, of Chicago. He founded NAFTAT with
friends Bruce Elliott of Los Angeles and John Keeney of New York
City.
   Here's a sampling from Dillenburg's long list of complaints:
   Movies _ ``The Big Chill.''
   Theater _ the revival of ``Hair.''
   Television _ ``The Wonder Years.''
   Books _ volumes on the riotous 1968 Democratic National
Convention in Chicago, ``as insignificant an event as ever happened
in this country.''
   Dillenburg and Elliott got together in 1987 and discovered their
mutual exasperation with ``oldies'' radio. They decided it was time
to get the Monkees off their backs.
   Preserve what is worth remembering from the '60s _ the Beatles,
Bob Dylan and the civil rights movement, for example _ and scrap
the rest, Dillenburg suggests.
   NAFTAT is part of a natural anti-boomer backlash, according to
Northwestern University sociologist Bernard Beck. He says any
cultural statement that lasts too long ``seems to generate
resentment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DAHLONEGA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Roberts may not be rich, but he knows
how to get to the gold faster than anyone else.
   Roberts, of Diamond Bar, Calif., won Sunday's 27th annual speed
gold-panning contest with a time of 7.55 seconds _ an unofficial
world record, according to the contest's organizers.
   The old record was 9.23 seconds, set in 1985 by Bob Box of
Ahwahee, Calif.
   The contest tests a person's ability to swiftly sift through a
pan of sand and leave eight clean nuggets. It had been held for a
quarter-century in Rosamond, Calif., but was moved last year to
Dahlonega, site of an 1828 gold rush, the nation's first.
   Roberts' victory kept the contest trophy in the family. His
father, Jack, took home the gold last year with a time of 12.73
seconds.
   ``I think this record will stand for at least five to 10
years,'' the father said. ``There was a lot of history set here
today. This is going to become a big national event.''
   His son wasn't so sure.
   ``I've seen pans in practice as fast as five seconds so until
the record gets down to five seconds, I can't see it lasting,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As if New York weren't expensive enough. The
cost of loving it is going up.
   The state, after years of allowing manufacturers free use of the
``I Love New York'' logo, will start charging royalties this year.
   People who print the logo on sweatshirts, keychains, pens or
other consumer goods will be forced to give New York state between
6 and 10 percent of the money they make, said Stephen Morello, a
state deputy commissioner for economic development.
   The state has spent more than $100 million advertising itself to
tourists since beginning the ``I Love New York'' advertising
campaign in 1977, he said.
   ``We think this is one modest way to begin recapturing some of
the investment without negatively impacting the motto's
effectiveness,'' Morello said.
   The state registered the motto with a red heart symbol in place
of the word ``love.'' Though the symbol has been adapted for a
variety of bumper stickers and other uses, the state only holds the
trademark for loving New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
