<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-US     04-18 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-US,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Group Opens Office In Panama To Watch Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. organization that sent
American observers to the Philippines for that country's disputed
1986 elections has opened an office in Panama to monitor the May 7
general elections.
   The government, however, issued a statement Monday warning that
it had not authorized any foreign organization to open electoral
information offices but stopped short of saying it intended to
close the Center for Democracy office.
   Allen Weinstein, president of the Washington-based center, told
a news conference that his organization's goal is to help bring
about ``national reconciliation'' and democracy in Panama.
   A letter signed by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of
the Senate subcommittee on hemispheric affairs, said the opening of
the office demonstrates the U.S. government's worry about whether
Panama's government will live up to its promises to hold free
elections.
   Weinstein said the office will give out ``informal and
unofficial information'' about ``all phases of the electoral
process.''
   The Center for Democracy includes Republican and Democratic
party leaders and senators.
   Panama said it had invited election observers from Antigua,
Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras, Jamaica and Nicaragua.
   Relations between the United States and Panama have deteriorated
since Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's de facto leader, was
indicted by a court in Florida on drug-running charges in February
1988.
   President Eric Arturo Delvalle then tried to fire Noriega, but
the general orchestrated Delvalle's ouster. The United States has
imposed economic sanctions on Panama through April 1990, but
President Bush said the sanctions could be modified if the
elections are fair.
   The Center for Democracy was founded in 1984.
</TEXT>
