<FIRST>r w PM-OverseasVoters     04-18 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overseas Voters,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Americans Voted Overseas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smaller proportion of Americans voted in
last year's presidential election than in 1984, but the rate went
up for those who voted while abroad, according to the head of the
Federal Voting Assistance Program.
   Henry Valentino said the overseas rate rose to 35.3 percent from
33 percent four years earlier, based on an estimate that 2.5
million civilian Americans were outside the country on Election Day.
   But despite the improvement, that rate was still lower than the
overall turnout, which was 50 percent.
   ``It's because so many Americans abroad don't know they're
allowed to vote, or find it too much trouble to get an absentee
ballot,'' Valentino said in an interview. ``It's not like just
going down to the corner polling place.''
   He added that the increase last year was due to efforts made by
both political parties to get out the vote.
   Many states have slow and complex procedures for issuing
absentee ballots, especially to Americans who live in other
countries. Some voters mail in their ballots too late for them to
reach election boards in time to be counted.
   Valentino calculated that 21 House seats and eight Senate seats
could have been decided by the absentee vote.
   Of the roughly 750,000 members of the armed forces stationed
abroad, 63.2 percent voted, compared with 55.3 percent in 1984.
Valentino credited ``intensive and aggressive voting assistance''
by the military for the high rate among that group.
   Valentino's office is part of the Department of Defense, but is
responsible for helping both the military and civilians overseas to
vote.
   Older soldiers, like older civilians at home, were more likely
to vote. In the armed forces only 46.2 percent of the 18- to
20-year-olds turned in ballots, compared with 71.6 percent for
those 45 and older.
   Each military unit has an officer responsible for helping get
out the vote. Valentino said their efforts were visible in an even
bigger increase of voting by dependents of Americans in the armed
forces _ spouses, grown children and other relatives in their
households. That rate jumped to 57 percent from only 27.6 percent
four years earlier.
   Voting by the 200,000 civilian employees of the U.S. government
abroad and their dependents also increased, rising to 64.5 percent
from 57.5 percent in 1984.
   But in general, a smaller proportion of Americans vote than do
residents of other countries with unrestricted elections.
   ``I used to say it was fewer than in any country except
Botswana,'' said Curtis Gans, head of the Committee for the Study
of the American Electorate.
   ``Now I understand that Botswana is ahead of us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
