<FIRST>u a AM-KmartExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0423 04-18 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K mart Explosion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0423,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Injured In Pipe Bomb Explosion At Department Store</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7 with three grafs to CORRECT spelling to Minier
sted Minear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pipe bomb exploded at a K mart department
store Monday night, seriously injuring a 5-year-old girl,
authorities said.
   Only about 50 shoppers were in the store when the bomb went off
and no other injuries were reported, but the mother of the child
was treated for fainting, police said. The source of the bomb was
not immediately known.
   The victim, Erin Bower of Indianapolis, lost four fingers and
half of her left hand in the explosion, and also suffered facial,
eye and abdominal injuries, authorities said.
   She was taken to Methodist Hospital, where she was listed in
stable condition before undergoing surgery, hospital spokesman
David Richards said. The explosion occurred about 7:50 p.m. at a K
mart in northeast Indianapolis, said a spokesman for the Castleton
Fire Department. There was no fire.
   Scott Minier, a spokesman for the Marion County Sheriff's
department, described the bomb as having a ``pressure-sensitive
release.'' He said it was concealed among packages of trash bags in
the hardware section toward the rear of the store.
   ``We believe it was in another box stashed in the trash bags,''
Minier said. Police dogs trained to sniff out bombs were searching
the store late Monday.
   Minier said there were no bomb threats or any other warning that
the bomb would explode.
   Louis M. Profeta, a medical student at Indiana University, said
he was shopping with his girlfriend when the explosion occurred.
   ``We were a few aisles away, we heard a loud muffled explosion,
like a large balloon exploding,'' Profeta said. ``Then we saw a
cloud of smoke and flaming debris shoot up in the air. I went
running toward the area then I thought it might be a gunshot blast,
so I stopped.''
   Profeta said all of the shoppers in the store and the K mart
employees scrambled for the door after hearing the explosion. Then
he and another shopper with some medical training went to help the
girl.
   ``I saw the little girl, her clothes were on fire and the mother
was screaming. Both father and mother were covered in blood,''
Profeta said. ``We rendered first aid and got the father and mother
away, then got her stabilized.''
</TEXT>
