<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-18 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Hatch Act Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has voted overwhelmingly to repeal
major portions of the Hatch Act and let federal Civil Service
employees participate in partisan political activity on their own
time.
   Despite the 297-90 House vote Monday, final enactment into law
is far from certain. The House approved an almost identical bill
last year, but it died in the Senate.
   The administration is opposed to the bill and Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh has said he will recommend a veto should it reach
President Bush's desk.
   The measure was pushed strongly by various unions representing
federal workers, and their leaders were quick to praise the House
members who voted for it.
   ``This is not a political party issue ... it's a political
freedom issue,'' said Robert M. Tobias, president of the National
Treasury Employees Union. ``We urge the Senate to join the House in
standing firmly on the side of rights for federal workers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>As Costs Rise for Poor, Number of Available Homes Shrinks</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor families face a shrinking number of
low-cost homes and apartments, even as federal spending and the
number of families aided rises, according to a private study.
   More of the poor had to pay more for housing because of soaring
costs from 1978 to 1985, said the study titled ``A Place to Call
Home.''
   The study was produced by two groups that generally advocate
increased funds for social programs, the Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities and the Low Income Housing Information Service.
The authors used data from a 1985 housing survey.
   The study said the proportion of poor renting families who pay
at least 60 percent of their income for rent and utilities rose
from 44 percent in 1978 to 55 percent in 1985.
   The number of houses and apartments available for a monthly rent
of $250 or less _ 30 percent of the income of a family making
$10,000 a year _ was 9.7 million in 1970, or 2.4 million more than
the comparable number of families.
   In 1978, there were still 370,000 more units than families, but
by 1985 the number of families had risen to 11.6 million while the
number of houses and apartments available at $250 or less had
fallen to 7.9 million _ a deficit of 3.7 million affordable housing
units. Of the 7.9 million, 800,000 were vacant and 1.5 million were
occupied by families with incomes above the poverty line.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>House Approves Bill To Make King Holiday Commission Permanent</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has passed legislation to make the
Martin Luther King Jr. Federal Holiday Commission a permanent
agency with authorized spending of $500,000 a year.
   The legislation, sponsored by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., passed
the House Monday on a 305-84 vote. A similar measure is pending in
the Senate, which failed to act before adjourning last year on a
House-passed bill to make the commission permanent.
   The commission was established by Congress in 1984 to
institutionalize the federal holiday in honor of the slain civil
rights leader. Authorization for the commission expires May 1.
   Conyers told the House on Monday that the commission is needed
more now than ever before because most young people have no
first-hand knowledge of the civil rights movement.
   While the commission has received no federal funds in the past,
Conyers and other supporters of the bill argued that the $500,000
annual authorization is needed because private funds for the
panel's work have been drying up.
   The Senate bill, sponored by Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., would extend
the commission for five years at a cost of $1.5 million.
</TEXT>
