<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Malaysia-Turtles     04-18 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaysia-Turtles,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Biologist To Help Save Giant Turtles From Extinction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American biologist has embarked
on a two-year effort to help Malaysia save from extinction a
species of sea turtle that scientists say has been around for at
least 150 million years.
   Jeanne A. Mortimer, assistant professor at the Archie Carr
Center for Sea Turtle Research at the University of Florida in
Gainesville, arrived in February to work on saving the endangered
giant leatherback turtle.
   She said in a telephone interview today that the World Wide Fund
for Nature and the Malaysian Fisheries Department asked for her
help after she attended a conference on turtles in Kuala Lumpur in
1987.
   ``We want to increase the success rate of the hatcheries ...
besides educating the public on how to treat the leatherbacks,''
said Ms. Mortimer, who has worked on similar projects in Costa
Rica, Nicaragua, Mexico, Brazil, Pakistan and Thailand.
   The turtles, which reach as much as 6{ feet in diameter and
1,100 pounds, roam the seas as far away as Japan, Australia and the
Philippines and live as long as 100 years.
   Between June and August they return to lay their eggs on eight
miles of sandy beach on the South China Sea at Rantau Abang, 180
miles northeast of Kuala Lumpur.
   Ms. Mortimer said that in the 1950s, about 2,000 of the giant
leatherback turtles, whose scientific name is Demochlys Coriacca,
came ashore to lay eggs. Last year, however, just 40 to 50 returned.
   The alarming decline in the turtles' numbers has been attributed
to pollution, pilfering of eggs and disturbance by tourists.
   Officials say some leatherbacks mistake plastic bags for jelly
fish, the staple of their diet, and choke to death.
   Some Malaysians eat the turtles' eggs, which are a little
smaller than tennis balls, because they think it will improve their
sexual prowess.
   Ms. Mortimer said she will conduct courses for hatchery workers,
tourist guides and the public on how to treat leatherbacks.
   Also, hatchery workers will be on hand when the turtles return
to lay their eggs and will build fences around them.
   Maylasia recently passed a law that bans eating the eggs and
their collection, unless they are gathered for hatching.
   Since 1961, the Fisheries Department has collected endangered
eggs and reburied them. After about 55 days, baby turtles emerge
and are released into the sea.
   About 450,000 turtles have been released like this, but only one
in 1,000 survive to reach adulthood because other sea creatures
prey on them, scientists say. The turtles lay between nine to 14
eggs at a time and visit the beach five to nine times during the
season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
