<FIRST>r a PM-OverweightNurse     04-18 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overweight Nurse,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Private College Wrongfully Dismissed Student For Obesity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private college wrongfully dismissed a
nursing student when it forced her to leave the school because she
did not lose weight, a federal jury ruled.
   The jury Monday told Salve Regina College in Newport to pay
Sharon Russell $30,515 for tuition and wages she was deprived of
while completing her nursing degree at a school in West Hartford,
Conn.
   ``No one has the right to put any student through what I went
through,'' said Russell, 24. ``Hopefully it will deter this from
happening again.''
   Russell weighed 328 pounds in her junior year, around the time
she signed an agreement with the Roman Catholic college that she
would lose 2 pounds per week for the rest of the academic year or
drop out. She also agreed to regularly attend Weight Watchers
meetings.
   Russell was ultimately given a passing grade and allowed to
register for her senior year on the understanding she would diet
during the summer, which school attorney Steven P. Snow said she
did not do.
   In the fall of 1985, the college informed Russell she would not
be allowed to return for her senior year. It maintained Russell's
obesity had interfered with her ability to perform certain clinical
duties.
   ``A college ought to have the right to establish their own
standard minimum requirements and enforce those,'' said Snow.
   The $2,775 Russell paid for her first semester tution was not
refunded, said her attorney, Edward T. Hogan.
   The school breached its contract with Russell because she
substantially performed her educational duties and the contract for
weight reduction, said Hogan. He said she maintained a grade-point
average higher than 3.0 out of a possible 4.0, and only failed a
clinical course because of an instructor's bias.
   Snow said Russell had difficulty teaching diet classes and with
cardio-pulmonary resuscitation.
   Snow said the college had the same right to respond to Russell's
overeating as it would if a student's performance were affected by
drugs or alcohol addictions.
   ``I would think that every college in American would be
concerned about the adverse precedential affects of this ruling,''
he said.
   Russell said students in her class who smoked were not forced to
sign similar contracts.
   Russell, who said she gained weight after leaving Salve Regina,
completed her degree at St. Joseph's College, where she had to
repeat her junior year because her Salve Regina credits for that
year were not accepted.
   Russell, now a nurse in St. Petersburg, Fla., said she lost
substantial weight after she had her stomache stapled in August
1986, while at student at St. Joseph's. She declined to divulge her
current weight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
