<FIRST>r a PM-Doctor-Fraud Bjt   04-18 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor-Fraud, Bjt,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancer Specialist Vows Fight To Clear Name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor has vowed to clear his
name of fraud charges filed by Switzerland despite being barred
from traveling abroad by a U.S. judge, who feared cancer patients
might die in his absence.
   Dr. Rajko Medenica's trial on charges of defrauding the Swiss
government of $2.6 million opened Monday in Geneva. It was recessed
until Wednesday so the Swiss judge could consider a defense motion
for postponement until Medenica can attend.
   Medenica, a native of Yugoslavia who became an American citizen
last year, was ordered in March to surrender his passport and
remain in the United States by federal District Judge Sol Blatt Jr.
   Several of Medenica's patients had said they might die if the
doctor were jailed in Switzerland and unable to continue his
treatments.
   Medenica has developed a form of cancer therapy that tailors
interferon treatments to individual patients, many of whom who have
been treated unsuccessfully elsewhere.
   His patients include former heavyweight boxer Muhammad Ali, who
was given the treatment for a blood disorder.
   During a recent interview, the physician said he feels caught
between his responsibility to his patients and his desire to return
to Europe to clear his name.
   ``As a new American, I don't want to start my life by having
something dirty and something I'm not responsible for happening in
Europe,'' he said.
   The Swiss government alleges Medenica was responsible for fake
billing while treating patients, including many Yugoslavs, at a
state hospital in Geneva and a private clinic from 1973 through
1981.
   In 1983, he was sentenced in absentia in Yugoslavia to 20 years
in prison on related charges and his Yugoslavian property,
including a seaside villa, was confiscated.
   While jailed in Switzerland for 15 months as authorities
investigated his case, 36 of his patients died, according to court
documents.
   Medenica was released from the jail in 1984 after former South
Carolina Gov. John West, whose daughter was treated for throat
cancer by Medenica, persuaded a judge to grant bond. West also
helped raise much of Medenica's $300,000 bail.
   The doctor then came to Hilton Head Island and with the help of
South Carolina's two U.S. senators, Strom Thurmond and Ernest
Hollings, fought Yugoslavia's request for extradition.
   Medenica, 49, strongly denies any fraud. He says his records
show he performed all the services for which he charged, even
giving Yugoslavs a 50-percent discount. The billing, he said, was
handled by the Yugoslavian consulate and Swiss authorities.
   ``I am always concerned about my patients,'' he said. ``One of
the biggest problems ... in Switzerland was that I was blindly
looking at the patients and the other people organized the
billing.''
   Attorney F. Lee Bailey, who represented Medenica during his
hearing before Blatt in Charleston, admitted the billing documents
were false but said they were not fraudulent.
   ``If patient A got $100 worth (of services) and was charged $50
and if patient B got charged $100 and got $50 worth, at the end of
the day justice was done but the documents were false,'' he said in
a telephone interview from Boston.
   If the Swiss proceed with the trial without Medenica, Bailey
said he will ask Blatt to reconsider his order keeping the doctor
in this country or appeal the ruling to the 4th U.S. District Court
of Appeals.
   Bailey also suggested the Swiss case could be tried in the
United States because it is based largely on documents. That would
allow Medenica to attend the trial and tend to his patients, he
said.
   In their motion in the Swiss court Monday, Medenica's attorneys
asked for a postponement of eight to 12 months so the doctor could
train someone to care for his patients in his absence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
