<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Crash-Prison     04-18 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash-Prison,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crash Foils Helicopter Escape Attempt, Two Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MH1, PD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter pilot's inexperience and poor choice
of aircraft may have been the difference between a daredevil prison
escape of a drug kingpin and the tangled wreckage lying inside the
compound.
   Moments after former powerboat champion Benjamin ``Barry''
Kramer leaped onto the small helicopter that swooped into the
exercise yard Monday morning, the craft's rear rotor became tangled
in the 12-foot fence surrounding the Metropolitan Correctional
Center.
   ``Had he not hit the fence, he would have escaped,'' said Warden
John Clark.
   The crash left Kramer with a broken right leg; pilot Charles
Clayton Stevens, 34, of Gold Beach, Ore., suffered two broken legs
and facial injuries.
   They were taken to Jackson Memorial Hospital, where they were
listed in guarded but stable condition today.
   Although Stevens once spoke of his love for working in a hostile
environment, he was known to regulars at nearby Tamiami Airport as
a nervous airman with a student pilot's license.
   ``He was very squirrelly on the helicopter,'' said Paul Barth,
president of Biscayne Helicopters Inc. ``We sort of stayed away
from him.''
   Other experienced pilots wondered about Stevens' selection of
the two-seat Bell 47-1A helicopter to try to snatch Kramer, who is
serving life without parole for distributing half a million pounds
of marijuana throughout the Midwest.
   ``In my opinion, that would not be the kind of bird to use,''
said airport patrolman Rich Fisher. ``That's an observation
helicopter. It's no work horse. It's a light-duty, slow-moving
machine.''
   Calvin R. Coady, a flight instructor for Aris Helicopters Ltd.
of San Jose, Calif., said Stevens paid him $35,000 in cash for the
37-year-old helicopter Dec. 17.
   ``I remember it very well _ the majority of the money was $100
bills, with a few 50s,'' Coady said, adding that the large amount
of cash made him suspicious but that he didn't ask Stevens about
its source.
   Most of the 1,000 prison's inmates are awaiting federal trial.
The 36-year-old Kramer was being held in a special high-security
area because he was considered an escape risk.
   ``We are not surprised to hear of the attempted escape. After
all, Mr. Kramer is a man of tremendous wealth facing a life
sentence,'' said Tom Cash, special agent in charge of the Drug
Enforcement Agency in Miami. ``But we never anticipated the
method.''
   The DEA in February warned the U.S. Marshal's Office that Kramer
might be planning to break out, Cash said. Kramer would have no
problem financing an escape, he said.
   ``We estimate that Kramer made about $60 million in drug
smuggling,'' Cash said. ``We only confiscated $20 million in cash
and we know he used offshore banks.''
   The brazen escape attempt unfolded like the 1975 Charles Bronson
movie ``Breakout.''
   ``That movie has given everybody the idea that escaping prison
in a helicopter is a piece of cake,'' Cash said.
   Stevens dropped low enough for Kramer to jump onto one of the
landing skids. The helicopter started to rise, but then caught its
rear rotor in the wire atop the fence around the 50-by-200-foot
exercise area and crashed.
   Kramer was sentenced after his conviction in Illinois with
former car-racing star Randy Lanier on charges of running a
multimillion dollar pot-smuggling ring.
   He was brought to the prison outside Miami to face a
marijuana-smuggling indictment in Fort Lauderdale and a Miami gun
charge.
   U.S. Marshal Dan Horgan said Kramer now faces an attempted
escape charge, which carries a maximum sentence of five years in
prison, and Stevens faces charges of aiding an escape.
   In an interview last summer with The World newspaper of Coos
Bay, Ore., Stevens said he was a sea diver who harvested sea
urchins, albacore, clams, kelp, mussels and oysters for export to
Japan.
   ``My goal is to make money,'' he told the newspaper. He added
that although he could make as much as $1,500 a day as a diver, he
wasn't in the business only for the money.
   ``I'm trained for that environment,'' he said. ``It's exciting,
an adrenaline high. It's just such a hostile environment. I love
it.''
   He also said the diamond earring he wears would one day pay for
his funeral.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
