<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-18 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Exchange's Key Index Sets Another Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index overcame
losses in early trading to close at yet another high today, and the
dollar rose slightly against the yen.
   The dollar closed at 132.10 yen, up 0.27 yen from Monday's
131.83 yen finish. It opened at 132.23 yen and ranged between
132.00 yen and 132.27 yen
   In the previous three trading days, the dollar had slipped a
total of 1.02 yen.
   The dollar-yen rate moved little today as market players awaited
the release later in the day in Washington of the U.S. consumer
price index for March, traders said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added
13.33 points, or 0.04 percent, and finished Tuesday's trading at a
record 33,321.66. It also had set a record Monday when it gained
157.89 points to close at 33,308.33.
   The index lost in morning trading but recovered in the afternoon
as investors, expecting little increase in the U.S. price index,
started buying, said Kenji Ishizuka of Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   ``This showed that market players were quite optimistic about
the figure, which they think wouldn't be much different from last
month,'' he said.
   The market expects a 0.6 percent increase in the price index in
March, up from February's 0.4 percent.
   Other dealers said some investors were concerned the price index
might show signs of inflation.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.1 billion shares,
up from Monday's 750 million. Among gainers were steel and
machinery issues.
