<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-PublicRadio     04-18 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Public Radio,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Public Radio Network to Exxon's Money: `No,Thanks'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alaska Public Radio Network board has
decided to return $32,283 that Exxon Corp. had donated to help the
network cover the Exxon Valdez oil spill.
   ``I think there is a perceived conflict of interest,'' network
executive director Diane Kaplan told the board at an emergency
meeting Monday. ``I believe it would be inappropriate for us to
accept it.''
   Exxon officials said late last week that the oil company had
sent the network a check after they learned state legislators were
considering a supplemental budget request for the money.
   Network officials said at the time that they would accept the
check and that they did not consider it an ethical issue.
   Exxon, the owner of the tanker that ran aground last month and
spilled more than 10 million gallons of oil into Prince William
Sound, has underwritten network programs in the past, as have other
oil companies.
   Exxon's oil-spill contribution, however, was unusual in that it
was provided as reimbursement for coverage of a specific news event
in which it has been accused of negligence.
   Kaplan stressed that network officials did not ask Exxon or the
legislators for the money, and that accepting it would not have
compromised news coverage by the network's member stations.
   However, the board agreed that the appearance of a conflict of
interest could jeopardize the network's credibility. The six-member
board voted unanimously to return the check with a letter of thanks
to Exxon.
   Exxon spokeswoman Jan Cool said the company understood the
board's reasoning.
   ``Our intentions were entirely honorable,'' she said. ``We
certainly wouldn't have made the grant if we felt we were putting
the public broadcasting network in any kind of compromising
position.''
</TEXT>
