<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0611EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Politics     04-18 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Politics,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peres Turns Aside Challenge at Party Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres turned aside a
challenge to his leadership of the left-leaning Labor Party at a
marathon meeting where he came under stiff criticism for his peace
policies and for losing the last national elections.
   The 12-hour session of Labor's Central Committee on Monday
underscored widening dissatisfaction with Peres' handling of
Israel's second largest party.
   Peres came under attack mainly from four party officials and
Cabinet ministers who have already announced or indicated
intentions to try to unseat him at the party's convention in 1990.
   But the challengers never brought their proposals to a vote and
Peres boasted today that the meeting's result amounted to backing
for his leadership.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a longtime rival of Peres, did
not speak at the meeting. Analysts believe he would be the most
serious challenger to Peres if he steps forward at the convention
next year.
   One of the challengers, former party secretary Uzi Baram, said
the party needed a more dovish platform and should support peace
talks ``with every Palestinian who recognizes Israel, including the
PLO.''
   The Israeli government rules out talks with the PLO, which it
considers a terrorist organization.
   Peres is more dovish than Shamir in his peace policies, but he
backs the refusal to talk to the PLO. The party platform expresses
that view but there are growing voices for a more flexible approach.
   Three other challengers to Peres who have also urged conditional
talks with the PLO focused on Labor's electoral loss to the
right-wing Likud bloc of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Likud edged out Labor 40 to 39 seats in the 120-member
parliament last November. Labor later joined Likud as a junior
partner in a broad-based coalition government.
   Peres, foreign minister in the last joint government, took the
finance job this time, aiming to help his movement's ailing
collective farms and industries. However, the new job has virtually
locked him out of influencing foreign policy.
   ``We have to analyze our failures, we have to correct them.
People should realize that it's time to change leadership,'' said
Mordechai Gur, a minister without portfolio.
   ``There was an ideological failure, an organizational failure
and a failure of leadership,'' said Iraqi-born Energy Minister
Moshe Shahal, another challenger. The fourth was Communications
Minister Gad Yaacobi.
   ``I know there is not a good feeling or mood in the party,''
Peres responded, speaking to the 1,300 party delegates at a Tel
Aviv convention hall.
   ``Those who feel that I should continue, vote for me, and those
feeling that someone else should, vote for him,'' Peres said.
   He told army radio today that the results clearly left him in
charge. ``I never received a vote of confidence like at this
meeting,'' Peres said.
</TEXT>
