<FIRST>r a PM-Wright-O'Neill     04-18 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-O'Neill,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Speaker Defends Wright</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former House Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip''
O'Neill defended his besieged successor, calling Jim Wright ``the
most honest and decent man I know.''
   The House Ethics Committee on Monday formally charged the Texas
Democrat with 69 violations, including trying to evade limits on
outside earnings.
   ``Jim Wright would never do anything he thought was wrong or was
breaking the rules of the Congress,'' O'Neill said Monday.
   O'Neill said perceptions of ethical behavior have changed since
the Nixon years, and few people would survive the intense scrutiny
focused on those in public life today.
   He also criticized the committee for hiring a professional
prosecutor to investigate Wright.
   ``He's just out there to see if he could nail someone,'' O'Neill
said. ``Here he is with 69 particulars. You only do that with a
grand jury. They're treating Jim differently than they ever treated
anybody else. I feel sorry for Jim Wright.''
   One charge accuses Wright with using a book he wrote,
``Reflections of a Public Man,'' to evade limits on outside income.
The committee says he sold a large quantity of the book to a group,
claiming the payment as royalties.
   O'Neill said he believed the sale could have been accomplished
by Wright's staff without his knowledge.
   He called other charges technical ommissions, little items a
public official may forget to report, putting him in violation of
various rules.
   Wright is ``the most honest and decent man I know,'' the retired
Massachusetts Democrat said during a speaking engagement here.
   O'Neill said he believes committee members had to come up with
the charges to justify the $1.5 million they spent on the
investigation, which has gone on for most of a year.
   ``They chase after so many things out there, especially with the
leadership,'' said O'Neill. ``There are not many people who you
can't go over tooth and nail and find something. We're being
over-investigated.''
