<FIRST>r a PM-IncomeTaxesRdp     04-18 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Income Taxes Rdp,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millions in Last-minute Rush to Beat Tax Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nothing is certain but death, taxes and last-minute income tax
returns, and two extra days to file didn't change that for millions
of Americans.
   Filers jammed post offices, IRS information centers and
accountants' offices on Monday.
   ``Human nature doesn't change because they have two more days,''
said Helen Adorjan, an Illinois Revenue Department spokeswoman.
``They just procrastinate two more days.''
   Time for dithering ran out at midnight Monday because April 15
fell on a weekend. Many people were grateful for the reprieve.
   ``I got it done Sunday night,'' said Dennis de la Mata of
Chicago. ``The extra two days made a big difference. This is the
first time in nine years that I filed on time.''
   Businesses that thrive on tax season also found reason to cheer.
   ``We're taking in more clients, a lot of new clients,'' said
Idelle Rubino, a receptionist at the H&amp;R Block office near the
University of California, San Francisco, Medical Center. ``More
time to pay means more won't take the time to do it themselves
until the last minute.''
   Long lines and traffic jams surrounded many post offices, but
some people found ways to ease the strain.
   Los Angeles rock station KLSX-FM offered coffee and donuts at
the downtown Terminal Annex, the city's main mail processing
center, which posted buckets at curbside until midnight.
   ``We want to add some merriment and not make the people feel bad
that they're procrastinators,'' said KLSX disc jockey Peter Tilden.
   The home of the Dallas Cowboys saw unusual off-season activity
as the Internal Revenue Service set up shop at the Texas Stadium
ticket office. IRS officials passed out advice while a pizza
delivery service passed out free pies and an entertainer in Mickey
Mouse costume helped ease tensions.
   In Pittsburgh, the first game of the National Hockey League's
Patrick Division finals between the Penguins and the Philadelphia
Flyers apparently helped prevent a late filing crunch.
   ``It's been crazy, but good. It was a little more congested last
year,'' supervisor Don Smith said at the downtown post office. ``We
had people dropping off their returns on their way to the hockey
game.''
   Protesters with complaints about how the government will spend
the tax checks also gathered at filing points.
   In San Francisco, members of the Berkeley-based Northern
California War Tax Resistance distributed $6,000 from people who
refused to pay all or part of their taxes because they contend 60
percent of federal income taxes are used for ``war and war
preparations.''
   The Philadelphia Jobs With Peace Campaign protested quietly
outside the city's main post office by displaying model tanks, guns
and bombers. And six placard-waving members of the Libertarian
Party flanked lines of cars outside the main post office in Tuscon,
Ariz., urging people to support abolition of the income tax.
   George Paris, who says he is homeless but paid taxes on his
earnings from part-time jobs, stood near the Birmingham, Ala., post
office holding a sign reading ``Build Homes, Not Bombs.''
   An estimated 6 million Americans were expected to file their
income taxes on Monday, according to the IRS.
   Not everyone had to have their returns in the mail last night.
   Residents of Rhode Island, New Hampshire, Maine, Connecticut,
upstate New York and Massachusetts got an extra day because Monday
was the Patriots' Day holiday in Massachusetts. They have until
tonight to mail returns to the IRS office at Andover, Mass.
   But already, IRS officials elsewhere were busy planning for next
year. They will hold a public meeting a week from today in
Indianapolis for suggestions on how the agency can do its job
better.
   ``We're hoping people won't forget about taxes now that tax
season is over,'' said Carolyn Stumpf, an IRS spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
