<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     04-18 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Vice Minister Charged With Bribery In Recruit Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors filed bribery charges today against a
former senior government official caught up in the Recruit
stock-profiteering scandal and said they will now focus the
investigation on politicians.
   Aides of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone profited in the stock deals, but both
men have denied any personal wrongdoing.
   The scandal has seriously eroded public confidence in the
Takeshita government, and support for the prime minister fell below
4 percent in a poll by Kyodo News Service last week.
   The Tokyo District Public Prosecutor's Office today charged
Kunio Takaishi, 59, a former vice minister of education who was
arrested on March 28.
   He was the 14th person _ all businessmen or bureaucrats _
arrested so far in the scandal.
   All now have been formally charged, and prosecutors said they
would turn their attention from bureaucracy's part in the scandal
to the role of politicians.
   Takaishi is accused of receiving bribes from Recruit Co. and
providing favors for the information and publishing conglomerate.
   Others who have been charged include Recruit founder Hiromasa
Ezoe; Takashi Kato, a former vice minister of labor; and Hisashi
Shinto, former chairman of Japan's telecommunications giant, Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
   Recruit sold unlisted stocks in a subsidiary at bargain prices
to about 160 influential politicians, public officials and
businessmen. The buyers profited handsomely when the shares were
listed for public trading and shot up in price.
   According to a 1988 Supreme Court decision, the sale of stock
bound to rise in price and not available to the general public
could amount to bribery.
   At least 17 politicians, including Takeshita and Nakasone, have
been linked to the scandal directly or through stock purchases by
aides.
   In addition, Takeshita has acknowledged receiving more than $1
million in political contributions from Recruit in 1986 and 1987,
but has said the donations all were legal.
   Despite repeated demands from opposition parties that he resign
and call elections to allow a public judgment, Takeshita has vowed
to stay on and push for political reforms.
   Passage of the budget for this fiscal year, which began April 1,
has been blocked by an opposition boycott of Parliament in support
of demands that Takeshita resign or call Nakasone to Parliament for
questioning about his role in the affair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
