<HEAD>Dollar Stable in Thin European Trading, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fluctuated in a narrow range in
extremely thin European trading late this morning as the market
awaited key U.S. inflation statistics.
   Gold prices moved up.
   The release today of the U.S. consumer price index for March was
likely to give an indication as to whether there was any room for
the U.S. Federal Reserve to ease monetary policy, traders said.
   One Rome trader said a rise in the index could lead the Fed to
tighten monetary policy and the dollar would rise.
   Another Rome trader said market sentiment toward the dollar was
neutral and that it was uncertain that the inflation report would
move the dollar out the doldrums.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7090, compared with
$1.7095 Monday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday:
   _ 1.8633 West German marks, up from 1.8565
   _ 1.6385 Swiss francs, unchanged
   _ 6.3070 French francs, up from 6.2825
   _ 2.0999 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0953
   _ 1,366.50 Italian lire, up from 1,364.00
   _ 1.1850 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1855
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.27 yen to a closing 132.10 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at 132.25 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $385.25 a troy ounce, up
from $385.00 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $385.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $385.40, up from $384.50 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 6 cents to close at a bid
$386.68.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.81 a troy
ounce, up from Monday's $5.80.
