<FIRST>r a PM-LottoFever     04-18 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotto Fever,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Pool Funds, Land Share of Record Lottery Jackpot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: MaryAnn in 3rd graf is CQ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family ties proved wildly profitable for two
clans who combined to win half of the record $69.9 million Illinois
Lotto jackpot.
   The two families, with members in four states, claimed their
$17.5 million prizes Monday, while the holders of two other winning
tickets had yet to be identified by state officials.
   ``We just couldn't believe it,'' said MaryAnn Dixon, 37, of
suburban Naperville, when she and her husband discovered after
Saturday night's drawing that they were winners. ``When we called
everyone, no one would believe us. We had to keep repeating, like,
`Hey, we're not kidding.'''
   The winning ticket was one of 15 Mrs. Dixon bought on behalf of
herself, husband Daniel and 10-month-old daughter, Kate, as well as
her parents _ Louis and Mary Matlosz of Elizabeth, N.J. _ and two
brothers and a sister and their families in New Jersey. Mrs. Dixon
is expecting a second child in July.
   Daniel Dixon, 38, said he had no plans to quit his job as a
mechanical engineer for Molex Inc. of Lisle, an electrical
component manufacturer. ``I like my job,'' he said.
   Not so with some other winners. Ron Miller, 36, of Little York,
said he plans to quit his job as a hog buyer at a meat packing
plant and ``try something a little more fun _ maybe professional
bass fishing.''
   Miller, who is married and has a 10-year-old daughter, will
split his winning share with brother Scott, 29, of Chandler, Ariz.,
and a brother in Stafford, Texas, represented Monday by his wife,
Barbara.
   Scott said he plans to stop driving a delivery truck and travel
or take some courses, while Barbara said she plans to pay debts and
invest in her new dress-designing business.
   Ron Miller said he called his sister-in-law Barbara on her
birthday six days before the drawing and suggested a three-way,
15-ticket pool, ``seeing as the lottery prize was so high.'' He
said he was ``hysterical'' after learning of his fortune.
   The news got around fast in Little York, a town of about 300 in
west-central Illinois, and a big sign in the post office declared,
``Congratulations, Ron.''
   The final figure for the jackpot, boosted by four winner-less
drawings and a frenzy of ticket-buying last week, was $69,940,000,
said Lottery Director Sharon Sharp. The prizes will provide each
family with about $874,000 a year before taxes for 20 years.
   The two other winning tickets were sold in the Chicago area and
in southern Illinois, and officials said the holders were expected
to come forward later this week.
   The winners beat odds of 12.9 million to 1 to pick the six
winning numbers from 1 to 54: 3, 14, 32, 40, 46 and 54.
   The jackpot beat the previous record U.S. lottery payout of
$61.98 million last October in California. That pot was split among
three winning tickets.
   The largest single winner in U.S. history remains a Florida
woman who won $55.16 million in her state's lottery in September.
</TEXT>
