<SECOND>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Police Break Up Strikes, Students Clash With Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with student-police clashes in
three cities but protests peaceful in Seoul. Picks up 5th pvs, `About 18,000...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police firing tear gas stormed four
factories held by strikers and arrested 175 workers today, and the
government warned it would use troops to keep vital industries
running if labor unrest spreads.
   Also today, radical students battled riot police in three cities.
   Officials said riot police seized the electronics and machinery
factories at dawn in Puchon on the western outskirts of Seoul after
strikers refused to give up. Some strikers hurled firebombs and
rocks at the officers, but police officials said they had no
reports of serious injuries.
   Radical students calling for the overthrow of President Roh
Tae-woo's government staged campus protests in Seoul and other
cities today, the eve of the anniversary of a student uprising on
April 19, 1960.
   Students hurling firebombs and rocks battled riot police in
campus clashes in the provincial cities of Chonju, Suwon and Taejon
when authorities blocked them from marching into the streets.
Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said about 2,500 students
were involved in the provincial protests.
   About 8,000 students shouting ``Down with dictatorship!'' and
''Yankee go home!'' staged a peaceful march through eastern Seoul.
Thousands of riot police watched but did not intervene apart from a
few minor scuffles.
   About 18,000 riot police were mobilized in Seoul to prevent
violent protests, officials said.
   Police stormed the Seoul office of a government lawmaker and
overpowered eight students who had attacked the office with
firebombs and then occupied it, officials said.
   ``Overthrow Roh Tae-woo,'' the students yelled during the attack.
   The government has warned that a growing wave of strikes
threatens South Korea's political stability and the economy.
   Labor Minister Chang Yung-chul urged workers and management to
settle wage disputes peacefully.
   But Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon also issued orders to use
troops and military equipment to keep vital industries running if
threatened by strikes. Kang said radicals fomenting labor unrest
would be sternly punished.
   Officials said there were no immediate plans to deploy military
forces.
   Government officials charged that militant labor unions were
trying to organize a nationwide strike to mark the May 1
international labor holiday. Union leaders have denied the charge.
   Industrial workers, many of whom are poorly paid and work long
hours in poor conditions, are demanding major wage increases to
share in South Korea's growing prosperity.
   The government ordered a major crackdown on labor disputes after
Roh warned last week that strikes threatened to hamstring the
economy. He said walkouts had cost $2.4 billion in lost production
and that exports were down $600 million so far this year.
   Two of the country's three car producers, Daewoo and Kia, said
today they had resumed partial production after being forced to
halt operations Monday.
   But Hyundai, the nation's biggest car producer, said it had not
resumed operations because of strikes and a shortage of spare parts.
   Also today, some 200 journalists staged a peaceful protest in
Seoul to denounce the government for arresting two journalists who
wanted to visit communist North Korea. The protesters said the
government was trying to suppress press freedom.
</TEXT>
