<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Rebels     04-18 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Rebels,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Rebels Claim Capture Of Strategic Garrison Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels claim to have captured a
strategic garrison town in southern Sudan where an international
relief effort is trying to avert 100,000 famine deaths.
   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, in a Radio SPLA
broadcast monitored in Nairobi, said they had taken the town of Bor
on Monday and wiped out its garrison.
   ``Remnants are being mopped up in the forest around the town,''
the rebels said in the broadcast Monday.
   Bor lies in the heart of the southern Sudanese region targeted
by a U.N.-coordinated relief effort that hopes to deliver, before
rains begin next month, May, enough food to feed 2.3 million people
until October when the rains traditionally end.
   Failure of the project could mean starvation for 100,000 people,
say relief officials who estimate that more than 250,000 southern
Sudanese died in 1988 due to war and the famine it created.
   However, U.N. officials now concede less than half their
original target of 105,000 tons will be met due to bureaucracy,
sluggish donor support and poor planning.
   Bor is about 125 miles north of Juba, a town key in the $132
million relief effort and the government's last major stronghold in
the south.
   The rebels took up arms against Sudan's Moslem-dominated
government in Khartoum in 1983, demanding autonomy and more
economic development for the predominantly Christian and animist
African-descended south.
</TEXT>
