<HEAD>Curfew Ended, Search Continues for Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and INSERTS new 14th graf ``Beridze said...''
to include official saying one of the dead was shot by soldiers. </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today lifted the curfew in the capital
of Soviet Georgian and searched for 14 people reported missing
after troops broke up a pro-independence demonstration in the
city's center.
   The curfew was imposed in Tbilisi after the military tried to
disperse the demonstrators on April 9 and at least 19 people were
killed. A Georgian official acknowledged Monday that one of the 19
was shot by soldiers.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, a native of Georgia and
a former Communist Party chief of the republic, said the violence
damaged President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform efforts.
   Shevardnadze has been in Georgia for more than a week trying to
ease tensions.
   ``We should learn how to communicate with the people, for the
destiny of perestroika, democratization and renewal of our society
depends on this,'' he said in remarks distributed by the official
Tass news agency. ``There is no other road.
   ``What happened in Tbilisi is a tragedy for the people. Vast
damage has thus been done to perestroika and democratization
processes.''
   Official Radio Moscow said Georgian officials decided on Monday
to lift the curfew after noting a ``substantial improvement of the
situation in the city.''
   Students were reported to be back in classes today and public
transportation was operating normally.
   Lea Umanishvili, chief editor of Georgian television in Tbilisi,
said the curfew was lifted this morning. And Zurab Lomidze, deputy
director of the Georgian news agency Gruzinform, said on Monday
that the soldiers and tanks, which arrived on April 7, would begin
leaving today.
   Ms. Umanishvili said in a telephone interview from TV
headquarters that no tanks and only a few soldiers were visible on
the streets.
   She said the Ministry of Health still was searching for 14
people listed as missing after the clash. The list consists of
three or four boys ages 11 to 13, two women, and the rest men, she
said.
   Tbilisi residents have been plastering lists to walls charging
that 100 people disappeared after the clash and that many of them
died in addition to the 19 in the official death toll.
   Rolad Beridze of the Georgian Foreign Ministry denied the rumors
of a higher death toll. He said Monday that most of the reported
disappearances had innocent explanations.
   Beridze said Monday that soldiers shot and killed one resident
who was violating the first night of the curfew on April 9. He said
two companions were wounded with the curfew violator.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda said Monday that three
girls who had reportedly disappeared were found to have been taking
a vacation at a suburban resort.
   Pravda today quoted district military officials as saying that
the curfew and the military operations had cost $1.6 million.
   The area has been closed to foreign reporters.
   The demonstrations began on April 4 when protesters criticized
calls from members of the republic's ethnic Abkhazian minority to
break away because of alleged discrimination by Georgians.
   Other protesters have demanded Georgia secede from the Soviet
Union because of alleged interference from the central government.
</TEXT>
