<FIRST>r a PM-SmokingFlap     04-18 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smoking Flap,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Smolder Over University Smoking Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where there's no smoke, there's ire _
particularly when a public university in this tobacco-growing state
tries to limit smoking.
   Members of the Legislature's Tobacco Task Force raised the
threat of reprisals Monday against the University of Louisville
over a policy that took effect March 1 limiting smoking to
designated areas in 100 campus buildings.
   ``We've got basically some people that are wanting to bite the
hand that feeds them,'' said Sen. John Rogers.
   The task force ordered a study of tobacco's contribution to the
Kentucky treasury and the size of the University of Louisville's
share. The Legislature convenes in 1990 to write the budget for
higher education through 1992.
   Rep. Clay Crupper, who called for the study, said his
tobacco-growing constituents were angry about a state institution's
implied hostility toward tobacco.
   ``They pay a lot of taxes,'' said Crupper, chairman of the House
Agriculture Committee. ``I've got letter after letter, `Whatever
you do, don't let them have any of our tax dollars from tobacco
because they don't deserve it.'''
   Dan Hall, special assistant to university President Donald
Swain, and Larry Owsley, university vice president for
administration, said the policy was not a slap at tobacco growers
or discrimination against employees who smoke.
   ``We're not on any crusade. We are in this to try to regulate a
situation in a working environment,'' Owsley said.
   But the task force was unmoved.
   ``You folks remind me a lot of a teen-ager who needs money, but
you're somewhat embarrassed about your parents,'' Rogers said. ``If
something happens that the money ... you want is not forthcoming,
then I think that you're going to have to bear a part of the
burden.''
   The senator said the smoking restrictions should be scrapped.
   ``If you've got a few people that are squealing because they
don't like the smoke, which do they like the best or the least? The
smoke or the paycheck? Because tobacco is very instrumental in
paying their salaries,'' Rogers said.
</TEXT>
