<FIRST>r a PM-BostonMarathon-Newspage 1stLd-Writethru a0512 04-18
0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boston Marathon-Newspage, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0512,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abebe Mekonnen, Ingrid Kristiansen Win Boston Marathon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to RESTORE time element; PICKS UP 3rd graf
pvs, `Mekonnen, 25 ...'; A longer version moved on the sports wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERT ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Track Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abebe Mekonnen continued Ethiopa's domination of
men's marathoning and Norway's Ingrid Kristiansen turned the tables
on rival Joan Benoit Samuelson in winning the Boston Marathon.
   Mekonnen broke away from Tanzania's Juma Ikangaa with about 1{
miles left in the 26-mile, 385-yard race Monday to win in 2 hours,
9 minutes, 6 seconds, the seventh fastest time ever in the
93-year-old race.
   Mekonnen, 25, missed the 1988 Olympic marathon because his
country joined North Korea's boycott of the Seoul Games. He said he
was happy with his victory but added, ``I don't consider it my
Olympic race.''
   Ikangaa finished second in 2:09:56 and John Treacy of Ireland
came in third in 2:10:24, just as they did last last year.
   Kristiansen failed in her bid to become the first woman
marathoner to beat 2:20, but she led every step of the way and
wasn't seriously challenged in taking her second victory here.
   Her winning time of 2:24:33 was the third-fastest ever for a
woman.
   Samuelson, the 1984 Olympic champion and course record-holder at
2:22:43, struggled to come in ninth in 2:37:51. She had beaten
Kristiansen in their three previous meetings.
   Marguerite Buist of New Zealand finished second among the women
in 2:29:04 and Kim Jones of Spokane, Wash., was third in 2:29:34.
   Each of the winners received $45,000, plus appearance money. The
race drew 6,418 official entrants.
</TEXT>
