<FIRST>u i PM-KhashoggiArrested 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 04-18 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khashoggi Arrested, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0514,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Arms Merchant Jailed In Marcos Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details of charges, background;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested Saudi arms dealer Adnan
Khashoggi today on U.S. charges that he helped Ferdinand and Imelda
Marcos hide millions of dollars in paintings and property plundered
from the Philippines.
   Khashoggi, a jet-setting financier known for his big deals and
an alleged central role in the Iran-Contra affair, faces charges
stemming from ``illegal property dealings,'' a Justice Ministry
statement said.
   The Marcoses fled the Philippines in February 1986 after the
military-civilian uprising that deposed Marcos and brought
President Corazon Aquino to power. They are accused of taking an
estimated $3.5 billion in cash and property.
   The U.S. government has accused Khashoggi of fronting for Marcos
to help divert and hide the former president's ownership of real
estate and valuable art.
   Khashoggi, 54, was arrested in a Bern hotel this morning and was
taken to the district jail in downtown Bern, the ministry statement
said.
   It was not immediately known why he was in Bern but he is
reported to hold interests in several European companies. His
office in Saudi Arabia declined immediate comment on the arrest and
referred inquiries to Khashoggi's lawyer, identified as Sami Fadel,
whose whereabouts were not disclosed.
   U.S. indictments naming the Marcoses, Khashoggi, five other
people and a California bank accuse the couple of plundering more
than $100 million from the Philippine treasury to buy real estate
and expensive art objects in New York.
   Khashoggi, the reputed broker of the arms deal at the heart of
the Iran-Contra scandal, was indicted in October in New York on
racketeering and other charges in the case.
   Khashoggi, who has lived in Paris, is accused of submitting a
false document to French officials who were seeking evidence at the
request of U.S. investigators.
   He also posed as the owner of paintings and New York property
secretly held by the Marcoses, prosecutors have said.
   Specifically, he is charged with racketeering, obstruction of
justice and mail fraud. Conviction of the charges would carry
penalities ranging from five to 20 years in prison.
   The Philippines claims that after the Marcoses went into exile
in Hawaii, their agents and Khashoggi carted away 25 paintings from
New York properties owned by the Marcoses. The action allegedly
came after a California federal judge ordered that none of the
Marcoses' property could be moved.
   Khashoggi allegedly sold 12 paintings for $3.2 million.
   The Swiss Justice Ministry statement said a warrant for
Khashoggi's arrest was issued March 24.
   Under the terms of a U.S.-Swiss extradition treaty, U.S.
authorities will have to formally request Khashoggi's extradition
within the next 60 days.
   Khashoggi has 10 days to file an appeal and request his release,
the announcement said. The Federal Tribunal, Switzerland's supreme
court, would have the final say if he fights an extradition order.
   Khashoggi, born in Mecca as the oldest son of the personal
physician of the late King Ibn Saud, has been in the headlines for
decades.
   Known for his flamboyant lifestyle and negotiating talents,
Khashoggi figured in several kickback scandals with U.S. aircraft
manufacturers paying him large amounts for arranging multi-billion
dollar defense contracts.
   He was also involved in the Iran-Contra affair in which proceeds
from sales of U.S. arms to Iran allegedly were funneled to
U.S.-backed rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist government.
   At one time, published reports estimated his personal wealth at
up to $4 billion. But declining oil prices and stricter control of
arms dealings were said to reduced his fortune.
   Mrs. Marcos has pleaded innocent to the charges contained in the
U.S. indictment. Marcos has said he is too ill to appear in New
York for legal proceedings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
