<FIRST>r w PM-Ginsburg-SecretOpinion 1stLd-Writethru a0466 04-18 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ginsburg-Secret Opinion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge's Censors Own Dissent, Citing Security Concerns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd and next last grafs to add attribution to Washington
Times</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The statue shows Justice as blind, and federal
appeals Judge Douglas H. Ginsburg says it sometimes needs to be
invisible as well.
   Ginsburg proved his point by deleting two-thirds of his dissent
in a case before releasing it publicly. Ginsburg said he was
withholding 12 of the 18 pages because his opinion was based on
secret government information, The Washington Post and The
Washington Times reported today.
   Civil liberties lawyers were quick to criticize the highly
unusual procedural step, and one likened it to secret actions of
the notorious Star Chamber that existed in England until 1641.
   ``It's bad enough to have secret evidence,'' said Kate Martin,
director of the American Civil Liberties Union project on national
security litigation. ``His dissent is an effort to write secret
law.''
   Ginsburg's opinion was issued in a suit alleging the FBI, as
part of its domestic surveillance program of the 1950s and 1960s,
engaged in illegal activity to discredit a New York man who was a
Communist Party member.
   The plaintiff alleged that government agents planted a
fictitious report in a car he used, causing Communist Party members
to think he was a government informant and expel him from the party
in 1964.
   The government wanted the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District
of Columbia to order a lower court to dismiss the case without
hearing it because it didn't want to release material that the
defense wanted to obtain through pre-trial discovery proceedings.
The appeals court rejected the government request.
   The appeals court majority said the government had not presented
compelling evidence that disclosure of its activities 20 and 30
years ago would result in disclosure of state secrets today.
   But Ginsburg, whose nomination to the Supreme Court was
withdrawn two years ago after it was revealed he had smoked
marijuana, said the lower court had ignored the government's
``legitimate and compelling interest in preventing disclosure of
exceedingly sensitive national security information,'' the
newspaper said.
   However, major portions of the judge's dissent were deleted from
the version released publicly and also from that given to the
plaintiff's lawyers. Only government lawyers were allowed to see
the full version.
   The Post and Times said court officials could not remember any
other instances in which the appellate court here had issued a
secret opinion.
   Mark Lynch, former head of the ACLU national security project,
told the Post: ``This is unusual and goes further than any case I'm
aware of. On the face of it, it's troubling. Our whole system of
law depends on court decisions being public.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
