<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GunsinSchool     04-18 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guns in School,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Schools Launch Anti-Gun Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest school system plans to
teach its students not to carry guns.
   Schools Chancellor Richard Green on Monday announced a week-long
``teach-in'' next week for all students on the dangers of guns,
with a list of suggested activities.
   The youngest could prepare art work warning about guns, for
example; the oldest could hold debates or write model gun laws.
   ``Violence and weapons have no place in schools,'' Green wrote
to parents of the system's nearly 1 million pupils. Yet, he noted,
guns and other weapons are confiscated in the schools daily.
   Green called for help at home with the program, asking that
parents teach nonviolence and caution against drug use, which was
linked to the prevalence of weapons. He also warned that children
caught with weapons would be suspended.
   About 200 guns were confiscated from pupils in 1987-88, the last
school year for which figures were available, said Board of
Education spokesman Bob Terte.
   In a separate program, the board has been placing monitors with
hand-held metal detectors at the entrances to five high schools, on
a rotating basis. That program is being expanded to 10 more schools
in September.
   No weapons have been found on pupils, but some weapons turn up
in the bushes outside when word gets out that the monitors are
present, Terte said.
</TEXT>
