<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Bomb     04-18 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Bomb,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Say No Solid Link Between Monday Blast, Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have found no
evidence linking two jailed Palestinians to the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103, even though a similar bomb was seized in a probe of the
suspected terrorists, officials said today.
   A 35-year-old federal police officer was killed and another was
critically wounded Monday when they tried to disarm the bomb.
   Alexander Prechtel of the federal prosecutor's office said
investigators only have ``very vague'' indications the two
Palestinians held by West German authorities may have been involved
in the Pan Am disaster.
   All 259 people aboard the Pan Am plane and 11 on the ground died
in the Dec. 21 terrorist attack in which a bomb disguised as a
radio-cassette player blew up the jet over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   A similar bomb hidden in a radio tuner exploded at the federal
police headquarters in Wiesbaden on Monday as two experts were
trying to defuse it.
   The 29-year-old officer who survived the blast was fighting for
his life today, said Willy Terstiege, a spokesman for the
Bundeskriminalamt, the federal police headquarters.
   Jochen Schroers, spokesman for the Frankfurt prosecutor's office
involved in the Pan Am investigation, said Monday's blast ``has
nothing whatsoever to do with our investigation.''
   The two Palestinians, alleged members of the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, remain in
investigative custody in West Germany following their arrest in
October after what police said was the biggest illegal weapons bust
in the nation's history.
   Prechtel said the bomb that exploded Monday was discovered
during investigation of the Palestinians, but he and other
officials declined to say when or where the explosive device was
found.
   Terstiege said two bombs were delivered to the Wiesbaden
headquarters Monday by authorities in the West German state of
North Rhine-Westphalia, where part of the October weapons
confiscation took place.
   Security sources, who requested anonymity, said the bombs were
discovered in raids on suspected Palestinian terrorist hideouts.
They also declined to say when or where the bombs were found.
   Officials of the Hesse state prosecutor's office, which is
investigating Monday's explosion, refused to comment on how similar
that bomb was to the one that blew up the Pan Am jet.
   Investigators in the Pan Am case have concluded the plane was
blown out of the sky when a detonator sensitive to changes in air
pressure set off plastic explosives packed into a radio
cassette-player in a suitcase.
   An identically disguised bomb containing Czechoslovak-made
plastic explosives was among the large quantity of weapons and
explosives seized in October raids of suspected hideouts of the
Popular Front in Frankfurt and Neuss.
   Police arrested 14 suspects in the October raids but only the
two remain in custody: Hafez Kassem Dalkamoni and Abdul Fattah
Ghandanfar.
   Prechtel said they are suspected of trying to set up terrorist
cells in West Germany.
   ``We have no evidence that the two might have been involved in
the Lockerbie bombing,'' Prechtel told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview from Karlsruhe.
   ``British investigators said the Pan Am explosion was caused by
the same type of (plastic) explosive that was found in Frankfurt,''
he said. ``But they haven't given us any proof of this.''
   CBS News last week cited unidentified U.S. government officials
as alleging that 21-year-old Khalid Jaafar unwittingly carried the
bomb aboard the plane in his baggage.
   But Prechtel said evidence shows that Jaafar, one of the victims
of the bombing, was innocent.
   ``As far as I know, the British have said the bomb was in a hard
suitcase,'' Prechtel said Monday. ``Mr. Jaafar seems to be
innocent. We know Mr. Jaafar had two small, soft-covered bags, so
we have no evidence that someone gave him a bomb.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
