<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Chile-Strike     04-18 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Strike,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Black Out Capital as General Strike Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of bombs today blacked out most
of the capital, damaged a government office, and injured one man at
the start of a one-day general strike against the military
government, police said.
   There were no immediate claims of responsibility for the
attacks. However, leftist urban guerrillas have often bombed
electric towers while battling the 15-year-old regime of Gen.
Augusto Pinochet.
   Today's explosions began shortly after midnight, destroying
several power towners and blacking out large areas of this city of
4.5 million people. Some neighborhoods remained without power well
into the morning.
   Several other bombs went off around Santiago, injuring one man
and damaging the government office, a bank and other buildings,
police said.
   It was not immediately clear if the strike had succeeded. Public
transportation was reduced, but thousands of workers walked to
their jobs or took the few operating buses.
   The government said Monday it had taken ``all the necessary
measures'' to prevent disorder and urged people to go to work.
Police were reported on maximum alert, and officers with machine
guns guarded some street corners.
   The strike was called by the United Workers Central, the
nation's largest labor federation.
   It is demanding freedom for its two top leaders, who were
banished to provincial towns last year for calling a strike in
October 1987. That strike was the last mass protest against the
government.
   The labor group also wants an increase in the monthly minimum
wage from $59 to $100.
   Diego Olivares, the labor group's acting president, said Monday
the strike should be peaceful.
   However, some leftist groups called for street demonstrations
today in Santiago and other cities. Police said they would not
allow such protests.
   A series of mass protests shook the government from 1983 to
1986, leaving at least 200 dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
