<DOCNO> AP890418-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-StadiumDisaster 2ndLd-Writethru a0508 04-18 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stadium Disaster, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0508,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with inquiry starting, judge's comments,
writs filed, Hurd calls for European soccer chief to retract. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Peter Taylor began a government-ordered
investigation of Europe's worst soccer disaster today, as a
14-year-old boy lost his fight for life and brought the death toll
to 95.
   Taylor, a lord justice of appeal, said he wants to ensure
similar tragedies never occur.
   In Switzerland, Europe's chief soccer executive apologized for
comparing English fans to wild animals. But Jacques Georges,
president of the European Union of Football Associations, also has
indicated that fans' behavior at the club semifinal in Sheffield
may keep British clubs barred from European cup tournaments,
despite a recent vote to readmit them in 1990.
   Of 170 people injured Saturday, 25 still are being treated in
Sheffield. Nineteen are in intensive care.
   A coroner was to start an inquest today to determine the cause
of six of the deaths. Police have identified all the victims except
the boy who died today.
   Newspaper reports indicated the deaths may have been caused by a
police officer's attempt to prevent a fatal accident among fans
pressing to get into Sheffield's Hillsborough stadium.
   In Liverpool, nine injured fans filed writs in the High Court
seeking damages for personal injuries. The writs allege negligence
or breach of duty against South Yorkshire police and the Sheffield
Wednesday soccer club whose stadium was the scene of the disaster.
   Before heading to the stadium, Taylor held a news conference
with West Midlands Chief Constable Geoffrey Dear, who is conducting
a separate inquiry into the actions of South Yorkshire police.
   ``I would respectfully say to all those who are disposed to
comment on this terrible disaster that it would be better for us to
wait to ascertain the facts before proposing any solutions,''
Taylor said.
   He promised his inquiry will cover all aspects of the tragedy,
including the behavior of fans outside the match, policing, sports
ground safety, crowd control and government plans to require soccer
fans carry identity cards.
   ``The focus of the inquiry will be to find out what happened and
make recommendations as to how this situation can be avoided in the
future,'' Taylor said.
   Evidence from fans would form an important part of the inquiry,
which will include public hearings, he said.
   Dear said evidence from the police inquiry will be passed to
Taylor and the coroner.
   ``This inquiry is seeking the truth and to cut away the
mythology that is beginning to grow,'' he said.
   The disaster occurred Saturday at an English Football
Association Cup semifinal between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest.
   All the victims were Liverpool fans either crushed against a
crowd-control fence in front of a standing-room-only terrace or
trampled or suffocated by the panicked crowd.
   Officials and fans accuse police of letting thousands of fans
into the stadium late and then responding too slowly when
late-comers crushed fans against the 10-foot-high fence. There also
are charges some fans had forged tickets or no tickets at all for
the sold-out match at the stadium, which has a capacity for 54,000.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the Cabinet member responsible for
police, told Parliament on Monday the government may ban
standing-room-only terraces at major soccer clubs.
   He also said the police officer's decision to open the outer
gate will be a central question for Taylor's inquiry. Survivors say
4,000 fans were pushing at the turnstiles trying to get inside.
   The Times of London today said Superintendent Roger Marshall
ordered the gate be opened because he feared late-comers would
force the collapse of a wall next to the gate.
   The judge who headed an inquiry into the 1985 Bradford fire when
56 people died cautioned today that large crowds always breed
danger and absolute safety can never be guaranteed.
   ``There are no easy solutions. You can make recommendation after
recommendation but at the end of the day there is always a human
element,'' Sir Oliver Popplewell told The Associated Press.
``Balancing the problem of hooliganism with the problems of safety
and from other sources is a very complex matter.''
   England's football association gave the go-ahead Monday for the
cup competition to continue. But the Liverpool team decided today
to postpone for one week a decision on whether to participate any
more this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
