<SECOND>PM-Britain-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0500,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Flier Killed In Air Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to CORRECT that plane had only one crewmember;
pickup 4th graf pvs `The plane...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENWICK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. attack jet on a training flight
crashed near this village in eastern England, killing the pilot and
scattering ammunition over a stretch of farmland, officials said
today.
   Authorities cordoned off the site after army officials warned of
the danger from the ammunition of the A-10 Thunderbolt II that went
down Monday about 20 miles north of the university town of
Cambridge.
   The crash killed Capt. Donald R. Roberts, 29, of Rochester,
N.Y., said a spokesman for the 3rd U.S. Air Force in Britain.
   The spokesman said earlier that a second member of the two-man
crew ejected before the crash and parachuted to safety. However,
officials later corrected that report, saying only the pilot was
aboard.
   The plane was on a routine training mission from the nearby
Bentwaters air base, said the spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The spokesman said the plane carried practice ammunition that
had a propellant charge, not an explosive charge. But he cautioned
against anyone handling the shells.
   Experts from Bentwaters, 72 miles east of London, warned
Cambridgeshire police about the danger of the scattered ammunition
and police warned the public to stay clear of the crash site.
   The British domestic news agency Press Association said the
crash brought down overhead power lines and that it was the second
A-10 crash in Cambridgeshire in 13 days and the third in five
months.
   The Thunderbolt II is a ``tank-buster'' specializing in
low-level ground support maneuvers. It was built to carry
air-to-surface missiles and a 30mm cannon.
