<FIRST>r i PM-Austria-HitlerAnniversary     04-18 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Hitler Anniversary,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Consider Blocking Off Hitler House On Hitler's Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAUNAU, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities may block off the house
where Adolf Hitler was born on the 100th anniversary of the Nazi
dictator's birth, an official said today.
   ``There is concern that the house may be the target of
attacks,''said a local official speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said authorities were considering closing Salzburger Vorstadt
street, where the house is located, on Thursday, the anniversary of
Hitler's birth. He said the street also may be closed Wednesday.
   Hitler lived there only in the first three years of his life,
but the house has been the subject of controversy and occasionally
the target of neo-Nazi activities. It is privately owned, leased by
the government and now houses a day nursery.
   Newspapers reported authorities received threats and word that
ultra-rightist groups were planning to meet in Braunau on Thursday.
   ``We cannot take any risks. The terror threats must be taken
seriously,'' Johan Gruber, a prefecture spokesman told the daily
Oberoesterreichische Nachrichten.
   The newspaper said some 300 law enforcement officers were
expected to be deployed Thursday.
   Authorities were concerned there not be a repeat of events 10
years ago on Hitler's birthday, when uniformed neo-Nazis caused
disturbances near the house, the newspaper said.
   Owners of the 20 shops nearby threatened to take legal action if
the street is closed, according to the newspaper.
</TEXT>
