<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StockbrokerShooting     04-18 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stockbroker Shooting,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fired Stockbroker Convicted of Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury rejected a plea of insanity and convicted a
stockbroker of murdering his former boss one day after being fired.
   Superior Court Judge John Irwin immediately sentenced
42-year-old Lonnie Gilchrist to life in prison Monday in the 1988
shooting death of George Cook.
   The jury, which began deliberations on Thursday, rejected
Gilchrist's claim that he was in the grips of a paranoid psychosis.
   One day after he was fired in 1988 for not meeting performance
levels, Gilchrist entered Cook's Merrill Lynch office and shot the
regional vice president three times with a .22-caliber pistol as
the executive sat behind his desk.
   Witnesses said that as Cook crawled toward his door crying for
help, Gilchrist shot him twice more, beat and kicked him and
yelled, ``No billionaire is going to do this to me!''
   Steven R. Lively, another Merrill Lynch employee and a former
Boston College football star, tackled Gilchrist in Cook's office
and held him until authorities arrived.
   Defense attorney Norman Zalkind argued that Gilchrist's
childhood with an abusive and alcoholic father left him feeling
persecuted and blaming prejudice for his failures. Gilchrist, who
is black, had gone to the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People to file a complaint against Merrill Lynch.
   Before the shooting, Gilchrist completed a $125,000 bond
transaction, canceled a dental appointment and told co-workers he
was going to teach Cook a lesson. Assistant District Attorney
Ronald Moynahan said Gilchrist's business-as-usual manner showed he
was in control at the time.
   ``I think it's very important that the word go out that our
criminal justice system (is) determined by jurors of our peers and
not by the psychiatrists of the world,'' Moynahan said after the
verdict.
   Gilchrist graduated from the University of Pennsylvania's
Wharton School.
   Lively, who is black, quit the firm three months after the
shooting and filed a complaint with the Massachusetts Commission
Against Discrimination accusing Merrill Lynch releasing his name to
offset bad publicity on race relations.
</TEXT>
