<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-InformationForum     04-18 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Information Forum,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Praises Greater Soviet Freedom at Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today praised
greater freedom of expression in the Soviet Union and defended her
ban on broadcast interviews with members of the Irish Republican
Army.
   Opening a 35-nation conference on improving the exchange of
information between the East and West, Mrs. Thatcher also
reiterated that Britain will not bow to Moslem demands to ban
Salman Rusdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses.'' Many Moslems consider
the book blasphemous.
   Mrs. Thatcher said the novel ``broke none of our laws.''
   ``There must never be an area where the government has
discretion (to censor); it must always act within the law,'' she
said.
   The meeting of government officials, journalists and other
delegates from Eastern and Western Europe, the United States and
Canada, follows an East-West Conference on Security and Cooperation
in Europe held in January.
   The Vienna conference ended with participants committing to
facilitate news reporting and improve working conditions for
journalists. The London meeting is aimed partly at assessing
whether countries have lived up to their promises.
   Western nations are expected to use the month-long conference,
known as the Information Forum, to test the scope of Soviet
glasnost, or openness.
   Mrs. Thatcher said major changes in the Soviet Union and East
bloc countries now allow ``greater freedom to express views and
opinions that are not necessarily those of governments and ruling
parties.''
   But she said there was still distance to go.
   ``There will only be a common European home if the occupants can
mingle and talk freely,'' Mrs. Thatcher said, referring to Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev's comment that the West should view the
Soviets as part of Europe.
   There was speculation that Eastern bloc countries will react to
Western prodding on freedom of expression and human rights with
jibes that Mrs. Thatcher has curbed the media.
   As well as the IRA ban, imposed last year, critics point to her
attempts to ban the publication of ``Spycatcher,'' the memoirs of a
retired intelligence agent, and to what they regard as inadequate
proposals for the reform of Britain's secrecy laws.
   ``I make no apology for measures taken to prevent men of
violence using television and radio to spread fear and create an
illusion of authority,'' Mrs. Thatcher said. ``Terrorists have no
respect for freedom. They exploit freedom only to undermine it,''
she said.
</TEXT>
