<FIRST>r a PM-Principals'Lawsuit     04-18 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Principals' Lawsuit,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principals Challenge School Reform Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The principals' union has gone to court to
challenge a reform plan that would strip them of tenure and give
parents more of a say over schools.
   ``Principals should be the (chief executive officer) of their
schools rather than a political person that works at the whim of
the council,'' said Bruce Berndt, president of the Chicago
Principals Association.
   ``Tenure, we feel, is a necessary component for principals to
take them out of the political arena.''
   The association, which represents 450 of the district's 505
principals, some of whom work at more than one school, filed suit
Monday in state court.
   The lawsuit questions the constitutionality of the election
process for parent-controlled local school councils at each of
Chicago's 595 public schools and challenges a provision that strips
principals of tenure.
   Donald Moore, executive director of Designs for Change, an
education advocacy agency that helped write the law, said that if
successful, the lawsuit would cut the heart out of school reform in
the 410,000-student system.
   ``We always felt that two of the most vital elements of the bill
were to give parents a majority voice in the education of their
children and to eliminate principal tenure so that principals could
be held accountable for their performance,'' said Moore.
   Under the reform law, to take effect next month, parent-majority
councils would be elected by mid-October at each school.
   Parents would elect parents, teachers would choose teachers and
the community would elect its representatives _ a process the
lawsuit called unconstitutional.
   The councils, to be composed of six parents, two community
leaders and a principal, would evaluate principals and recommend
dismissing unsatisfactory ones.
   Under the law, principals also would be placed on four-year
performance contracts.
</TEXT>
