<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four masked assailants today killed a
Palestinian woman in the occupied West Bank, claiming she
collaborated with Israel, Arab reports said. Fifteen Palestinians
were reported wounded in clashes with soldiers.
   The West Bank and the occupied Gaza Strip were virtually shut
down by a general strike called to protest the army's alleged use
of confiscated Arab-owned cars to make surprise raids on
Palestinian villages.
   The Israeli newspapers Maariv and Al-Hamishmar reported the army
was investigating slogans found on walls in the Gaza Strip in
recent days calling on Arabs to ``gather firearms'' for renewed
revolt against Israel.
   Arab reporters said the graffiti called only for keeping up the
``armed struggle,'' a standard slogan of the 16-month Palestinian
uprising. The Palestinians' main weapons have been stones and
firebombs, and the use of guns would mean greater violence.
   The wounding of 15 Palestinians today came during at least four
separate clashes between Israeli troops and stone-throwing
protesters in the Gaza Strip, Arab reports said. The army said it
was checking the reports.
   A 14-year-old Arab boy also was wounded just outside Jerusalem
when an Israeli truck driver fired on stone-throwing youths, Israel
radio said. The youth was hospitalized in critical condition.
   The army said the boy apparently was shot by a garbage truck
driver after the vehicle was stoned in Al Azariye village, or
biblical Bethany.
   On Monday, six Arabs died, including two teen-agers shot by
soldiers and a man and a woman killed in a family feud in Gaza City
that some reports said was sparked by allegations of collaboration
with Israel.
   The army today denied that soldiers had killed one of the
victims, a 13-year-old girl from Dheishe refugee camp, which was
the scene of one of Monday's worst clashes.
   ``A complete investigation has shown that there is no connection
between any army action and the girl's death,'' the army
spokeswoman said.
   The spokeswoman, who is not identified under military
regulations, refused to elaborate on other possible causes of the
girl's death and said the girl's family took her body for burial.
   The army also said the circumstances were unclear in the Gaza
City deaths and in the stabbing death this morning of a 43-year-old
woman in the West Bank city of Nablus.
   Nadira Boulus reportedly was stabbed by four attackers masked
with Arab headdresses who broke into her home. Arab reports said
the attackers' supporters ringed the woman's house during the
stabbing.
   Ms. Boulus' death raised the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising o 439. Eighteen Israelis also have died in the revolt.
   Arab and Israeli reports said the circumstances of the deaths in
Gaza City of Kamal Khalil Ayad, 30, and Rifkah Abdel Hamid Ayad,
52, were unclear. Some reports said a family feud erupted over
accusations of collaboration with Israel.
   Both the Gaza City victims suffered multiple bullet wounds to
the head and chest. The relationship between them was not known.
   Arab reports said two other members of the family, a 3-year-old
girl and a 25-year-old man, also were shot. The army said two
people were killed and three wounded in the incident.
   During the Palestinian uprising, more than 65 of the
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs on suspicion of
helping Israel.
