<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FairnessDoctrine     04-18 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairness Doctrine,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs Broadcast Requirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee today approved a new
attempt to write into law a fairness doctrine that would require
broadcasters to air opposing sides of controversial issues.
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee, on a
voice vote, sent the measure on to the full Senate. A companion
measure is awaiting floor action in the House.
   Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., voted against the bill, and
Committee Chairman Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., noted that Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore., also opposed the bill, although he was not
present for today's vote.
   Critics such as Packwood contend that the fairness doctrine,
which was promulgated in the 1940s on the principle that radio and
television spectrum was scare, is outdated is this era of cable TV,
satellites and video cassette recorders.
   Broadcasters claim the doctrine exerts a ``chilling effect'' on
discussions of controversial issues and is an unconstitutional
infringement on their First Amendment rights.
   But the bill's primary sponsor, Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii,
said the need for such legislation is greater than ever. He said
there is evidence broadcasters have been devoting less time to
controversial issues since the Federal Communications Commission
repealed its fairness doctrine in 1987.
   A virtually identical measure passed Congress in 1987 but was
vetoed by then-President Reagan, who said it violated the First
Amendment.
   The Justice Department told Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman
of the House Energy and Commerce Committee, that it was
recommending that President Bush veto the new bill if it passes
Congress.
</TEXT>
