<DOCNO> AP890418-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Classified     04-18 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Classified,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Backs Out of Deciding Validity of Congressional Attempt on
Classified Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today backed out of deciding
the validity of a 1987 attempt by Congress to limit the president's
authority to withhold classified information from it.
   In an unsigned opinion, the justices sent the case back to a
federal trial judge for further study.
   The high court cited several changed circumstances, including
the possibility that the dispute may have become moot.
   At issue was a national security directive adopted by President
Ronald Reagan in 1983 requiring federal officials, before they are
allowed access to classified documents, to sign an agreement that
they will never disclose the information.
   The directive also established a standard form for officials to
sign, promising they never will divulge classified or
``classifiable'' information without written permission from proper
executive-branch authorities.
   Federal employee unions and some members of Congress bridled at
the directive, particularly the use of the word ``classifiable.''
   They said the presidential order restricted free-speech rights
of federal employees and ``allows after-the-fact classification of
information in order to punish whistleblowers for making
disclosures that embarrass their superiors.''
   Members of Congress said the directive would bar those federal
employees who sign from revealing information to Congress that it
is entitled to receive.
   Congress then enacted a spending bill aimed at blocking the
executive branch from withholding classifiable information or from
impeding congressional access to such material.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch struck down the legislation
last year as unconstitutional.
   The American Foreign Service Association, representing members
of the nation's diplomatic corps, joined with senators and House
members from both political parties in appealing directly to the
Supreme Court.
   But the cout today sent the case back to Gasch, noting that the
term ``classifiable'' has been given a new, narrower interpretation
by executive-branch officials.
   The case is American Foreign Service Association vs. Garfinkel,
87-2127.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru   04-18 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0573,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa and Jaruzelski Meet for First Time Since 1981</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with Jarulzelski comment;
picks up 4th pvs: The deliberately... ^By JOHN DANIZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and
Communist Party chief Wojciech Jaruzelski met today for the first
time in more than seven years, a day after the trade union was
legalized.
   ``I feel satisfaction. We have come a very difficult and long
way,'' Gen. Jaruzelski told reporters after the meeting.
   He said that ``reconciliation is a process, not an act,'' and
cited the broad agreement on political and economic reform reached
between communist authorities and the opposition.
   ``Today we only put another seal, in a way, on that accord,'' he
said.
   Walesa left the meeting without talking to reporters.
   Walesa and Jaruzelski began the meeting with a handshake inside
a reception room of the parliament building near downtown Warsaw,
said an official photographer who was present at the meeting. He
requested anonymity.
   The two men then sat on a sofa and had a long conversation
during the first part of the one-hour reception, reported
Solidarity activist Zbigniew Bujak, who was among the approximately
30 people present.
   The deliberately low-profile meeting was requested by the
government, according to an opposition source who demanded
anonymity.
   Jaruzelski issued the martial law decree of Dec. 13, 1981, that
resulted in the imprisonment of Walesa and thousands of other
Solidarity activists and the outlawing of the East bloc's first
independent trade union.
   But now Jaruzelski has led his reluctant party to reinstate
Solidarity, which he hopes will help pull Poland out of its
economic crisis.
   ``A new chapter is starting in the history of Poland, and it
seems that both of the politicians are characterized with a great
sense of timing and a capacity to respond to the challenges of the
time,'' said deputy government spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski.
   Walesa and Jaruzelski last met Nov. 4, 1981, about a month
before Jaruzelski imposed martial law and had Walesa jailed.
   Walesa attended today's meeting as a member of the Arbitration
Commission, which was appointed to oversee implementation of the
economic and political accords between the Solidarity-led
opposition and the government.
   The commission included 13 opposition delegates, many of whom
also had been jailed at Jaruzelski's order. In addition to
Jaruzelski and Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, the leaders
of Poland's two communist-allied political parties also were
present at the meeting.
   Solidarity was officially legalized Monday by three-judge panel
in a Warsaw provincial court, in the same room where the union had
its original charter approved in November 1980.
   Solidarity was suppressed after 16 months with the imposition of
martial law. The union movement was outlawed the following year.
   Party and government officials admit that by legalizing
Solidarity they hope to encourage the West to provide economic help
to Poland, which is burdened by a $39 billion foreign debt.
   In the April 5 accords, the government also agreed to create the
first freely elected legislative chamber _ a Senate that would have
veto power over the existing unicameral parliament, the Sejm.
   On Monday, Walesa had breakfast with Foreign Minister Roland
Dumas of France and said Poland must focus on solving its economic
crisis now that his union is legal.
   ``We have achieved half a victory for the moment. Now it's a
question of seeing if we can take advantage of all the
possiblities,'' Walesa told Dumas.
   Walesa praised President Bush on Monday for announcing an aid
package for Poland's economy. ``Bush is a great man and he knows
the Polish situation very well,'' he said.
   Walesa on Monday also attended a meeting of an opposition
committee supervising selection of independent candidates for the
June parliamentary elections, which will be the first in Poland
open to the opposition since 1947.
   The 1947 voting, which allowed communists to take unchallenged
power, was criticized in the West as tainted. This year's voting is
planned to remove the party's full monopoly on power, but still
leaves it in a dominant position.
   Solidarity members, who predict the union will grow to 5 million
to 7 million members, immediately face the twin tasks of organizing
the union and the election campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
