<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeCollapse     04-18 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Collapsed Bridge Was Listed In Poor Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLIVER SPRINGS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Urgent repairs were recommended
twice since 1985 but never carried out on a bridge that collapsed
over the weekend, killing a teen-ager and injuring two others,
inspection records show.
   The bridge was listed in ``critical'' condition after
inspections in 1985 and 1987, meaning it ``should be closed until
the indicated repair is completed.''
   State inspectors had found rotting guardrails and soil erosion,
and the records show that no repairs were made. The inspectors also
noted that a fire apparently had been set on some of the bridge's
wood a few years ago.
   The three victims from the Saturday night accident were riding
in a pickup truck that plunged 30 feet onto railroad tracks below.
   Local officials said the truck may have driven off the span,
knocked out a support on the way down and caused the bridge to
collapse.
   The state had no authority to enforce repairs on the span
because until last year it was owned by CSX Transportation, said
Gwen Hopkins, spokeswoman for the state Transportation Department.
CSX sold the bridge to Anderson County last year, said Lloyd Lewis,
a company spokesman in Jacksonville, Fla.
   Asked why the railroad had not addressed the problems cited in
the inspections, Lewis responded: ``Whatever did not happen three
years ago doesn't matter. We're not responsible anymore.''
   The county applied earlier for money to replace the structure,
said county attorney David Stuart. ``There was no doubt that it was
time to be replaced,'' he said.
   Glen Smith, 44, said his brother died in 1981 when his car hit
the bridge rail and went over the side. The accident led to a
petition drive to build a new bridge, he said.
   Saturday's accident was the second involving a Tennessee bridge
failure in two weeks. Inspection reports on both structures warned
earlier of problems.
   Eight people died April 1 in the collapse of a bridge over the
Hatchie River 45 miles north of Memphis. Investigators said flood
waters had weakened the supports of that bridge.
</TEXT>
