<FIRST>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     04-18 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,270</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Tuesday by the Supreme Court.
   
   ANTITRUST
   
   The court, in a major victory for consumers, upheld state laws
that allow those indirectly affected by illegal price-fixing to sue
for monetary damages.
   By a 7-0 vote,the court reinstated efforts by four states _
California, Minnesota, Alabama and Arizona _ to participate in a
multimillion-dollar settlement of a nationwide conspiracy to fix
cement prices.
   The case is California vs. ARC America Corp., 87-1862.
   
   KAL CRASH
   
   The court expanded airlines' protection against big damages,
limiting the financial penalties that may be imposed against Korean
Air Lines for a 1983 disaster in which 269 people died when a KAL
passenger jet was shot down over Soviet airspace.
   By a 9-0 vote, the justices said the airline will not have to
pay more than $75,000 in damages for each person who died in the
disaster.
   The case is Chan vs. Korean Air Lines, 87-1055.
   
   CLASSIFIED INFORMATION
   
   The court backed out of deciding the validity of a 1987 attempt
by Congress to limit the president's authority to withhold
classified information from it.
   In an unsigned opinion, the justices sent the case back to a
federal trial judge for further study.
   At issue was a national security directive adopted by President
Ronald Reagan in 1983 requiring federal officials, before they are
allowed access to classified documents, to sign an agreement they
will never disclose the information.
   The case is American Foreign Service Association vs. Garfinkel,
87-2127.
   
   VACATION PAY
   
   The court ruled unanimously that states may prosecute employers
for withholding accrued vacation pay owed fired workers.
   The court, in a case from Massachusetts, said the federal
Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) does not pre-empt
criminal prosecution in such cases.
   The case is Massachusetts vs. Morash, 88-32.
</TEXT>
