<FIRST>r a PM-GreekLibel     04-18 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greek Libel,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Takes Time Magazine to Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time magazine says it will vigorously fight a
libel suit filed by Greek Premier Andreas Papandreou over an
article reporting an accusation he stole millions of dollars from a
bank.
   The lawsuit was filed in London and announced here Monday by
Papandreou attorney Leonard Boudin, who said the premier is seeking
as-yet unspecified damages.
   The lawsuit cites the cover story in Time's international
edition March 13. A similar article in the U.S. edition was not on
the cover.
   The articles quoted former Greek bank president George Koskotas,
who is jailed in Massachusetts, as saying he passed millions from
the Bank of Crete to Papandreou and other figures in the premier's
Socialist government.
   Papandreou, premier since 1981, has denied the accusation.
   Boudin said that in using Koskotas, Time was relying on ``a man
whose character and reputation for truth is questioned by Time
itself in the article.''
   Time said that it tried repeatedly to get Papandreou's response
and that it noted in the article earlier denials made by the prime
minister.
   ``Time magazine will take whatever steps are necessary to fight
the allegations of this lawsuit and defend its right to report
news,'' the magazine said in a statement.
   Boudin said the lawsuit was filed in England because the story
was more damaging abroad and because it is easier for a public
figure to make a case under English libel law than under American.
   Since last fall, allegations of financial wrongdoing at the Bank
of Crete have rocked the Papandreou government, which is up for
re-election in June.
   The scandal and the 70-year premier's open affair with a
34-year-old former airline stewardess have hurt him with voters.
</TEXT>
