<FIRST>r a PM-Volkswagen-Blacks     04-18 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Volkswagen-Blacks,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement Reached In Racial Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volkswagen of America Inc. has agreed to pay
$670,000 and the United Auto Workers $48,000 so settle claims that
they discriminated against black employees, a spokesman for the
automaker said today.
   About 800 blacks could share the money under the settlement,
which is subject to approval by U.S. District Judge Gustave
Diamond, who is presiding over the 6-year-old case. He scheduled a
June 13 hearing on the settlement.
   ``This is not an admission of guilt on VW's part or the UAW's
part,'' said VW spokesman Tom McDonald in Troy, Mich.
   He said the defendants settled to avoid the costs of further
litigation and to ``make sure that the reputation of Volkswagen
remains as high as it was when we were making cars in Westmoreland
County.'' Volkswagen closed its lone U.S. assembly plant last year,
citing declining sales of its Golf and Jetta models.
   Individual payments would range from $70,000 to a supervisor who
said he was harassed on the job to $200 for hourly workers who were
fired before their 90-day probations expired.
   Any money not claimed by individuals will be used to establish a
scholarship fund for minority students.
   The plaintiffs had sought $70 million when they filed the
class-action suit in 1983.
</TEXT>
