<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Musical 1stLd-Writethru   04-18 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Musical, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0571,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Lloyd Webber Musical Opening to Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `The cast...' with one graf to CORRECT Ball's
role; picks up 14th: Kathleen Rowe...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Lloyd Webber's new musical ``Aspects of
Love'' received mixed reviews today following weeks of speculation
in the British press that the Tony Award-winning composer was
losing his Midas touch.
   The show is his first musical since the Broadway smash hit ``The
Phantom of the Opera,'' which swept the Tony Awards last season.
The new show, made up of songs without spoken dialogue, signals a
newfound emphasis on emotion over spectacle from the man who
brought felines and trains to melodic life in ``Cats'' and
``Starlight Express.''
   Charles Osborne in The Daily Telegraph said the show, which
opened Monday at the Prince of Wales Theater, was ``certainly
Andrew Lloyd Webber's best so far.''
   However, Milton Shulman in The Standard found the show ``a
mannered, rather precious operetta ... singularly lacking in real
passion.''
   At a cost of $3.4 million, the production sold advance tickets
worth $8.5 million. It is sold out through 1989.
   The musical, set in France and based on a 1955 novel by David
Garnett, relates the tangled romantic intrigue among three
generations of a family and their entourage. Their ``aspects of
love'' include romance between cousins and lesbianism.
   The black-tie opening came five days after the show's originally
scheduled debut.
   The premiere was delayed by problems with scenery and length. In
addition, James Bond actor Roger Moore, who was to play aging
dilettante George Dillingham, left the show during rehearsals.
Moore said he felt he was not up to singing the part.
   The show marks director Trevor Nunn's first musical since his
production of ``Chess'' bombed on Broadway last year.
   Jack Tinker in The Daily Mail applauded Lloyd Webber's daring.
``This is uncharted territory on so many fronts,'' he wrote. But he
added that he wondered ``whether the public are prepared for such a
show of courage or not.''
   Michael Billington in The Guardian praised the show for
exploring ``the human heart rather than the possibilities of
high-tech scenery.'' But he called it ``a beguiling, fitfully
pleasing musical, rather than a perfect one.''
   Irving Wardle in The Times called it ``a well-crafted show,''
but he faulted the music as ``timid and uninteresting.''
   The cast includes Kevin Colson, who inherited Moore's role, as
the wealthy painter, George, and Michael Ball as his nephew, Alex.
Both men are romantically linked to a French actress, Rose,
performed by American Ann Crumb.
   Kathleen Rowe McAllen, another American, plays George's Italian
mistress, Giulietta. Diana Morrison is George's young daughter,
Jenny, who becomes ensnared by the dangerous liaisons around her.
   The show's most heavily plugged song, ``Love Changes
Everything,'' has received extensive airplay on British radio. It
is sung by Ball, who is being hyped as the London theater's new
teen hearthrob.
   ``Aspects of Love'' helps resuscitate a genre, the English
musical, which received a double blow last year with the
back-to-back Broadway failures of ``Chess'' and ``Carrie.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Jakes     04-18 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Jakes,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Leader Says No Rehabilitation of Dubcek</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Czechoslovakia's Communist Party
said Tuesday there will be no rehabiliation of Alexander Dubcek,
who led the 1968 ``Prague Spring'' liberalization campaign that was
crushed by Soviet tanks.
   ``We don't intend any political rehabiliation or return of
Alexander Dubcek to political activity,'' Czechoslovak leader Milos
Jakes told reporters. ``No one would accept that except for a few
people.
   The return of Dubcek might be misunderstood and could ``lead to
instability,'' he said.
   Jakes held a news conference after meeting with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev on a working visit to the Soviet Union.
   The Czechoslovak Communist Party lags behind parties in Hungary
and Poland in adopting reforms modeled on Gorbachev's restructuring
campaign, but Jakes said it was reforming at its own pace.
   ``Czechoslovakia is not a conservative force on the map of the
world,'' he said.
   ``We have similar tasks to the Soviet Communist Party. Certainly
we take into account our internal conditions in Czechoslovakia when
we determine the rate and scope of change,'' he said. ``We also
take into account the experience of the Soviet Union. This is very
important to us.''
   Parts of Gorbachev's reform effort are similar to changes
initiated by Dubcek in 1968. But the Czechoslovak leadership
installed after Dubcek was ousted in April 1969 has resisted
political change.
   A series of protests demanding political and economic reforms
rocked the Czechoslovak capital of Prague this year. In a
much-publicized trial, dissident playright Vaclav Havel was
convicted of incitement and obstructing police and sentenced to
jail.
   Dubcek was allowed to travel to Italy in November, his first
trip abroad in 18 years, but in March he was denied permission to
attend the congress of the Italian Communist Party.
   The Czechoslovak party newspaper Rude Pravo charged in March
that recent interviews Dubcek has given to Western journalists were
used to give ``a semblance of authenticity'' to ``slanders'' of the
current leadership.
   Jakes said the Czechoslovak party under Dubcek set a correct
course for reforming the country's political and economic
structure, but it got out of control.
   ``The leadership of that time was not able to guide the country
along the right road,'' Jakes said. ``We witnesses the weakening of
socialism and he violation of traditions that had existed since
1948,'' the year communists took power.
   Dubcek today ``is a private citizen and he speaks his own
mind,'' Jakes said.
   Noting that Dubcek's sons have professional careers and that the
former Czechoslovak leader is living on a pension, Jakes added, ``I
don't think he has grounds to complain.''
   Jakes said the party was willing to give more power to smaller
parties that are allied with it, but does not plan to allow the
creating of opposition parties, as Hungarian communists have
pledged.
   Reforms in Czechoslovakia, as well as in the Soviet Union where
a political opposition is not permitted, must be carried out by the
Communist Party, he said. ``If it is not headed by the party the
process will not lead to strengthening of socialism,'' Jakes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
