<FIRST>r w AM-Archives-Soviet     04-18 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Archives-Soviet,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Records of Consulates Will Be Turned Over to Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Records of Imperial Russian consulates in the
United States and Canada in the late 19th and early 20th centuries,
which have been in U.S. custody for 55 years, will be turned over
to the Soviet Union at a ceremony in Moscow Wednesday.
   Don W. Wilson, archivist of the United States, will deliver to
Soviet authorities the first boxes of the original files of the
consulates, the National Archives announced Tuesday.
   The boxes contain such items as passport application forms of
the Tsarist period, dated 1918 and containing a blank for ``social
rank,'' and a letter from Count Ilya Tolstoy inquiring about his
brother, the novelist Leo Tolstoy.
   The remainder of the more than 400 boxes will be returned to the
Soviet Union in the course of the year, the archival agency said.
The papers have all been microfilmed, and the copies will be
available to researchers here.
   The documents, created from about 1862 to 1922, are from files
of Soviet consulates in New York, Chicago, San Francisco, Honolulu,
Philadelphia, Portland, Ore., and Seattle, and in Montreal and
Vancouver, British Columbia.
   Until 1933, the records were stored in the Russian Embassy in
Washington. At that time the Russian financial attache, who was
custodian of the records, asked the U.S. government to take
custody. They were moved to a warehouse under the auspices of the
State Department and were occasionally consulted by officials of
the Soviet Embassy, the announcement by the archives said.
   In 1947, they were transferred to the National Archives for
safekeeping.
   ``These records, which document official government activity,
should properly be held for research use in the Soviet Union,''
Wilson said in a statement issued here. ``For years the United
States has supported the efforts of the International Council on
Archives and UNESCO to see that archival materials which have
migrated from their country of origin should be returned to their
proper home.''
   Wilson is in the Soviet Union as head of the U.S.-U.S.S.R.
Commission on Archival Cooperation for negotiations on joint
archival projects including an agreement on cooperation in
genealogical research.
   The announcement said Fedor M. Vaganov, chief of the main
archival administration of the U.S.S.R. Council of Ministers and
Soviet head of the commission, would represent the Soviet Union at
the presentation ceremony.
   It said the records related, among other things, to property
claims and activities of Russian nationals in the United States and
Canada, principally from 1900 to 1917. Others deal with
Russian-American trade, Russian church affairs and consular routine.
</TEXT>
