<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Brecher     04-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Brecher,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Edward M. Brecher, Writer on Scientific Subjects, Dead at Age 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORNWALL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward M. Brecher, a writer who once
argued in favor of the right to end one's life at a time and in a
manner of one's own choosing, has died in what was ruled a suicide.
He was 77.
   Brecher, who was found dead at home Saturday, wrote ``Opting for
Suicide'' for The New York Times Magazine in 1979 after he had
contracted cancer of the colon the previous year.
   He was the author of numerous books and articles on medical,
scientific and social subjects.
   A son, Jeremy, said Monday that Brecher left one note for family
and friends and another for the police saying he felt the time had
come for him to end his life.
   Dr. Gurd Gudernatch, an assistant state medical examiner, said
today that Brecher died by asphyxiation and his death has been
ruled a suicide.
   For much of his long writing career, Brecher collaborated on
books and articles with his wife, Ruth Ernestine Cook Brecher, who
died in 1966. They received the Albert Lasker Award for medical
journalism in 1963.
   The couple wrote ``An Analysis of Human Sexual Response,'' a
1966 version for the general public of Masters and Johnson's
``Human Sexual Response.''
   Among his later works were ``The Sex Researchers,'' ``Licit and
Illicit Drugs'' and ``Love, Sex and Aging.''
   Brecher was born in Minneapolis and graduated from Swarthmore
College. He received a master's degree from the University of
Minnesota.
   In 1947, he became an associate editor of Consumer Reports and
four years later he joined the U.N. Technical Assistance
Administration as an editor. He worked mainly as a free-lance
writer since 1952.
   Survivors include two other sons and four grandchildren.
</TEXT>
