<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Solzhenitsyn     04-18 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Solzhenitsyn,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Gulag Archipelago' to be Published in Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hungarian publishing company has
announced plans to release ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' Alexander
Solzhenitsyn's monumental history of Soviet labor camps, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The newspaper Esti Hirlap said the publishers, Szabad Ter, would
publish the book soon, but did not say when.
   A French publishing firm that is in charge of printing the
exiled Russian writer's works in Paris has given the Budapest
publishers a three-month option to decide whether they show an
interest in the book, Esti Hirlap said.
   ``The Gulag Archipelago'' posed a fundamental challenge to
Soviet authority. In it, Solzhenitsyn argued that Stalin's terror
was no aberration, but was rooted in Lenin's concept of total rule
by the Communist Party. In January 1974, the book was denounced as
``slanderous'' and the author as a ``renegade'' in Pravda, the
party's official newspaper.
   The French firm also signed a contract with Hungarian publishers
on two other books by Solzhenitsyn, ``Cancer Ward'' and ``The First
Circle.'' The books circulated in the Soviet Union as ``samizdat,''
self-published manuscripts that were passed from hand to hand.
   Szabad Ter has recently published two books about Imre Nagy, the
premier during the Hungarian uprising in 1956.
</TEXT>
