<FIRST>u a PM-DepartmentStoreBomb 2ndLd-Writethru a0563 04-18 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Department Store Bomb, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0563,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb In K mart Store Seriously Injures Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with two sted four men being sought, details
on bomb, former employees to be questioned; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, ``The
store ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NA1, NA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN HUDDLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today said they were looking for two
men who left a department store seemingly unconcerned moments after
a pipe bomb hidden in a toothpaste container maimed a 5-year-old
girl.
   The bomb apparently exploded in Erin Bower's hand after she took
the pump-type container from a shelf at a K mart store Monday
night, investigators said today.
   The explosion blew off four fingers and half her left palm and
injured an eye and her abdomen, officials said. Methodist Hospital
spokesman David Richards said her doctor is ``cautiously optimistic
of partial vision in that eye.''
   None of the 50 other people in the store was seriously hurt.
   Charles A. Petersen of the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms, said the bomb apparently was electrically fired. ``It
was a little more sophisticated than the average pipe bomb. It took
some knowledge to construct it,'' he said.
   Police said they have no suspects and no motive in the bombing
but were searching for two men seen leaving the store when the
explosion occurred.
   Detective Sgt. Mike Kouns said the men did not appear to be
concerned about the bombing, unlike other customers. Investigators
released composite sketches of two men based on descriptions from
store employees, Kouns said.
   Kouns said that police would question K mart employees who have
been fired recently but that there was no immediate reason to
believe a former worker was involved.
   The store received no warning before the explosion, which
occurred about an hour before closing, said Sheriff Joseph G.
McAtee.
   ``The store looks like everybody dropped whatever they were
looking at,'' said Scott Minier, a Sheriff's Department spokesman.
``There's blood on the tile. The trash bag area is a mess. There is
a blood and merchandise scattered all over.''
   Minier said the bomb had a pressure-sensitive release.
   ``It sounded like a pop,'' said a clerk, Judy Kiefer. ``The
first thing I heard was a child screaming. A lot of people were
saying, `Get out of here.'''
   The girl's mother, Maurine Bower, 31, suffered a minor shrapnel
injury to one of her legs and fainted. She was treated at the
hospital.
   Louis M. Profeta, a medical student at Indiana University, was
shopping when the bomb exploded.
   ``I saw the little girl, her clothes were on fire and the mother
was screaming. Both father and mother were covered in blood,''
Profeta said. ``We rendered first aid and got the father and mother
away, then got her stabilized.''
   The father, Kevin Bower, 31, was holding his youngest daughter,
Megan, 1, at the time of the explosion.
   The severed portion of Erin's hand was packed in ice and taken
to the hospital, but officials said it could not be reattached.
   ``She still has her thumb and about half of the palm of her
hand,'' said Barbara McGraw, a hospital spokeswoman.
   Authorities brought in dogs to sniff out more explosives. None
was found.
   Other K mart stores in the Indianapolis area planned to take
precautions as a result of the bombing, Minier said.
   Agents of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms are
aiding the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FSX     04-18 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FSX,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aerospace Workers' Union Representative Attacks Proposed Plane Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed FSX fighter plane deal with Japan
will cost America jobs and might damage national security, a
representative of the aerospace workers' union told Congress on
Tuesday.
   ``We know the deal does not serve our members' interests, does
not serve the economic interests of their communities and we are
unconvinced that it serves our national security interest,'' said
William Holayter, legislative director of the International
Assocation of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
   Holayter told the House Banking subcommittee on economic
stabilization that the proposed deal for Japan to build its own
version of the F-16 fighter would jeopardize the jobs of 10,000
union members employed on production lines by General Dynamics in
Fort Worth, Texas.
   The Bush administration is reviewing a memorandum of
understanding signed with Japan in the final months of the Reagan
administration under which General Dynamics, based in St. Louis,
would develop with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries an advanced
version of the F-16, for deployment in the 1990s.
   Critics say the deal is a $7 billion giveaway of U.S. technology
that will help Japan develop its own aircraft manufacturing
capacity, an industry in which the United States retains the lead.
   However, an independent analyst told the subcommittee that the
FSX deal would benefit the United States as much as it would Japan.
   ``I cannot see how the FSX project, with its specialized fighter
engine, will provide Japan with some technology to break through
the commercial jet engine market, technology they do not already
possess in a form more germane to the commercial market,'' said
George Berke, a former fighter pilot who now works as a defense
analyst and consultant in Washington.
   Japan has been assembling and manufacturing components for
advanced U.S. aircraft since the Korean War in the early 1950s,
said Berke, and that has not caused the United States to lose
either jobs or its lead in the field.
   ``More jobs will be lost if we rebuff the Japanese than we can
hope to gain by insisting on an off-the-shelf buy,'' he said.
   William R. Hawkins, an analyst for the U.S. Business and
Industrial Council, and William G. Phillips, president of the
National Council for Industrial Defense, a lobbying group, opposed
the proposed deal.
   Hawkins urged Japan to buy U.S.-made F-15 or F-18 fighters to
replace its own aging fleet of F-1 fighters, and said Tokyo sought
the FSX deal because it ``wants to expand its aerospace industry
and bring its technological capabilities up to the first rank.''
   Phillips, whose group has campaigned against what he called the
erosion of America's industrial base, applauded ``President Bush
for his willingness to carefully review the intricate details of
the deal and his insistence on changes in the basic documents.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
