<FIRST>r a PM-Frat-Drugs     04-18 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frat-Drugs,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Wanted to Seize Frat House After Cocaine Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors wanted to seize a
University of New Hampshire fraternity house after two members were
arrested for selling cocaine, but school officials opposed the
action, according to a report published today.
   Kappa Sigma's president and a fraternity brother were charged in
1988 with selling cocaine to undercover police inside the house,
and police favored seizing it under federal drug laws, The Union
Leader of Manchester reported.
   ``Durham police presented the case to the U.S. attorney's
office, and we were eager to adopt the case. We believed it was
meritorious and had decided to do it, provided we got the
cooperation of the university,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney David
Vicinanzo told The Union Leader.
   The newspaper said Vicinanzo refused to discuss a meeting he had
with university officials. He said only, ``We didn't do the
forfeiture.''
   Vicinanzo did not immediately return a phone call this morning.
   Gregg Sanborn, dean of student affairs, told the newspaper,
``Given the specific information relating to this case, we did not
feel (the house) was subject to forfeiture.''
   Federal drug forfeiture laws allow prosecutors to seize homes,
cars, boats and other property used for drug trafficking.
   Both fraternity members pleaded guilty to drug charges. One
served 80 days in jail; the other was sentenced to a year, the
newspaper said.
   Sanborn said both students withdrew from the university and
would be subject to university discipline if they sought
readmission.
</TEXT>
