<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseReadiness     04-18 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Readiness,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commanders Say Readiness Should Take Priority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Readiness of U.S. military forces should take
priority over modernization and force size in this time of tight
Pentagon budgets, U.S. commanders said Tuesday.
   ``Readiness is pre-eminent,'' Gen. Duane H. Cassidy,
commander-in-chief of the U.S. Transportation Command, told the
Senate Armed Services Committee. ``Readiness will affect our people
first. Most important it will make them see that they can't do
their job in a hollow force.''
   Cassidy joined Gen. Colin L. Powell, commander-in-chief of the
Forces Command, and Gen. Thomas C. Richards, deputy
commander-in-chief of the U.S. European Command, in an appearance
before the committee.
   Powell, who was national security adviser in the Reagan
administration, and Richards stressed that readiness must take
priority over modernization of aircraft, tanks, ships and other
systems and the size of U.S. forces.
   ``When the squeeze finally comes and you can't do it all, then I
would vote in an instant for a smaller but ready force,'' Powell
told the committee.
   Richards, who said he spoke for NATO commander Gen. John Galvin,
said ``the readiness of our force must come first. If we have to
take any cuts, then modernization and force structure are both
areas we must go to before we look to readiness of the forces.''
   President Bush and congressional budget negotiators announced
last Friday an agreement to cut $10 billion from the fiscal 1990
defense budget instead of the previously expected $6.3 billion.
   Then-President Reagan had proposed a budget authority of $305.6
billion for fiscal 1990, which opens Oct. 1, but Bush and
congressional officials agreed on authority of $295.6 billion.
   In his testimony, Powell emphasized that the Pentagon needs some
indication of the type of defense the nation envisions.
   The one thing the Defense Department ``needs more than anything
else is a clear sign what the American people and Congress will
support in the future,'' the general said. ``What's killing us is
the lack of stability.''
</TEXT>
