<FIRST>r i AM-Hitler-House     04-18 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hitler-House,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities May Block Off Hitler's House on Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAUNAU, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities may block off the house
where Adolf Hitler first lived to avoid protests and possible
attacks on Thursday, the 100th anniversary of the Nazi dictator's
birth, officials said Tuesday.
   ``We cannot take any risks,'' Johan Gruber, a spokesman for the
district prefecture, told the daily newspaper Oberoesterreichische
Nachrichten.
   Salzburger Vorstadt street, where the house is located, may be
closed on Thursday, the anniversary of his birth, a local
government spokesman said on condition of anonymity. He said the
street also might be closed on Wednesday.
   The newspaper said local officials received threats and heard
that neo-Nazis were planning to meet in Braunau on Thursday. About
300 police were expected to be deployed, the paper said.
   Hitler lived in Braunau the first three years of his life. But
the house, which is privately owned and now holds a day nursery,
has been the subject of controversy and the target of neo-Nazi
activities.
   Ten years ago on the April 20th anniversary, uniformed neo-Nazis
created disturbances near the house, something authorities hope to
avoid Thursday, the newspaper quoted officials as saying.
   On April 5, the government placed an anti-Fascist memorial stone
in front of the house. The granite is from the quarry of the
Mauthausen concentration camp, where the Nazis killed tens of
thousands of Jews. The inscription reads: ``For Peace, Freedom and
Democracy. Never Again Fascism. Millions of Dead Warn.''
   Owners of shops on the street said they would take legal action
if the area was blocked off, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
