<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     04-18 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zimbabwe Leader Announces Long-Awaited Investment Code</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Robert Mugabe announced
Tuesday a market-oriented investment code to attract domestic and
foreign capital to this southern African nation's flagging economy.
   His long-awaited announcement indicates Mugabe is moving away
from the Marxist-Leninist principles he espoused when he led the
white-ruled British colony of Rhodesia to independence as
black-governed Zimbabwe on April 18, 1980.
   It won cheers from 40,000 people celebrating the ninth
independence anniversary at a rally where trumpet fanfares and
military parades inherited from the colonial era competed with
rhythmic traditional dances and tribal drums.
   Mugabe promised to relax state controls of prices and wages and
make it easier for companies to send profits out of the country.
   The lack of an investment code has scared away foreign
speculators as the government juggled vows to nationalize with
assurances that its word should be good enough for investors who
demanded some kind of insurance.
   As a result, the biggest private foreign investments since
independence are a bubblegum factory built by Danes and a
U.S.-funded baked beans cannery.
   Nevertheless, Zimbabwe remains among black Africa's most
prosperous nations.
   Mugabe said real economic growth has occurred, but the pattern
``has been highly unsatisfactory'' and threatened to reduce living
standards.
   ``It is my government's conviction that the country should enter
a new phase of sustained growth and development so that the economy
responds more adequately to the challenges we face and aspirations
of our people,'' he said.
   The government now recognizes the need for a more rational and
market-orientated way to determine prices and incomes, Mugabe said
in a sharp turn away from previous policies that is in line with
reforms being attempted in other African states.
   Economists long have urged Mugabe to introduce economic reforms
to attract foreign capital at a time when 140,000 students leave
schools each year to compete for just 8,000 jobs.
   Mugabe, 65, made major social reforms in the country by
introducing cheap schooling and free health care. But Zimbabwe's
agriculture-oriented economy remains largely in the hands of
100,000 minority whites who favor free enterprise.
</TEXT>
