<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Passover     04-18 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Passover,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis Prepare for Passover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis cleaned their houses of bread and
other leavened foods Tuesday and made last-minute preparations for
the Passover holiday that commemorates the exodus of the ancient
Israelites from Egypt.
   The Jewish holiday begins Wednesday evening with a traditional
feast known as a Seder.
   The army organized Seder meals on its bases, but budget
constraints forced it to cancel its main Passover feast with
dignitaries, an army spokesman said.
   The 16-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip kept many soldiers on patrol, but they received holiday
care packages, the spokesman said. He said they contain ``all the
needs to make a Kosher Seder, matzo, sweet red wine, gefilte fish,
all kinds of good dishes.''
   Many Israelis headed for resorts to enjoy the holiday,
especially the Red Sea and Sea of Galilee.
   Lior Raviv, a manager at King Solomon Hotel at the Red Sea
resort of Eilat, said he expects 600 people for Passover dinner.
``We started making the matzo balls tonight and will have made
about 2,000 by tomorrow afternoon,'' he said.
   Matzo is the wafer-like, unleavened bread that the ancient
Israelites are said to have eaten during the exodus because they
had no time to leaven yeast for bread. Most Israelis today do not
eat bread or other leavened goods during the holiday.
   Travel agents reported an increase of more than 10 percent in
Israeli travel abroad for the holiday. Yigal Yardeni of Peltours,
Israel's oldest travel agent, said Israelis went away for many
reasons, including to forget the uprising.
   ``Israelis want to escape, not just this intefadeh (uprising) in
the territories, but the feeling of isolation that has accumulated
in Israel over the past 40 years. They need this holiday to clear
their heads,'' he said.
   In Jerusalem's ultra-Orthodox neighborhood of Mea Shearim, the
pungent smell of bleach hung in the air Tuesday as families carried
out traditional spring cleaning aimed at removing all bread and
other leavened products from their homes.
   Religious seminary students removed books from synagogues
Tuesday to shake out any bread crumbs that might have lodged in the
pages.
   The country's two chief rabbis symbolically sold all the state's
``hametz,'' forbidden Passover foods, to an Arab lawyer from east
Jerusaelm for about $5,500, the Chief Rabbinate said. The sale is a
traditional legal fiction reversed after the holiday.
</TEXT>
