<FIRST>r w AM-SEC-Budget     04-18 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Budget,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Say Bigger SEC Budget Needed to Prevent Financial Scandals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Banking Committee leaders on Tuesday
promised to support a bigger budget for the Securities and Exchange
Commission, raising the possibility of a savings-and-loan type
scandal if the government relaxes its vigilance over financial
markets.
   ``When we fail to provide the funds needed to staff a regulatory
agency ... then we leave too many opportunities for unscrupulous,
or simply incompetent, individuals,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., chairman of the securities subcommittee. ``I hope we can
apply the lessons from that (savings and loan) experience.''
   Dodd was supported by Sen. John Heinz of Pennsylvania, the
senior Republican on the subcommittee, and Sen. Donald W. Riegle
Jr., D-Mich., the chairman of the full committee.
   Heinz said that in one year Drexel Burnham Lambert junk bond
chief Michael Milken, accused in the government's biggest-ever
securities fraud case, earned $550 million _ more than four times
the SEC's $135.2 million budget for 1988.
   ``It's truly a remarkable irony,'' he said.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder complained that the SEC's staff
total has remained almost flat since 1980, increasing from 2,041 to
2,050 during a time when securities trading has mushroomed. Ruder
is seeking budget authorization of $178 million in 1990, $212.6
million in 1991 and $238.1 million in 1992.
   ``Without additional resources, the commission's enforcement
staff will be unable to maintain its current pace of enforcement
actions,'' he said.
</TEXT>
