<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-18 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scandal Prosecutors to Focus on Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators of a stock scandal that has shaken
public trust in Prime Minister Noburu Takeshita and prompted
resignations of three Cabinet ministers said Tuesday they will
concentrate on prosecuting politicians.
   They made the statement after bringing bribery charges against
former Vice Minister of Education Kunio Takaishi, who was arrested
March 28.
   Fourteen bureaucrats and businessmen have been arrested in the
scandal centering on the publishing and information conglomerate,
the Recruit Co. They include Takashi Kato, a former vice minister
of labor, and Hisashi Shinto, former chairman of the
telecommunications giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
   Prosecutors said Tuesday's action concluded their inquiry into
the government bureaucracy's part in the scandal. They said they
will now focus on politicians.
   At least 17 politicians or aides, including those of Takeshita
and former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, reportedly received
large profits from 1986 sales of stocks in a Recruit subsidiary.
Most of the politicians, including Takeshita, have denied personal
wrongdoing.
   In a poll released Sunday, Takeshita's popularity sank to 3.9
percent, an all-time low. The survey followed his acknowledgement
last week that he had received more than $1 million in political
contributions from Recruit.
   Opposition parties repeatedly have demanded that Takeshita
resign and call new elections because of the scandal, but Takeshita
has vowed to stay on and push for ethics reform.
   Recruit sold unlisted shares at bargain prices to about 160
influential politicians, public officials and businessmen. The
recipients made large profits when the shares were listed shortly
afterward for public trading and shot up in price.
   Investigators said Tuesday that former Recruit chairman Hiromasa
Ezoe had sought Takaishi's help in blocking Education Ministry
plans to impose new regulations on job placement magazines. The
publications are one of Recruit's main lines of business.
   Ezoe sold the 59-year-old official 10,000 shares of stock
``which were certain to rise in value and extremely difficult for
the general public ... to obtain,'' the prosecutors said.
   According to a 1988 Supreme Court decision, the sale of stock
bound to rise in price and not available to the general public
could amount to bribery.
   Takaishi resigned from the ministry in June 1988 to run for
Parliament but pulled out of the race after his links to the
scandal were disclosed.
</TEXT>
