<FIRST>r a AM-WashingtonSale     04-18 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Washington Sale,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Marks Bicentennial With Sale of Washington Memorabilia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Pittiful' in penultimate graf is cq spelling in manuscript.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bicentennial of George Washington's
inauguration will be observed by Sotheby's with a sale of old
American manuscripts, including the first newspaper account of his
induction into office.
   The auction of 150 lots of American historical manuscripts, to
be held April 25, has sparked great interest among potential
buyers, Mary-Jo Kline, a vice president at the auction house, said
Tuesday.
   ``After two years of talk and celebration of the bicentennial of
the Constitution and its outcome, people really didn't need to be
reminded that this is an important month for Washington,'' she said.
   A highlight of the auction will be a report of Washington's
inauguration on April 18, 1789, that ran in the May 2 issue of the
Gazette of the United States. It is expected to bring $10,000 to
$15,000, the auction house said.
   The newspaper was established by John Fenno on April 15, 1789,
to provide a reliable source of news about the new government. The
Gazette's story about Washington's swearing-in on the balcony of
Federal Hall in New York City is probably the first printed account
of the event, according to Sotheby's.
   The May 2 issue that will be sold on the auction block is one of
10 copies known to survive. The other nine are owned by
institutions.
   One of the most interesting Washington-related items to be sold
is a 12-page fragment from the manuscript of Tobias Lear,
Washington's secretary from spring 1786 to 1793. The entry of
October 1786 provides a verbatim version of Washington's memories
of Benedict Arnold's treason in 1780.
   Washington begins his account of Arnold, who furnished the
British army with intelligence reports, by recalling: ``I had a
good opinion of Arnold before his treachery'' and ends by calling
him a ``mean, pittiful scoundrel.''
   The manuscript is estimated at $15,000 to $25,000.
</TEXT>
