<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DefenseProbe     04-18 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Probe,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Denies Document Access</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today refused to
release search warrants and related documents from the Pentagon
bribery investigation.
   Rejecting attempts by news organizations to inspect the
documents, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 3-0 that the
public has no right to such material, at least until a grand jury
has issued indictments.
   The ruling upheld decisions by judges in Los Angeles and San
Diego.
   Judge William Norris said the public's interest in observing the
judicial process is outweighed by the potential damage to an
investigation, including the risk of evidence being destroyed and
innocent people being maligned.
   More than a dozen people have been convicted or have pleaded
guilty in the 2-year Operation Ill Wind probe, in which contractors
and consultants are accused of bribing Pentagon officials for
inside information useful in winning contracts.
   Federal prosecutors obtained 39 search warrants in 16 judicial
districts around the country in June 1988.
</TEXT>
