<FIRST>r a AM-SeafoodAds     04-18 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seafood Ads,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Seafood Group Proposes $41 Million Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alaska seafood group has proposed a
$41.3 million advertising campaign to reassure anxious consumers
that state seafood remains pure despite last month's oil spill.
   At least part of the money could come from the Exxon Corp.,
whose tanker ran aground March 24 and spilled 10.1 million gallons
of North Slope crude oil into one of the nation's richest fishing
grounds.
   Merry Tuten, executive director of the Alaska Seafood Marketing
Institute, outlined at a board meeting Monday a major television
campaign and ads in national and international seafood and consumer
publications.
   Tuten told the joint state and industry group that the spending
plan ``was a guesstimate'' and that a final budget could be much
higher _ or much lower _ depending on the outcome of market
research.
   The tentative budget, which has been submitted to Gov. Steve
Cowper for review, is nearly seven times the size of the
institute's annual budget.
   Much of this year's campaign pitches the virtues of ``pure''
Alaska seafood from pristine coastal waters, ads aimed at consumers
spooked by reports of pollution in East Coast fishing grounds.
   In an April 7 letter to Tuten, Exxon's Don Cornett offered to
finance a state marketing campaign to reassure consumers or
wholesalers who ``believe that the supply or quality of Alaska
seafood will be affected.''
   ``Based on your analysis, we want your recommendations, and
budget figures for an appropriate marketing response. The ASMI
would have control ... and Exxon would be willing to provide
appropriate funding.''
   But some board members worried that taking the money might
hinder later efforts to collect damages from Exxon. Tuten said any
Exxon financing will be reviewed first by the state attorney
general's office.
</TEXT>
