<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-18 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College students are planning a campus
demonstration in favor of legalizing marijuana _ but not, they
insist, for the reasons you might think.
   In an era of anti-drug sentiment, University of Illinois
students planning the 13th annual ``Hash Wednesday'' say they want
to promote the cannabis plant as a source of pulp for paper and
fiber.
   One of the organizers, Debby Spindel, said smoking pot in the
open or yelling obscenities at police will be discouraged.
   Steve Hager, an Urbana native and editor of High Times magazine,
said that if fast-growing marijuana plants were used as a source of
pulp in place of trees ``the greenhouse effect and deforestation
would never be happening.''
   ``The whole issue has shifted to the environment,'' Hager said
of efforts to legalize the forbidden weed.
   Jon Gettman, national director of National Organization for the
Reform of Marijuana Laws, said legalizing the growing of marijuana
makes economic sense.
   ``We grow $33.1 billion of it a year just for the flower,''
Gettman said. ``We're talking about giving farmers another
legitimate cash crop.''
   No matter what they claim as the purpose of the legalization
drive, police will be on hand Wednesday, said campus spokesman
Terry Shephard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STATHAM, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carolyn Freeman and Viola Crow insisted for
23 years that they were being billed for their neighbor's water.
They took sponge baths and recycled dish water in futile attempts
to reduce their bills.
   This month, the city finally acknowledged that the elderly
sisters were right _ and agreed to pay back everything they were
owed.
   ``I was on the verge of a nervous breakdown'' over the large
water bills, said Mrs. Freeman, 69. ``We've been counting the
drops.''
   She said she took her first real bath at home this weekend for
the first time in more than two decades. ``It was wonderful,'' she
said.
   The sisters' troubles began in 1966, when this little town west
of Athens started charging for water by usage instead of a flat
rate.
   Their bills started soaring although they did everything they
could to cut down on water use: set up a barrel to catch rain
water, took sponge baths, recycled dish water, even ate canned
vegetables to avoid having to wash fresh ones.
   Finally, city workers confirmed this month what the widows had
suspected all along _ the water line to the house next door ran
through their meter.
   Mayor C.D. ``Buck'' Holliday offered to reimburse the women
$280, the amount they've overpaid since 1986 when the city's
billing was computerized, but he later agreed to total repayment.
   ``I think they should give her free water for the rest of her
life, plus (pay) her for all her inconvenience,'' said assistant
city clerk Elaine Hyde. She said she didn't know how long it will
take to calculate how much the sisters should get.
</TEXT>
