<FIRST>r a AM-MeleeCharges     04-18 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Melee Charges,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Filed Against Partygoers In Fight With Deputies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Mount Fiji' in lead, Sheron in penultimate graf, are cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLFLOWER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A female professional wrestler known
as ``Mount Fiji'' and six other people have been charged with
assault, rioting or battery on authorities who tried to break up an
unruly bridal shower.
   The partygoers, most of them Samoan-Americans, alleged brutality
and racism by sheriff's deputies called to the party in suburban
Cerritos on Feb. 11.
   District Attorney Ira Reiner said Monday no charges will be
filed against the officers, who he said were attacked while
responding to complaints from neighbors.
   ``This was a mob, and there were very large people,'' Reiner
said. ``This began with a 290-pound man picking up a cinder block
and heaving it at a sheriff's deputy.''
   Sheriff Sherman Block said nine of the 15 deputies injured
required medical attention.
   An arraignment is scheduled May 1 in Los Cerritos Municipal
Court for David Dole, 28, Sale Paopao, 19, Jon Talamaival, 25, and
Mark Rodarte, 25, on charges of assault with a deadly weapon on a
peace officer and misdemeanor rioting.
   Emily Dole, 31, a wrestler, was charged with obstructing a peace
officer and rioting. Two other women, Opa Tagaloa, 23, and Sheron
Dole, 20, were charged with battery and rioting, and Tagaloa with
obstructing a police officer.
