<FIRST>u w PM-BaseClosings 1stLd-Writethru a0457 04-18 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measure Heads for Approval, Meets Some Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: TOP 6 grafs new to UPDATE with debate under way. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs, Last month. Vote not expected before 4 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House prepared today to accept a federal
commission's recommendations to shut down 86 military bases, but
some members maintained that the final list was not a fair one.
   ``We do need to address the wide expenditure of taxpayers' money
but we have a right to expect ... competence, honesty and
fairness,'' said Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., at the start of debate
on a resolution to reject the commission's plan.
   In the cases of Fort Sheridan and Chanute Air Force Base in his
state of Illinois, Porter claimed, ``We got uninformed judgment. We
got an unintelligent approach.''
   He argued that the information the commission used in estimating
the bases' value was outdated and erroneous.
   Both Democratic and Republican leaders said the House was
certain to accept the commission's plan.
   ``It's time to get serious about deficit reduction,'' said Rep.
Ronald Machtley, R-R.I. ``Obsolete bases have drained our
resources. ... The recommendations are the only viable option for
cutting expenditures of funds.''
   Last month, the House Armed Services Committee voted 43-4 to
support the report by the Commission on Base Realignment and
Closure, as the commission is formally known.
   Although they acknowledged that the resolution to disapprove
will likely be defeated, lawmakers from New Jersey, California and
Illinois continued to plead with their colleagues Monday.
   ``We've been told ... mistakes have been made,'' Rep. Jim
Saxton, R-N.J., said in a speech on the chamber floor. ``The House
has an opportunity not to be party to that mistake.''
   In debate last week, lawmakers cited congressional reports that
found the commission used incorrect information as a basis for its
decision and overestimated savings from the base closings.
   Savings from the plan, which also includes substantial changes
at 54 other facilities, are estimated at $694 million a year at
first. Savings over 20 years are estimated at $5.6 billion.
   The law requires that Congress either reject the entire plan or
allow it to go into effect as s.
   In a related development Monday, the National Federation of
Federal Employees filed suit against the goverment to prevent the
closings, saying the law creating the commission was
unconstitutional.
   The lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court said the Base Closure
and Realignment Act violates the Constitution ``by improperly
delegating the important legislative function of regulating the
disposition of government property, to the unelected secretary of
defense, and to the unelected members of the commission.''
   The union represents 5,000 employees at George Air Force Base
and Norton Air Force Base in California, and Chanute Air Force Base
in Illinois. All three bases are scheduled to be closed.
   James M. Peirce, president of the union, said the commission
based its decision on ``erroneous and out of date information.''
   ``To put it simply, the commission blew it and it doesn't appear
as if the majority of Congress gives a damn,'' he said.
   The union is seeking a declaratory judgment from the courts on
whether the Base Closure and Realignment Act is unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
