<FIRST>r a AM-Accident-Radiation     04-18 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Accident-Radiation,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Release of Radioactivity Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small amount of radiation was released
earlier this year when a nuclear weapons experiment went awry, a
spokesman for Sandia National Laboratories has confirmed.
   The incident occurred Feb. 3 on the Tonopah Test Range, about
200 miles northwest of Las Vegas.
   Sandia spokesman Nigel Hey said an 8-inch howitzer cannon shell
filled with electronic equipment and radioactive material was fired
above the range. Hey said a parachute attached to the shell failed
to open and the shell penetrated the Earth instead of floating
gently to the ground.
   The device did not explode, Hey said.
   Sandia officials decided the next day to blow up the dummy
warhead with dynamite rather than move it.
   Hey said the explosion contaminated an 80-square-foot area of
the test range with small amounts of uranium. State health
officials say snow in the area prevented Sandia officials from
cleaning up the contaminated area for 20 days.
   Bill Schneider, chief of the bureau of regulatory services for
the state Division of Health, said health officials monitored the
ground for radiation on March 7, and found no contamination.
   Sandia is an Energy Department contractor and conducts several
experiments a year in conjunction with the department's office of
military operations.
</TEXT>
