<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Evangelicals     04-18 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Evangelicals,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Conservatives He Still Supports the Idea of Tuition Tax
Credits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush reassured conservatives that he
still supports the idea of tuition tax credits for parents of
private school students, according to those who met with him
Tuesday.
   In addition, Bush received high marks, after a White House
meeting with a group of evangelical Christians and other
conservatives, for the personal example he sets by attending church
services every Sunday and by his concern for people.
   ``On behalf of the evangelicals, we are extremely pleased with
Mr. Bush,'' said Billy Zeoli, president of Gospel Films, who added
that more than any policy directive it was ``mostly his example''
that encouraged them.
   Asked if he was implying criticism of former President Reagan,
who spoke often of Christian values but rarely went to church,
Zeoli said he was making no comparison and that ``everyone has
their own style.''
   The group discussed other family-centered issues, including
Bush's child-care proposal and the recent Washington march by
hundreds of thousands of pro-abortion supporters.
   On March 29, Bush had raised conservative concerns when he told
a student who asked if his parents should get a tax break for
paying tuition to send their son to a private school: ``No, they
shouldn't.'' Bush added: ``Can't afford to do that.''
   When the conservatives told him Tuesday of their worries about
those comments, the president ``indicated there had been some
confusion and that philosophically he still thought credits were
good but that the budget would not allow it,'' according to Gary
Bauer, president of the conservative Family Research Council and
one of those at the meeting.
   Bauer, interviewed by telephone, and others, who spoke to
reporters outside the White House, said they were satisfied with
Bush's assurances. They said they recognized the budget argument
and were happy at least with his philosophical stance.
   White House press spokesman B.J. Cooper said that Bush has not
wavered in his support for the idea of tuition tax credits, but
that as the president had said on March 29, the constraints of the
federal budget and the need to maintain revenues are not conducive
to creating such a program this year.
   In those earlier comments, Bush had told the boy who questioned
him, ``Everybody should support the public school system and then,
if on top of that, your parents think that they want to shell out
in addition to the tax money, tuition money, that's their right.
But I don't think they should get a break for that.''
   The Reagan administration had supported the idea of tuition tax
credits for parents sending children to private schools, but
dropped the idea in a major overhaul of the tax system.
   Bush's March 29 comments caused Robert Dugan Jr., director of
the National Association of Evangelicals, to send a letter
expressing ``dismay'' about Bush's apparent shift of position.
   The conservatives, who in the past have been suspicious of
Bush's commitment to many of their causes, were generally
complimentary of him after Tuesday's meeting.
   ``As a general rule, evangelicals are happy and pleased with the
job the president has been doing,'' said Adrian Rogers, former
president of the Southern Baptist Convention.
   There was much discussion on abortion, with the conservatives
indicating they hoped the massive turnout by the pro-choice group
would not make Bush soften his anti-abortion stance.
   Bush said Tuesday that he supported the right of the protesters
to voice their opinions, said Jerry Vines, president of the
Southern Baptist Convention.
   However, he was ``very reassuring'' in his statement opposed to
abortion, said Bauer.
</TEXT>
