<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--NASAResignation     04-18 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--NASA Resignation,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Designer Leaving To Join Aerospace Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the team that redesigned the
faulty space shuttle booster rockets is leaving NASA this week to
become an aerospace official for Lockheed Corp.
   John Thomas, 52, is retiring as special assistant to the
director of the Marshall Space Flight Center to become Lockheed's
Kennedy Space Center site director.
   At the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, he has
worked on the Skylab and Spacelab programs as well as helping
pinpoint a failed booster rocket seal as the cause of the 1986
Challenger explosion. The redesigned solid fuel rockets have flown
successfully three times.
   Thomas will direct Lockheed's contract work processing space
shuttles, including stacking boosters and mating the shuttle
orbiters and boosters to the external fuel tank.
   Thomas said a decision to leave Marshall and NASA after 28 years
in various space agency assignments came after considering
``whether I wanted to go on doing what I was doing ... or go do
something different.''
