<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Farms     04-18 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Farms,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Collective Farm Directors Wary of Land Leasing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Collective farm directors are wary and confused
about new laws permitting them to lease land, but most see the move
toward private property as the only way to increase production,
according to a survey published Tuesday.
   Of the 176 heads of collective farms questioned by the Kursk
Agricultural Institute, only one-fifth believed strongly in leasing
and nearly half answered, ``I have doubts about it, but I just
don't see any other way.''
   Results were published in the Communist Party daily newspaper
Pravda.
   ``The conviction is widespread that the attitude toward leasing
could flip by 180 degrees one fine moment _ and goodbye to the
valuables attained through sweat and blood,'' wrote Y. Vorobyov,
dean of the institute in Kursk, a southwestern Russian city.
   One-fifth of the farmers believed leasing would only make things
worse, and 7 percent ``consider the situation so far gone that they
don't see any way out of it'' Pravda said.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told party leaders last month
they must give farmers a feeling they are masters of the land
because billions of dollars worth of investment brought only
marginal increases in harvest.
   On April 9, a new decree was published giving Soviet citizens
sweeping rights to lease land for 50 or more years, pass it on to
their children and sub-lease it. The decree created property rights
that had been virtually non-existent under 70 years of communism.
   The leasing decree's success in bringing economic improvement is
expected to depend on the bureaucrats who have the power to enact
the reforms or block them.
   Asked about the main obstacles to leasing, 38 percent of the
survey's respondents cited farmers' reluctance to undertake a new
enterprise; 34 percent pointed to farm specialists' disbelief that
the leasing would really be ``serious and long-term''; and 22
percent cited ``unclear ideas'' among farm leaders themselves about
what leasing meant.
   In all, however, almost two-thirds saw leasing as a positive
phenomenon, Pravda reported.
   Vorobyov wrote that two years ago, a similar survey asked more
than 500 farm specialists if they planned to lease land, and 25
percent gave a ``categorical no'' while only 10 percent said they
did.
   ``We have been taught by the bitter experience of the past,''
Pravda said, referring to the collectivization period of the 1930s
when millions of peasants were forced to give up their land to
collective farms.
</TEXT>
