<HEAD>British National to Head Tamil Negotiations With Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels chose a Sri Lankan-born
British national to set up peace talks with the government aimed at
ending their 6-year-old war for a homeland, officials and rebel
sources said Tuesday.
   Anton Balasingham, head of the political section of the largest
Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, will set
the date and place for the talks, and participate in the
negotiating team, according to rebel sources.
   Evans Cooray, press secretary to President Ranasinghe Premadasa,
said the government had been notified Balasingham was designated to
make arrangements for the talks.
   On Saturday, Tamil rebels accepted an invitation by Premadasa
for meetings on ending the ethnic violence that has claimed more
than 12,600 lives since 1983. The announcement came after they were
blamed for three days of bombings that killed 79 people.
   Premadasa extended the offer to the radical Sinhalese People's
Liberation Front, which has not responded to the president's call.
   The Front launched a violent campaign against the government,
saying it was making too many concessions to the Tamils. They have
been blamed for more than 2,500 killings since January.
   Sinhalese extremists killed six people late Monday in separate
attacks in Southern Sri Lanka, an official said on condition of
anonymity. Victims included a soldier, a policeman and his brother,
the official said.
   Tamil militants have been fighting since 1983 for a separate
homeland they propose to carve out of the northern and northeastern
provinces, where most Tamils live.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. They say they are discriminated against
in jobs and education by the majority Sinhalese.
   Sri Lanka's government and military has been dominated by the
Sinhalese since the island, formerly called Ceylon, became
independent from Britain in 1948. Mostly Buddhists, they make up 75
percent of the population.
