<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Drought     04-18 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recovery Underway, But Slowly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation has been coming back slowly from
last summer's drought, but conditions are improving, government
reports showed Tuesday.
   Streamflows increased in March for most of the nation, the U.S.
Geological Survey reported, although below normal rates persisted
in the Northeast, a portion of the Southeast and part of the wheat
belt.
   Overall, about 30 percent of the nation was still classified as
in severe or extreme drought at the end of March, compared to 33
percent in February and a high of about 40 percent last August, the
National Climatic Data Center reported.
   Only nine times in this century has drought been more widespread
in March, according to the center, a division of the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Those years were 1902,
1934-35, 1940, 1954-55-56-57 and 1977.
   The Northeast has emerged as a major water problem area, with
the Delaware River basin hovering near the drought emergency level,
the Geological Survey reported.
   Rainfall this month has helped push water levels in the basin
above the emergency mark, the agency said, but not by a wide margin.
   The Delaware River was measured at only 2.4 billion gallons per
day in March, 61 percent below normal and the second lowest level
since 1940.
   In the Northeast, below-normal streamflows were reported in
Maine, Vermont, New Hampshire, New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey
and northern Ohio.
   The St. Lawrence River, one of the nation's largest, averaged 12
percent below normal for the month at 142 billion gallons per day.
   The survey also noted that flows were below normal in most of
Georgia, northern Florida and southern South Carolina.
   To the west, below-normal water flows were recorded in most of
Kansas and in parts of Wyoming, Nebraska, Missouri and North Dakota.
   On a national level, 45 river-measuing stations reported
below-normal rates while flows were above normal at 35 locations
and near normal at 99 places last month, the survey said.
   The Mississippi River _ which fell so low that barge traffic was
disrupted last summer _ was measured at 793 billion gallons a day
in March, 50 percent more than normal.
   Among the Mississippi's major tributaries, the Ohio averaged a
normal 161 billion gallons per day, while the Missouri was 28
percent below normal with a flow of 34 billion gallons per day.
   The Geological Survey reported that the Columbia River was 16
percent above normal at 92 billion gallons per day for the month.
   Other regions reporting above-normal streamflows for the month
included most of Oregon; northern Nevada and California; parts of
Colorado and New Mexico; northern and western Texas; Delaware and
the easternmost portions of Maryland, Virginia and North Carolina.
</TEXT>
