<HEAD>Officers Reprimanded For Trainee Mistreatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fort Benning authorities have reprimanded
27 officers and non-commissioned officers for physically abusing
Army trainees by ordering too much exercise, a spokesman said.
   The 27 face varying punishments including relief from duty,
formal reprimand, forfeiture of pay, demotion, confinement and
extra duty, Lt. Col. McDonald Plummer said this week.
   The 39 trainees from C and D companies of the 3rd Battalion,
32nd Infantry Regiment, were hospitalized in mid-February,
complaining of soreness and muscle swelling. All but two returned
to training. One is being treated for kidney malfunction at Walter
Reed Memorial Hospital and the other is out of the hospital.
   A new Army directive requires drill sergeants to ease up on
running and high-impact workouts during part of basic training. The
directive affects Fort Benning and the Army's other seven
basic-training posts.
