<FIRST>r w AM-Watkins-Spill     04-18 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Watkins-Spill,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Chief Says Spill Creates `Pivotal Time' For Oil Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The massive Exxon oil spill in Alaska's Prince
William Sound has blackened the image of the entire oil industry
and thrust it into ``a pivotal time in its history,'' Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins said Tuesday.
   ``Every oil company will have to confront the images created by
the spill,'' Watkins said in a speech to the National Petroleum
Council, a group of private energy officials that advises the
energy secretary on policy issues.
   Watkins said his department would attempt to persuade Congress
and the general public that the March 24 spill of 10 million
gallons of Alaskan crude by the tanker Exxon Valdez was an
aberration that should not halt oil development in Alaska.
   ``We're going to talk about the track record of the industry _
6{ billion barrels of crude shipped out of Valdez in a dozen years
on nearly 9,000 tankers with virtually no environmental damage _
until now,'' Watkins said.
   He stressed, however, that the enormity of the Exxon spill had
galvanized public opinion in a way that evolving problems, such as
U.S. reliance on foreign oil, could not.
   ``Obviously, the oil industry has suddenly and tragically
reached a pivotal time in its history,'' Watkins said, adding that
it would require efforts by the entire industry to recover from
public relations damage caused by the Valdez spill.
   Watkins said his department would continue to lobby for
legislation permitting oil companies to explore for oil in the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge. A Senate bill offering such
authorization was approved by the Energy and Natural Resources
Committee in early March but was put on hold after the Exxon spill.
   ``We're going to ... attempt to break the linkage that I'm
afraid is developing in the public's mind that the Valdez incident
means that we no longer can risk new development on the North
Slope,'' Watkins said.
   Watkins said pursuit of possible oil discoveries in the Arctic
refuge was justified as a means of limiting the nation's growing
dependence on imported oil.
   ``Our vulnerability to oil supply disruptions is greater today
than it was at the time of the Arab oil embargo (and) becoming more
apparent to the American public as we approach and perhaps pass the
50 percent oil import mark,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
