<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1859EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-18 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Forces Reopen Supply Route to Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces reopened Kabul's
main overland supply route that had been blocked by Moslem
guerrillas, and a convoy of 1,300 trucks and other vehicles resumed
its journey toward the capital Tuesday, officials said.
   In the battle for the eastern city of Jalalabad, the guerrillas
launched another assault, attacking it from four directions, said
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani.
   Foreign journalists saw about 200 trucks from the convoy reach a
government checkpoint on the Salang Highway just north of the
capital Tuesday. Amani said more would arrive throughout the night
and Wednesday.
   He said the convoy, which was blocked for more than a week,
began moving again after the government soldiers dislodged the
U.S.-backed guerrillas from two posts on the highway.
   Helicopter gunships provided air cover for the convoy, which
included a few crowded buses and taxis. Gunfire was heard as the
vehicles moved south, but truck drivers said it was not serious.
   Government troops in armored personnel carriers waved their caps
and cheered as they saw the convoy's vehicles approach the capital.
   After the departure of Soviet troops in February, Soviet
supplies continued to move down the 260-mile Salang Highway until
the guerrillas blocked it on April 6.
   The government on Tuesday sent a separate convoy of about 105
trucks from Kabul to Jalalabad, about 75 miles to the east, Amani
said. He said he believed the vehicles had reached the city.
   However, some guards at a checkpoint about 10 miles east of
Kabul said the road was closed. Others said it was open most of the
way.
   That road has been blocked for more than two weeks by
Pakistani-based guerrillas who have been attacking Jalalabad since
March 6.
   Amani said 18 civilians were killed and 21 wounded in the
Jalalabad fighting. Two government soldiers were killed and five
injured, while 47 guerrillas died and 19 were injured, he said.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas have made Jalalabad the target of
their first major offensive since the departure of the Soviet
troops, who had been helping the Marxist government.
   Amani also reported 32 guerrillas killed in battles to the south.
   There was no way to confirm those reports independently.
   In other fighting, guerrillas attacked a district near the
southern city of Khost, Amani said. He said no civilians or
government troops were killed but 18 guerrillas died.
   Government forces also battled guerrillas in the southern
province of Kandahar, killing 14 and wounding 40, Amani said.
</TEXT>
