<HEAD>Bork Says Liberals Seek Control Of Laws and Culture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert H. Bork, still stinging from the
Senate's rejection of his nomination to the Supreme Court two years
ago, says he was the victim of liberals who are trying to take
control of the nation's laws and culture.
   The former federal appeals court judge said Monday that the
political blood-letting continues to infect Contress and is a
mounting threat to President Bush.
   ``The members of the '60s generation have reached middle age,
and they have brought their ideological baggage with them,'' Bork
told the Economic Club of Indianapolis.
   He says liberals are trying to manipulate judicial and executive
branches of the government to change the American way of life.
   ``These folks want to run the presidency from Capitol Hill, and
they want to have the Supreme Court enact the laws that Capitol
Hill does not dare,'' Bork said.
   ``The fact is that our political parties have grown increasingly
polarized, and the mood in Washington right now, I think, is little
short of poisonous,'' he said.
