<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Volunteers     04-18 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Volunteers,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Announces Plan for Overseas Volunteer Service Corps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea announced Tuesday it will
create a youth volunteer corps to offer technical assistance to
less developed countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
   The Korean Young Volunteers is patterned after the U.S. Peace
Corps, said Lee Soo-jung, press secretary to President Roh Tae-woo.
   He said the government program will give youths experience in
international cooperation and allow South Korea to contribute to
less-developed nations.
   It has not been decided where the first group of volunteers will
go.
   In the latter half of 1990, the program will send abroad 50
young people, selected mainly from among college students, and 100
annually in succeeding years, Lee said.
   He said members of the service corps will receive five months of
training, and will be paid salaries and living allowances during
their two-year overseas tours.
   The volunteers will offer assistance in health and sanitation,
agricultural techniques, community development, sports and youth
activities, and education and cultural pursuits, Lee said.
</TEXT>
