<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-Lebanon     04-18 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Lebanon,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Little U.S. Can Do to Stop Lebanon Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Tuesday the United States has extremely limited influence on the
warring factions in Lebanon and can do little through diplomatic or
political pressure to improve the situation.
   ``It is a great tragedy that is very, very intractable,'' Baker
told the Senate Foreign Relations Commitee. ``It does not lend
itself to an easy solution.''
   He said that for all practical purposes, the State Department is
limited to issuing statements strongly deploring the violence,
urging a ceasefire and calling for the withdrawal of Syrian forces
from the country.
   ``We make a lot of statements and sometimes it is frustrating to
think that is really about all we can do,'' Baker said. ``I don't
know what else, frankly, we can do. We have scant influence with
the Syrians.''
   Baker said President Bush discussed the Lebanon situation
earlier in the day with French President Francois Mitterrand, but
he did not elaborate.
   In Paris, presidential spokesman Hubert Vedrine said Mitterrand
had contacted Bush as well as British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and several other world leaders to solicit their help in
ending the war.
   Baker said that some people believe there ``ought to be somehow
some greater activity or action on the part of the United States,
either unilaterally or acting jointly with France.''
   ``We don't see the potential for that right now,'' he said.
   Responding to questions, Baker said that the United States is
urging international support for mediation efforts by the 21-nation
Arab League to bring a stop to fighting between Christian and
Moslem forces.
   ``It is our view that the initiative that has the greatest
chance of success is the initiative of the Arab League,'' Baker
said.
   Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum, R-Kan., asked if it would help
matters to call the U.S. ambassadors to Lebanon and Syria home for
consultation.
   ``I don't know how much a statement recalling ambassadors would
make,'' Baker replied.
   ``The situation in Lebanon remains a rebuke to everyone's hopes
for a restoration of stability and independence for that tragic
country,'' Baker said.
   Casualties from the fighting in Lebanon during the past six
weeks total at least 270 killed and 975 wounded.
   Syria maintains about 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab
League mandate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
