<HEAD>Rebel Raids Force Closure of Catholic Mission Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel raids and the abduction of six
staff members forced the closure of a 300-bed hospital run by a
Roman Catholic mission in northern Uganda, a newspaper said Tuesday.
   Dr. Pierre Levi Cotti, the hospital director, said the facility
on the outskirts of Gulu, 280 miles north of Kampala, won't be
reopened until the government can guarantee security.
   Rebels seeking drugs have raided the hospital 12 times since
last year, according to the state-run New Vision newspaper.
   In March, they abducted the deputy director and five nurses from
the facility, which is run by the Italian Verona Fathers, the
newspaper said. All but one nurse were later released.
   Rebels of the Holy Spirit Movement, one of 10 insurgent groups
seeking to overthrow President Yoweri Museveni, have staged attacks
in the Gulu area in recent months.
