<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Armed Services Committee voted
unanimously Tuesday to recommend that the Senate confirm President
Bush's choice of General Motors executive Donald Atwood to become
deputy defense secretary.
   By 20-0, the committee approved Bush's nomination of the
automaker's vice chairman to take over the No. 2 civilian pos at
the Pentagon.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the committee, expressed hope
that the full Senate would vote on the nomination either Wednesday
or Thursday.
   During his confirmation hearing, Atwood promised to sell his
more than $3 million in company stock to avoid any conflict of
interest. He also said he took out an insurance policy to guarantee
his GM pension should the company fail, to protect against any
suggestion he would use his government office to protect the
company for the sake of a pension.
   Atwood, 64, owns about $1.4 million in restricted GM stock
options and about $1.2 million in Class E common stock as well as
other types of common stock estimated at over $750,000, documents
show.
   In addition, Atwood owns from $5,000 to $15,000 in AT&amp;T stock
and from $50,000 to $100,000 in Exxon stock. Financial disclosure
forms only require listing a range of assets.
