<FIRST>r w AM-US-Afghanistan 400   04-18 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan, 400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Says Fighting Should End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The continuing turmoil in Afghanistan will
``tarnish the international atmosphere'' unless an end to the
fighting is found, a Washington-based Soviet diplomat said Tuesday.
   ``Everybody is going to lose,'' if the conflict continues, said
Oleg Derkovsky, counselor at the Soviet Embassy.
   Derkovsky, in a meeting with a group of reporters, repeated
Soviet charges that Pakistan has violated the U.N.-mediated Geneva
Accord which oversaw the withdrawal of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan on Feb. 15.
   In recent weeks, the Soviets have repeatedly accused Pakistan of
interfering in Afghanistan by supporting Moslem guerrillas in their
decade-long fight to topple Kabul's government.
   The Geneva accord calls for Pakistan and Afghanistan not to
interfere in each other's internal affairs. The United States and
Soviet Union are guarantors of the pact, which was signed last year.
   But the United States has vowed to continue to support the
rebels as long as Moscow continues to ship munitions to the Kabul.
The rebel leaders are based in Pakistan, which has funneled much of
the U.S. weaponry and support to the rebels over the years.
   Derkovsky called the conflict, in light of the Soviet pull-out,
``a civil war'' that will grow into a regional conflict.
   ``Regional conflicts tarnish the international atmosphere,'' the
diplomat said.
   He charged the United States with violating the spirit of the
accord and called the U.S. decision to send a special ambassador to
the rebel factions ``not a helpful step.''
   The Soviet official, who questioned the U.S. policy of not
recognizing the Kabul regime, said the act ``confuses the
situation'' because the official would not be dealing with a
recognized government.
   The official's statement came a day after U.S. Ambassador Thomas
R. Pickering said the pro-Soviet Afghan government has turned to
the United Nations Security Council in a bid ``to retain its waning
grip on Afghanistan.''
   The ambassadors of Cuba, East Germany and Mongolia had called
Monday for a U.N.-arranged cease-fire and an international
conference to set up a coalition government in Afghanistan.
   The new U.S. ambassador accused Kabul of trying to involve other
nations in its struggle for political survival.
   ``The Afghan people themselves must be allowed to determine
their own future, without outside interference or coercion,''
Pickering told the council.
</TEXT>
