<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CatastrophicHealth     04-18 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Health,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeal of Program Introduced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of House Republicans introduced
legislation Tuesday to repeal parts of the catastrophic health
expansion of Medicare passed last year _ mainly the income tax
surcharge imposed on the well-to-do elderly to help finance the
program.
   The measure, unveiled at a news conference, would keep most of
the major benefits of the program, but revamp a prescription drug
benefit and make its more generous provisions apply only to
low-income Medicare beneficiaries not poor enough to qualify for
Medicaid.
   However, the measure passed by overwhelming margins with
bipartisan support in both the House and Senate last year _ despite
vocal opposition from those opposed to the surcharge feature _ and
was signed into law by then-President Reagan with great fanfare.
   That surcharge that has provoked a barrage of letters to members
of Congress even though it does not apply not apply at all to any
of the estimated 60 percent of the 32 million Medicare
beneficiaries who do not have enough income to pay federal taxes.
   Of the 40 percent subject to the surcharge, only those couples
with annual incomes of $100,000 or so would be subject to the
maximum surcharge of $800 a person _ or $1,600 per couple _ that
frequently is cited as example of the additional burden placed on
the elderly to pay for the program.
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, D-Fla., a lead sponsor of the
legislation, acknowledged in an interview that many of his own
constituents who have complained mistakenly believe they will be
subject to an income tax surcharge.
   Bilirakis and other sponsors also acknowledged that getting
their bill passed will be an uphill fight and that their first
hurdle will be to get a hearing for their legislation in the
Democratic-controlled House.
   But Bilirakis said he is hopeful the letters of complaint
reaching Capitol Hill will have the same impact as the outpouring
of opposition to a recent proposal for a congressional pay raise.
   On that issue, he said, ``They bombed us and bombed us and
bombed us and finally Congress bent.''
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Finance Committee
that has main jurisdiction over the issue in the Senate, has
already said he probably will schedule a hearing merely to air the
issues raised by opponents to the progressive financing nature of
the catastrophic health expansion.
   Bentsen expressed confidence that whatever support may be
emerging for redoing that portion of the bill will evaporate once
the large majority of Medicare beneficiaries not subject to the
surcharge realize they are likely to either see their own premium
payments go up or have benefits reduced.
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel of Illinois, who signed on as a
cosponsor, said he reacted in response to ``so many people out
there who have raised their voices'' about costs of the Medicare
expansion.
   He said that, at the very least, discussion f the legislation
should drive home the point that ``there is no magic wand you can
wave here and have it all free.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0173 </DOCNO>
