<FIRST>r w Non-DeductibleWeddings     04-18 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>Non-Deductible Weddings,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Undertaker Can't Take a Business Deduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tax Court turned thumbs down Tuesday on a
Minnesota undertaker who took a business tax deduction for $11,000
of expenses of wedding receptions for two daughters.
   William L. McReavy of Minneapolis and his wife, Kathleen,
claimed the receptions as an advertising-entertainment expense,
contending that 82 percent of the people invited were clients or
referral sources for his Washburn-McReavy Funeral Chapels, Inc.
   ``The personal element of the expenses for the McReavys'
daughters' weddings was so prominent that we believe that even a
person not versed in the tax law would know that the corporation
could not deduct them,'' the court held.
   The court was so unimpressed by the argument that it allowed the
Internal Revenue Service to add a negligence penalty to the
McReavys' bill.

</TEXT>
