<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     04-18 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arabs Kill Suspected Collaborator; 21 Wounded In Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four masked youths wearing Arab headdresses
broke into the home of a Palestinian woman accused of collaborating
with Israel and stabbed her to death Tuesday, Arab and Israeli
military reports said.
   Most stores and businesses in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip were closed by a general strike that halted public transport.
   Israeli troops in the occupied lands shot and wounded at least
30 Palestinians in clashes with stone-throwers Tuesday, Arab
hospital officials said. They said the ages of the wounded ranged
from 8 to 52.
   At least 439 Palestinians have been killed in the 16-month-old
uprising against Israeli occupation, and 18 Israelis have been
slain.
   Eighteen of Tuesday's casualties were reported in Gaza's Khan
Yunis refugee camp. Doctors said 18-year-old Amir Ahmed Risik was
in critical condition with a bullet in the chest and was moved to a
hospital in Israel.
   Arab reporters said the trouble in Khan Yunis began with
stone-throwing in the morning in which 10 people were wounded. In
the afternoon, they said, camp residents marched to the home of a
youth killed earlier in the week and more clashes occurred.
   An army official confirmed the death but provided no details.
   Another casualty was a 14-year-old Arab boy shot on the
outskirts of Jerusalem when an Israeli garbage truck driver opened
fire on youths who stoned his vehicle, the army said. The shooting
occurred in Azariye, the Arabic name for biblical Bethany.
   Doctors at Mukassed Hospital said he had a critical head wound.
   Jerusalem police closed three private schools established to
tutor students from the occupied lands whose universities have been
closed by Israeli military authorities, Israel radio reported.
   The schools, run by teachers from West Bank's Bir Zeit and
Bethlehem universities, were discovered after an Arab youth from
Gaza was detained in Jerusalem and told police about them, the
radio said.
   It said police were trying to determine whether other such
schools had been started to to circumvent the university closing.
Jerusalem police spokesmen were not available for comment.
   All Arab universities were closed in January 1988, soon after
the uprising began, on grounds they were focal points of the revolt.
   On Monday, six Palestinians died, including two teen-agers said
to have been shot by soldiers during funeral marches that turned
into anti-Israeli protests.
   The army Tuesday denied one of the teen-agers, Rafideh Khalili
Ahmad Abu Laban, 13, was a victim of army gunfire.
   ``She was not killed during the clash between soldiers and local
residents,'' an army spokesman, adding that the investigation
continued but was hampered by the parents' refusal to allow an
autopsy.
   Witnesses in the Dheishe refugee camp said the girl was watching
a funeral march from a nearby hillside when she was struck in the
forehead by a bullet apparently fired by soldiers.
   Arabs identified the victim of the stabbing Tuesday as Nadira
Boulus, 43, of Nablus on the West Bank. She was dead on arrival at
nearby Rafidiyeh hospital, doctors said.
   An army spokesman confirmed the death.
   Arab reports said Ms. Boulus suffered multiple stab wounds from
four attackers masked with kaffiyeh headdresses. Supporters of the
attackers ringed the house during the killing.
   The reports said Ms. Boulus previously was beaten by Palestinian
activists who accused her of collaborating with Israel.
   Arabs have killed more than 65 of the Palestinians who died in
the uprising, accusing them of helping Israeli authorities.
   In Israel, police detained three Palestinians in connection with
a fire that destroyed 70 trees near Jerusalem in a forest named for
the late President John F. Kennedy.
   The fire was put out, said police spokesman Uzi Sandori.
   Last summer, thousands of acres of trees were burned in Israel.
Authorities blamed Palestinians after uprising leaders urged such
attacks.
</TEXT>
