<FIRST>r w AM-US-Ambassadors     04-18 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Ambassadors,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote Delayed on Negroponte, Others Confirmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Tuesday delayed a vote on the nomination of John Negroponte to be
ambassador to Mexico because of questions raised about his part in
the Iran-Contra affair.
   The panel also voted to postpone a vote on the nomination of
Joseph Verner Reed as Chief of Protocol for the White House.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., blocked the vote because Reed wrote a
letter last year to former Secretary of State George Shultz asking
that PLO chief Yasser Arafat be allowed to address the United
Nations, said a congressional source. Reed wrote the letter in his
capacity as a U.N. undersecretary after Shultz denied Arafat a visa
to come to New York.
   Three ambassadors were approved by the panel, including Michael
Armacost as ambassador to Japan, James Lilley as ambassador to
China and Terence A. Todman as ambassador to Argentina. The
nominations must now be approved by the full Senate.
   Postponement of the a vote on Negroponte was requested by Sen.
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., the chairman so he could review classified
answers provided by the nominee late Monday regarding his role in
the plane to aid the anti-Nicaraguan Contras, said the source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The committee had asked Negroponte to explain the messages he
conveyed to the Honduran goverment in 1985 when he served there as
ambassador. The message involved continued support for the Contras
at a time when Congress had banned U.S. military aid to the rebels.
   Negroponte denied at his confirmation hearing that the message
he was asked to relay offered Honduras accelerated U.S. economic
and military aid in return for its support of the Contras.
Documents which have surfaced at the trial of former White House
aide Oliver North suggest such a quid pro quo may have been offered
to the Hondurans by George Bush when he served as vice president.
   But Negroponte, who was present at Bush's meeting with Honduran
President Roberto Suazo in March 1985, has denied there was any
talk of a swap.
</TEXT>
