<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru a0632 04-18 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa Says It May Delay Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `In Namibia...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with U.N.
personnel escort three guerrillas to Angola in first such transfer. Pick
up 9th pvs, `At a...' Minor editing to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The timetable for removing South
African troops from Namibia will be abandoned unless all black
nationalist guerrillas withdraw to Angola soon, Foreign Minister
Pik Botha said Tuesday.
   Botha said the U.N. plan to bring independence to Namibia still
is on schedule, despite heavy fighting this month when guerrillas
of the South-West Africa People's Organization crossed into Namibia
from Angola.
   But the timetable will be disrupted if guerrillas still in the
territory do not leave by month's end, Botha said.
   South Africa claims 1,600 guerrillas entered Namibia, also known
as South-West Africa, after April 1 in violation of an agreement
they would remain in Angola at least until mid-May.
   According to South Africa, 278 guerrillas have been killed and
28 captured, about 380 have returned to Angola, and about 900
remain in Namibia. SWAPO says the numbers are much lower.
   Botha said his troops will not return to their bases or withdraw
to South Africa, as called for in the U.N. plan, until a total
SWAPO withdrawal is verified.
   South Africa does not disclose its troop strength in Namibia,
but it is supposed to have no more than 12,000 soldiers there by
May 14.
   In Windhoek, the Namibian capital, territorial officials said
U.N. personnel escorted three SWAPO guerrillas into Angola Tuesday.
The three were among only seven guerrillas who have turned
themselves in at U.N. assembly points to be sent to Angola. The
officials said the four others remained in Namibia.
   Tuesday's transfer was the first by U.N. forces since the
assembly points were established last week in northern Namibia.
   The territorial officials also reported a landmine explosion
damaged an army truck Monday in the northern Namibia. They said no
one was injured by the blast, which they blamed on SWAPO.
   At a news briefing, Botha expressed annoyance at reports that
security forces acted callously in disposing of bodies of slain
guerrillas. He said such reports diverted attention from SWAPO's
responsibility for the combat.
   Armed forces chief Gen. Jannie Geldenhuys said his troops had
firm instructions not to bury enemy bodies in mass graves. But he
said ``relatively inexperienced'' policemen did so when ``suddenly
confronted with large numbers of dead in blistering heat.''
   By Tuesday, only seven guerrillas had reported to U.N.
checkpoints established to give the insurgents safe passage back to
Angola. The others who have withdrawn did so on their own.
   South African, U.N. and local community officials have predicted
few guerrillas will venture near the assembly points because of
heavy concentrations of South African-led police and soldiers
around each area.
   U.N. police monitors are to be deployed in northern Namibia this
week, and their superiors have urged residents to report any
incidents of harassment or brutality. There have been numerous
allegations that security forces have been mistreating SWAPO
supporters.
   South Africa has ruled the mineral-rich territory since World
War I. In December, it agreed to allow independence in exchange for
Cuba withdrawing its estimated 50,000 troops from Angola.
   SWAPO has been fighting South African rule since 1966 and is
favored to win most votes in independence elections scheduled for
November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
