<FIRST>r w AM-Capitol-DomeStatue     04-18 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capitol-Dome Statue,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitol Statue to Be Restored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The giant bronze statue of Freedom on top of
the Capitol dome is so badly deteriorated after 125 years that it
will be removed _ probably by helicopter _ brought to the ground
and restored, the architect of the Capitol said on Tuesday.
   Architect George White made the disclosure at a ceremony
launching a multi-million dollar fund raising effort to provide
private-sector dollars to finance restoration projects at the
Capitol and to create a fund to buy art works associated with its
past.
   White said the first projects will be the restoration of the
statue, formally titled ``Armed Freedom,'' and the installation of
marble fountains on the Capitol's East Plaza, ending its use as a
parking lot.
   He estimated the cost at $300,000 to $400,000 but said that the
paving of the entire plaza in patterned stone will likely cost more
than $6 million.
   The statue, which weighs 14,985 pounds, rises 19 feet six inches
from the top of the dome. It was hoisted into position and bolted
into place on Dec. 2, 1863.
   ``It hasn't been touched since,'' White said. ``When we had the
dome repainted last summer we confirmed that the statue is in vary
serious condition.
   He said that cracks had developed in some of the interior
fastenings of the statue and that an exterior piece of the staue's
flowing robes had fallen out. The statue consists of five separate
pieces of cast bronze bolted together and attached to a cast-iron
base.
   ``The whole thing is in really bad condition,'' White said.
``Bronze does deteriorate.''
   In preparation for removing the statue a protective cage will be
built around it, White said and added:
   ``We'll probably take it down by helicopter.''
   White estimated the cost of the project at $250,000 but added,
``It could cost a lot more, depending on how serious the damage is
when we get it down and are able to examine more closely.
</TEXT>
