<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Communists     04-18 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Communists,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Wants to Keep Control of Visits by Communists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration told Congress on
Tuesday it wants to preserve the right to control entry to the
United States of anyone who was ever a Communist.
   The stance was spelled out in a letter to Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass, who has led a six-year fight to change the current law and
limit the power of the government to keep out visitors from abroad.
   The National Education Association, a private group, distributed
a letter to Congress in support of Frank's bill. It said the
present law has been used to keep out Primo Levi, the Italian
chemist and novelist, Colombian novelist Gabriel Garcia Marquez and
Mexican novelist Carlos Fuentes.
   The letter from the administration, signed in the name of Joe D.
Whitley, acting associate attorney general, said, ``Unless our
reservations are addresssed, the department cannot support the
enactment of this proposed legislation.''
   He asked for changes to Frank's bill that would permit the
attorney general to set conditions for the visit to the United
States of anyone who has ever belonged to a Communist party or to
one of its affiliates.
   Frank criticized the Justice Department, which he said had
refused to discuss his bill with him and then had sent its
nine-page letter of objections only on the morning of the session.
   He said he may agree with some of the objections but would not
discuss them at Tuesday's session.
   Meanwhile, the Judiciary Committee's immigration subcommittee
rejected, 7-3, an effort to amend Frank's bill in such a way as to
preserve the administration's right to control the visits of
present and former Communists. Rep. Lamar S. Smith, R-Texas, is
expected to propose the amendment again as the bill goes through
later stages in the House.
   ``I, too, am a supporter of free speech,'' Smith told the
subcommittee. ``However, our country's national security should
never be jeopardized for free speech.''
   Smith was opposed by Rep. Hamilton Fish Jr., R-N.Y., who joined
the Democrats in voting against the amendment.
   ``The exclusion of Communists is out of date,'' Fish said in an
interview after the session.
   ``There are different kinds of Communists in different
countries. Some would be people we wouldn't want as visitors.
Others would be acceptable. An Italian Communist, for example, is
different from many others,'' he said.
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn, chairman of the subcommittee,
ridiculed Smith's proposal.
   ``With that amendment in force, George Washington would never
have been able to get back in if he had left the country,''
Morrison said. ``It would exclude anyone with revolutionary ideas.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
