<FIRST>r w AM-US-Thailand     04-18 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Thailand,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members of Congress Seek Human Rights for Displaced Cambodians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 100 House members are asking the Thai
government to help Cambodians ``held against their will'' leave
refugee camps near the Thai-Cambodian border and under the control
of the communist Khmer Rouge.
   A letter sent to Thai ambassador Vitthya Vejjajiva said that
thousands of the perhaps 100,000 displaced Cambodians in Khmer
Rouge-controlled camps ``are held against their will ... and would
move to other camps if they had the freedom to do so.''
   A copy of the letter bearing the names of members of both
parties was circulated Tuesday by Asia Watch, a private human
rights monitoring organization.
   It quoted reports as saying camp inmates are subjected to
summary executions, forced removal to mine-strewn combat areas,
forced labor, torture, denial of medical treatment and other abuses.
   As a first step toward providing freedom of movement to the
displaced Cambodians, the letter asked Thailand to facilitate free
access by international relief agencies to Khmer Rouge camps on its
soil. It welcomed recent reports that the Thai government was
considering measures to improve the refugees' situation.
   The Thai Embassy said the letter was received and preparing a
statement on it.
   Countries working toward a political settlement involving the
withdrawal of Vietnamese military forces from Cambodia have urged
safeguards against a return to power by the Khmer Rouge, blamed for
millions of deaths during its rule of Cambodia before the 1978
Vietnamese invasion. Thailand has been accused of seeking to use
the Khmer Rouge as a buffer between its forces and the Vietnamese
army in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
