<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Robbery     04-18 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Robbery,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robbers Commit Suicide After Standoff, One Surrenders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bank robbers committed
suicide and a fourth surrendered after their hostage escaped from a
plane used in a getaway attempt, officials in northeastern Brazil
said Tuesday.
   A fifth robber committed suicide Saturday, a day after the drama
began, police said. Officials said the robbers had made a pact to
commit suicide if their crime failed.
   The episode that ended Monday night at Val-de-Caes airport in
the Amazon River city of Belem began Friday when five gunmen tried
to rob a bank in Acu, 1,860 miles northwest of Rio, authorities
said.
   When police arrived, the gunmen took five hostages and demanded
a plane and pilots to make their escape with $24,674 in cash.
   Police gave them a Brazilian-made 19-seat Bandeirantes, and the
robbers released all their hostages except one.
   The subsequent chase covered more than 1,200 miles across
northern Brazil.
   On Saturday, the robbers and their hostage flew to Belem, 2,140
miles northwest of Rio, where they released the pilot and co-pilot.
   When negotiations with police stalled, one of the robbers shot
himself. His body was left on the runway and taken to a morgue.
   On Monday, the Roman Catholic archbiship of Belem, the Most.
Rev. Alberto Ramos, met with the robbers and offered to take the
place of Fonseca as hostage. The gunmen refused.
   Police said hostage Hudson Fonseca, manager of the Northeastern
Bank of Brazil in Acu, slipped away from his captors Monday night.
The robbers had tried unsuccessfully to negotiate for a new
aircraft to replace the plane they were given earlier, authorities
said.
   ``They were exhausted and desperate,'' federal police
spokeswoman Myrtes Nabuco de Oliveira Pontes said by telephone.
``When the police refused to meet their demands for a new plane,
they began tearing the aircraft apart.''
   Teams of police sharpshooters surrounded the commuter plane,
which was parked on a landing strip.
   However, three robbers came down the plane's stairway pointing
pistols at their own heads shortly after the hostage escaped and
shot themselves without warning, federal police agent Fernando
Cesar said.
   A suspect remaining in the plane then called out for a
cigarette, which a police officer outside offered to him, the agent
said. When the suspect came out for it, authorities grabbed him and
took him into custody, he said.
   News reports said officials had stormed the plane, but officials
denied using force.
</TEXT>
