<DOCNO> AP890418-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MeterThieves     04-18 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meter Thieves,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oakland Police Target Parking Meter Thieves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city is considering a plan to put
alarms or exploding dye packs inside its parking meters to stop
vandals who have smashed or stolen half of them in the past nine
months, officials said Tuesday.
   Merchants are angry because motorists ignore parking
restrictions when the meters don't work, and customers are
discouraged by fewer open parking spaces.
   ``This meter problem is a really frustrating situation that's
costing the city a lot of money, and what's odd is that the thieves
are not getting much for their efforts,'' said Public Works
Director Terry Roberts.
   Vandals who bash or steal the meters can hope at best to get $20
for their efforts. In many cases they get only a few dollars, or a
few cents if they can't pry open the vault-like coin containers,
Roberts said.
   But more than 4,000 of the city's 8,500 parking meters have been
bashed in, broken open or ripped right out of the ground and carted
off. Police find the twisted metal carcasses strewn under freeway
underpasses and in parks.
   ``It seems people popped a few tops off the meters some months
ago and found it was easier than they thought and, of course, the
word spread,'' Roberts said.
   About 75 people have been arrested in the parking meter
bashings. Police have vowed to seek felony theft charges in as many
cases as possible, said Lt. Larry Eade.
   ``We've arrested people who have filled up shopping carts with
the meters, then covered them up with their belongings,'' Eade said.
   The city, with a population of about 350,000, has lost about
$450,000 in revenue because of damaged meters. It will cost
$840,000 to replace 7,000 of the old meters with a $120
tamper-resistant version, officials said.
   Some of the new, heavy-duty meters are in place, but they are
not immune to vandalism either.
   Thieves sometimes rip out the new machines, take them to
secluded locations and bash them open, police said.
   The city plans to allocate $12,000 for overtime to fund an
undercover police squad looking into the problem, and may put
alarms or exploding colored dye packs in meters, said Yvonne
Garcia, chief of staff to Mayor Lionel Wilson.
   ``If these people are causing all these problems just for a few
nickles and dimes, I think they've got to be pretty stupid,'' said
Al Federas of Lake Shore Travel, one of the merchants who
complained about the thefts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
