<DOCNO> AP890418-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Stanford-FusionTest     04-18 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stanford-Fusion Test,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientist Says Test Proves Utah Fusion Experiment Not Chemical Reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scientist said Tuesday a controlled,
simultaneous test of a University of Utah chemist's claim to have
achieved nuclear fusion in a jar of water proved the energy
produced did not come from a chemical reaction.
   Robert Huggins, Stanford University professor of material
sciences, said his experiment using palladium electrodes in jars of
heavy water and plain water in a picnic basket produced energy that
may have resulted from fusion.
   Huggins said he can't be sure the energy is from fusion, but is
certain it is not from a chemical reaction, as some other
scientists have speculated. He suggested the energy may result from
a different type of fusion than is commonly known.
   He said he ran five experiments over two weeks, using a jar of
heavy water, or deuterium oxide, and a jar of plain water. If the
experiments produced the same results, he said, it would indicate
the energy was not from fusion.
   Instead, he found much higher temperatures from the deuterium,
which meant the energy probably was not a chemical reaction because
there is no essential chemical difference between the two kinds of
water.
   ``There are significant thermal differences between the
deuterium and the hydrogen (plain water) system,'' he said. ``We
don't say what it is.''
   The discovery of cold fusion was announced March 23 by
University of Utah chemistry professor Stanley Pons and British
colleague Martin Fleischmann.
   Pons, who said Monday further experiments with heavy water and a
palladum electrode yielded even more energy and run more
efficiently, noted the apparent cold fusion discovery had been
partly verified by more than 60 university and private laboratories.
   Of the more than 60 other experimenters, Pons said none has
reported observing both the production of neutrons and the high
level of heat he and Fleischmann produced.
   Neutrons are a tell-tale sign of fusion, the process powering
the sun, in which tremendous amounts of energy are released when
the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse.
   Scientists say that if fusion can be created as easily as Pons
and Fleischmann claim, it could be a relatively inexpensive and
virtually inexhaustible energy source.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NH-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0690 04-18 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NH-Abortion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0690,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Senate Votes To Repeal Anti-Abortion Laws</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with governor personally opposing abortion,
House vote on measure, 14 other states with similar anti-abortion laws;
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate voted 13-11 on Tuesday to
repeal three 1848 laws making abortion a crime.
   The bill, passed by the House on March 23, now goes to Gov. Judd
Gregg, who has not said whether he will sign it. Gregg has said he
personally opposes abortion.
   The laws have not been enforced since the 1973 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling legalizing abortion.
   The swing vote in the Senate was Democrat James St. Jean, who
said abortion is a decision for a woman to make in accordance with
her own religious beliefs.
   Fourteen other states have old anti-abortion laws on the books
that are unenforceable because of the Roe vs. Wade decision, but
there has been debate over whether they could take effect if the
high court overturned the decision.
   The states are Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas, Connecticut,
Delaware, Idaho, Illinois, Louisiana, Michigan, Mississippi,
Oklahoma, South Dakota, West Virginia and Wisconsin.
   The Supreme Court plans to hear arguments April 26 in a key
abortion-rights case from Missouri in which the justices are being
asked to overturn or substantially limit their landmark 1973
decision.
</TEXT>
