<FIRST>r w AM-OilResearch     04-18 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Research,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>$6 Million Cleanup Research Program Unveiled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department announced a joint $6
million, three-year research program with the petroleum industry
Tuesday to develop better recovery and cleanup equipment and
methods for large oil spills.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr. said the department would
pay for half of the program, with the American Petroleum Institute
paying for the other half. The department's current budget for such
research is less than $150,000.
   ``In the wake of the Exxon Valdez accident, we must make sure
that our oil spill contingency plans are thoroughly re-examined to
meet our responsibility for protecting the environment,'' said
Lujan.
   He made the announcement after meeting for about 20 minutes with
Richard Marro, chairman of Amoco and chairman of the American
Petroleum Institute, and with Charles DiBona, president of the
industry organization.
   Lujan said he was flying to Alaska on Wednesday for a four-day
tour of areas affected by the March 24 spill from the Exxon tanker
that has caused environmental havoc in Prince William Sound and
along Alaska's southern coastline.
   Meanwhile, the department said it was planning to step up
inspections at offshore oil drilling platforms to check whether the
industry ``is prepared to respond'' to an oil spill emergency. A
report on the inspections is to be presented to Lujan late next
month.
   The $6 million research effort over three years is aimed at
developing and field testing various methods and technology for
dealing with massive spills. Lujan has described the containment
equipment in Alaska at the time of the Exxon spill as little more
than ``tinker-toys'' that would not have contained the spill even
if it had been deployed rapidly.
   In Alaska, said Lujan, oil containment booms frequently broke
from the force of the waves and oil syphoning equipment was far too
slow to do much good.
   Department officials said the joint Interior-industry study will
involve laboratory and field testing of various oil-burning
techniques, new high-speed steerable booms, and more advanced
skimmer technology for clearing oil from ice-laden waters.
   Various chemicals, some of which are supposed to disperse oil
while others are designed to keep it together, also will be tested
under the program, the officials said.
   Marro said that while the industry has conducted research into
oil spill recovery technology for years ``there are lessons to be
learned'' from the Alaskan spill.
   He suggested the industry still does not know all it should
about how best to anticipate oil movement in a cold-water
environment and, for example, once new equipment becomes available
it remains unclear how it should be deployed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
