<FIRST>u w AM-BaseClosings 2ndLd-Writethru a0727 04-18 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0727,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Endorses Closing Recommendations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 15th graf pvs, ``The whole, with all but
a dozen yes votes coming from lawmakers in Ill., Calif., and N.J.; inserts
2 grafs after 16th graf pvs, ``Obsolete bases, with Schroeder quote; adds
6 grafs with names of those voting for resolution and those abstaining.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to back
a plan to close 86 military bases and scale back five more despite
complaints that the move will not save as much as advocates had
promised.
   By a vote of 381-43, the House rejected a resolution to
disapprove the recommendations of the Commission on Base
Realignment and Closure, giving the green light for Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney to follow through on the panel's proposals
beginning in January.
   ``It is incumbent upon all of us to make sure this base closing
list is implemented,'' the chairman of the House Armed Services
Chairman, Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said moments before the vote.
   The commission's recommendations affect a total of 145 domestic
military installations by closing some, reducing the operations of
others and changing the missions of additional bases.
   The law establishing the commission, the Base Closure and
Realignment Act, requires that, once approved by the secretary of
defense, the commission's recommendations proceed unless both
houses of Congress vote to disapprove them, in which case none of
the proposals would take effect.
   The House action means the changes proposed by the commission
will proceed.
   In debate before the vote, opponents of the move said it would
not save as much money as the commission projected.
   ``This list simply does not save money,'' said Rep. Jim Saxton,
R-N.J.
   He was jointed by representatives from Illinois and California
in saying that the plan would not save $694 million in the first
year, or $5.6 billion over 20 years, as the commission projected.
   ``In terms of savings, I don't believe they're there. In terms
of expenditures, I believe thy're underestimated,'' said Saxton,
who opposes the closing of Fort Dix in his home state.
   Saxton cited a congressional report that said the savings in
closing Fort Dix had been overestimated by $20 million.
   The New Jersey representative also noted that a report by the
General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress, had
found that the commission used incorrect data in its analysis of
Army training centers, including Fort Dix.
   ``Had accurate data been used, Fort Dix would hae been ranked
first,'' Saxton said.
   Rep. Terry Bruce, D-Ill., said the estimated savings rely on
major defense policy changes, including reductions in personnel,
and not on the closing and realigning of bases.
   ``The whole tone of the commission was based on manipulating
data, changing ratings, fudging dollar figures and misleading both
Congress and the public,'' Bruce said.
   All but a dozen of the votes for the resolution came from
representatives from Illinois, California and New Jersey. Among the
plan's supporters, Rep. Ronald Machtley, R-R.I., argued that it was
``time to get serious about deficit reduction.''
   ``Obsolete bases have drained our resources. ... The
recommendations are the only viable option for cutting expenditures
of funds,'' he said.
   Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee, said that although the GAO had found some
errors in the commission's work, the bottom line was still the
savings.
   ``Maybe we don't save as much money on some of the bases, maybe
we disagreed with the models that was used, but they never said on
one of these bases that it was going to cost money to close them if
you look at it over a six-year period,'' Schroeder said.
   Last month, the Armed Services Committee voted 43-4 to support
the commission report.
   Schroeder also said that she and Rep. Brian Donnelly, D-Mass.,
will introduce legislation next week to close and realign bases
overseas.
   Schroeder said that total basing costs overseas have increased
nearly 500 percent since 1974 and that leaving those installations
out of the domestic base closure bill was a ``glaring omission.''
   ``Our allies have insisted on higher and higher payments for the
permission to operate bases on their soil,'' Schroeder said. ``In
essence we are being forced to pay more for the privilege of
defending our allies _ $2 billion a year, up from $200 million in
1974.''
   Twenty-six Democrats and 17 Republicans voted for the resolution
while 229 Democrats and 152 Republicans voted against it. Four
Democrats and five Republicans did not vote.
   Voting for the resolution were Reps. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz.; Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif.; George E. Brown Jr., D-Calif.; Matthew G.
Martinez, D-Calif.; Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.; Edward Roybal,
D-Calif.; Jerry Lewis, R-Calif.; Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo.;
Frank Annunzio, D-Ill.; Terry Bruce, D-Ill.; Jerry Costello,
D-Ill.; Richard Durbin, D-Ill., and Lane Evans, D-Ill.
   Also in favor of the measure were Reps. William Lipinski,
D-Ill.; Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.; George Sangmeister, D-Ill.; Gus
Savage, D-Ill.; Philip Crane, R-Ill.; Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.; Henry
Hyde, R-Ill.; Ed Madigan, R-Ill.; Bob Michel, R-Ill.; John Edward
Porter, R-Ill.; Lee Hamilton, D-Ind.; Frank McCloskey, D-Ind.; Carl
Perkins, D-Ky., and Harold Rogers, R-Ky.
   Others were Reps. James Hayes, D-La.; Olympia Snowe, R-Maine;
Helen Bentley, R-Md.; Brian Donnelly, D-Mass.; Joe Kennedy,
D-Mass.; James Florio, D-N.J.; William Hughes, D-N.J.; Frank
Palone, D-N.J.; Robert Roe, D-N.J.; Jim Courter, R-N.J.; Dean
Gallo, R-N.J.; Matthew Rinaldo, R-N.J.; Marge Roukema, R-N.J.; Jim
Saxton, R-N.J.; Christopher Smith, R-N.J., and Jack Brooks, D-Texas.
   Not voting on the resolution were Reps. Claude Pepper, D-Fla.;
Bob Whittaker, R-Kan.; Robert Davis, R-Mich.; Joe Kolter, D-Pa.;
Claudine Schneider, R-R.I.; Greg Laughlin, D-Texas; Rick Boucher,
D-Va.; James Quillen, R-Tenn., and Rod Chandler, R-Wash.
   As is the custom, House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, did not
vote.
</TEXT>
