<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-US     04-18 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-US,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland Acknowledges Bush's Aid Initiative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist government said Tuesday that
President Bush's economic aid plan for Poland is ``a step in the
right direction after years of restrictions and limitations.''
   But deputy government spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski strongly
disagreed with Bush's assessment that ``communism is fading.''
   ``Communism is not falling, and we will try to prove this,'' he
told a news conference.
   ``Developments in Poland, which have made the U.S.
administration change its stance toward Poland, undeniably testify
to the fact that we are moving forward and create new hopes.''
   Bush on Monday disclosed economic incentives to reward Poland
for steps toward democracy and to encourage further political and
economic reforms.
   The package included asking Congress to lower tariffs on
selected Polish imports under the generalized system of
preferences, and seeking congressional approval of U.S.-guaranteed
loans to stimulate private investment in Poland.
   Bush also announced a new U.S. willingness to work with other
Western financial leaders to help Poland deal with its $38 billion
foreign debt.
   Taken together, the moves could work to Poland's economic
advantage to the tune of more than $1 billion.
   ``The Polish government interprets this statement (Bush's) as a
step in the right direction after years of restrictions and
limitations,'' Rykowski said.
   He said Poland would be able to evaluate the package fully on
``the basis of concrete results.''
   If fully implemented, the U.S. package would largely reverse
economic sanctions taken against the government in 1981-82 after it
imposed martial law and banned Solidarity.
   A Warsaw court restored the independent trade union's legal
status Monday in accord with an agreement reached April 5 between
communist authorities and the opposition on economic and political
reform.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa praised Bush for his action when
he arrived in Warsaw Monday night from Gdansk.
   ``Bush is a great man and he knows the Polish situation very
well,'' Walesa told reporters. He called the U.S. aid proposal
``quite large.''
</TEXT>
