<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Israel     04-18 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Israel,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Meets with Hungarian Leader, Mediation Role Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
met Tuesday with Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz, and Hungary
announced it has assumed a mediating role in the Middle East.
   Shamir's sudden, unannounced trip raised speculation in Israel
that the two countries were about to restore diplomatic ties.
Hungary broke ties with Israel during the 1967 Middle East war.
   Shamir told the official MTI news agency shortly before his
departure that he hoped Israel and Hungary would establish normal
diplomatic relations ``in the very near future.''
   ``But I can't give any definite date,'' MTI quoted him as saying.
   Hungarian officials did not disclose the purpose of Shamir's
two-day visit, nor did they give details on his meeting with Grosz.
   However, the state news agency MTI quoted Foreign Ministry
spokesman Istvan Komoroczki as saying, ``Hungary has agreed to act
as a mediator and will try to persuade all parties concerned in the
Middle East crisis to sit down to the negotiating table.''
   Israeli radio reports also said Shamir was discussing an East
bloc role in Mideast peace efforts.
   The reports did not elaborate, but Hungary may be taking over a
role long attributed to President Nicolae Ceausescu of Romania.
   Ceausescu leads the only East bloc country that did not sever
relations with Israel during the 1967 Middle East war. However,
many countries now shun Romania because of its human rights record.
   Hungarian Premier Miklos Nemeth has said he expects full
diplomatic relations to be restored between Hungary and Israel by
June.
   Hungary is seeking removal of trade barriers imposed by Israel,
Kovacs told MTI. The agency said the Israelis have stressed they
extend trade preferences only to countries with which they have
full diplomatic ties.
</TEXT>
