<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-SoccerDeaths     04-18 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Soccer Deaths,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Dozens Have Died in Soviet Stadium Panics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stadium Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has experienced at least three
fatal stadium panics similar to the one that took 95 lives in
England last weekend, a Soviet newspaper reported Tuesday.
   Thousands of fans were allowed to enter an already crowded
standing-room area of the Sheffield stadium on Saturday, and
spectators were trampled or crushed against a fence.
   Sovietsky Sport said dozens of people died in Moscow's Lenin
Stadium on Oct. 21, 1982, during a game between Spartak Moscow and
Haarlem of Holland. It said cries of horror were heard when
``dozens of people died under the heels of thousands.''
   Authorities would not say at the time whether anyone was killed
or injured. Unofficial sources said a woman fell into a narrow
passageway and people trying to help her were trampled by the crowd.
   The article in Sovietsky Sport also said some boys died in a
crush at a junior hockey match between the Soviet Union and Canada
in Moscow's sports palace in 1975, but did not say how many.
   People also were killed in Krasnoyarsk in Siberia in 1982 at the
opening ceremony of the Spartakiad, a national winter sports
festival, it said.
