<FIRST>r w AM-Lewis-Drugs     04-18 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lewis-Drugs,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Friend Linked to Drug Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Lewis, an old friend of Mayor Marion
Barry, has had dealings with a man arrested as part of a major drug
crackdown in the nation's capital, according to sources familiar
with an ongoing probe into the drug ring.
   Investigators have gathered information that Lewis, already
under indictment on drug charges in separate cases in the District
of Columbia and the Virgin Islands, has dealt with Rayful Edmond
III, the alleged leader of a powerful local drug ring.
   However, Lewis and Edmond did not deal drugs together, the
sources said. Instead, Lewis may have purchased drugs from Edmond
or his partners when he traveled to Washington on several occasions
during the past year, the sources said.
   Edmond, 24, was arrested along with 16 other persons over the
weekend in what U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens called the ``most
significant'' crackdown on illegal drugs ever in the city.
   Lewis was indicted last Thursday on seven counts of perjury and
three counts of cocaine possession, stemming from an investigation
into Barry's visits to Lewis' hotel room last December.
   Lewis, a former District of Columbia and Virgin Islands
government employee, was charged with lying to a federal grand jury
about whether he possessed cocaine on Dec. 22, on a day on which
Barry visited him. Lewis is also charged with lying about using
cocaine with two separate individuals on Dec. 21, a day on which
Barry twice visited him.
   The federal probe began after city police on Dec. 22 were
inexplicably called off an attempt to make an undercover drug
purchase from Lewis, 48, after Barry showed up at his hotel room.
Barry has acknowledged contacting police officials looking into the
affair but has said he was only trying to speed up the probe.
   Lewis also went on trial Monday in the Virgin Islands on charges
he attempted to sell cocaine to undercover FBI agents during March.
   Stephens said Edmond's cartel, made up mostly of family members,
may have been responsible for up to 25 percent of the cocaine sold
in Washington, as well as a number of drug-related murders.
   Edmond and eight other accused members of the ring are being
held without bond after hearings Monday before a U.S. magistrate.
Seven other adults and a juvenile were also arrested on Saturday in
a sweep that followed a two-year investigation.
   Stephens said the case remains open, but wouldn't say if or when
he expects to make more arrests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
