<FIRST>r w AM-HousingSuit     04-18 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Suit,1st ld-writethru, a0715,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS day of week in lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first lawsuit filed under a new law
prohibiting housing discrimination against families with children
was filed Tuesday against the owners of a New Jersey apartment
complex.
   The suit, filed by the Justice Department's civil rights
division, charges that LaFonge Associates violated the recently
amended Fair Housing Act by refusing to rent a one-bedroom
apartment to a single parent and a child.
   Amendments to the Fair Housing Act that were enacted by Congress
last year housing discrimination against people with handicaps and
those with children. Retirement communities with special facilities
for elderly people are exempt from the law.
   The suit charged that LaFonge Associates ``engaged in a pattern
of practice of discrimination against persons on the basis of
familial status in the rental of dwellings .''
   The company, which owns Somerset Mews Apartments in Franklin
Township of Somerset County, N.J., was accused of telling
prospective tenants that it preferred to families without children.
   The Justice Department, acting on a complaint by the Housing
Coalition of Middlesex County of New Brunswick, sought an
injunction to force the company to stop the alleged discriminatory
practices.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in New Jersey, also seeks
compensatory damages and a civil penalty ``in order to vindicate
the public interest.''
</TEXT>
