<FIRST>r i AM-Indonesia-Capsize     04-18 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indonesia-Capsize,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indonesian Ship Capsize Leaves Scores of Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship capsized in a storm, leaving at
least two people dead and scores missing, the official Antara news
agency reported Tuesday.
   A police report said at least 26 were missing after the ship
capsized Saturday off Ambon Island in Indonesia's eastern Maluku
province.
   Antara said the small vessel Super Star was overcrowded with 142
passengers when it was caught in a storm and huge waves nine miles
off Hitu, Ambon, about 1,440 miles east of the capital, Jakarta.
   The agency said 62 people survived and two bodies were found,
which would leave 78 people not accounted for.
   Police Sgt. Laode Sakili said in Ambon that the 30-ton Super
Star had 74 people aboard, including seven crew, and that 26 people
were missing and two bodies were recovered after the craft
overturned on its way from Piru on Seram Island to Hitu. He said 46
people survived.
   Sakili said his latest report was received Monday from the
scene, and he could not confirm the Antara account.
   Antara said Capt. Wani Tanalessy sent distress signals, but the
first rescuers did not reach the scene until midnight, more than 11
hours after the ship sank.
</TEXT>
