<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-18 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms And Rain Along Front From Plains To Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Tuesday over parts of the southern
Plains and Virginia, and snow fell around the south end of Lake
Michigan.
   Thunderstorms developed in the afternoon over sections of
Oklahoma and Arkansas. In northwestern Arkansas, a thunderstorm
produced hail as big as marbles in Madison County.
   Showers were scattered from Illinois to West Virginia.
   Around the southern end of Lake Michigan, snow was occasionally
mixed with rain at Chicago in the morning, and snow continued over
parts of northern Indiana and southern Michigan and the northwest
corner of Ohio in the afternoon. Visibility dropped to a half-mile
in moderate snow at South Bend, Ind.
   The showers and thunderstorms were produced by a frontal system
that extended from New England to Kentucky and the southern Plains,
separating warm weather over the mid-Atlantic Coast states and the
Southeast from cool air prevailing over the north-central states.
   The contrast across the front was especially noticeable in
Indiana. At 2 p.m. EDT, while the snow was falling at South Bend
with a temperature of 34 degrees, 300 miles away at Evansville in
the state's southwestern corner it was 73 degrees.
   North of the front, temperatures were only in the 40s and 50s
from the Great Lakes to the northern and central Plains.
   Thunderstorms also developed during the afternoon over the Blue
Ridge mountains of western Virginia, with small hail reported in
the Shenandoah Valley.
   Scattered showers also were reported over southeastern Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 95 at Gila Bend, Ariz. Tuesday's
low in the 48 contiguous states was 19 degrees at Marquette, Mich.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over Florida, and from North Carolina to the southern Appalachians,
the central Gulf Coast states and southeastern Texas. Showers were
forecast over parts of New York state and New England, especially
during the morning. Scattered rain was forecast across the Pacific
Northwest.
   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted from the upper
Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes region to New England; in
the 80s from the southern Atlantic Coast states across the Gulf
Coast states to much of Texas and New Mexico, and over parts of
Colorado, Utah, southern Nevada and interior California; in the 90s
to near 100 degrees in the desert Southwest; and in the 60s and 70s
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
