<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SubmarineCuts     04-18 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Submarine Cuts,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Considering Cutting Both Attack Subs From Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon is considering the elimination of
both nuclear-powered attack submarines from the 1990 budget, two
congressmen said Tuesday.
   Reps. John G. Rowland, R-Conn., and Herbert H. Bateman, R-Va.,
said they have learned that Defense Department officials were
taking a serious look at eliminating the SSN-688 attack submarines,
which are the last two of the Los Angeles class series the Pentagon
planned to order.
   The proposal was revealed at a House Armed Services seapower
subcommittee hearing during which the lawmakers urged Navy
officials to fight to keep the submarines. The congressmen
represent the home states of the two manufacturers of the Los
Angeles-class subs _ the Electric Boat Division of General Dynamics
Corp. in Groton, Conn., and the Newport News (Va.) Shipbuilding Co.
   Vice Adm. William D. Smith, deputy chief of naval operations,
pledged his support for the submarines. He noted that elimination
of the submarines would mean that this would be the first year the
United States had not ordered an attack submarine since 1953.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is expected to annouce next week
plans to cut $6.4 billion from the 1990 budget proposed by
President Reagan. Elimination of the two Los Angeles class subs
would save about $1.5 billion.
   In an interview after the hearing, Rowland said proponents of
the submarine cuts inside the Pentagon are arguing the subs are
expendable since they are the last in the Los Angeles-class series.
   The Navy ordered its first SSN-21 Seawolf submarine, which will
replace the Los Angeles-class subs, last year from Electric Boat.
No Seawolfs were included in the 1990 budget, but two are expected
to be purchased the following fiscal year.
   Rowland and Bateman argued that the United States cannot afford
to eliminate two attack submarines in light of advances in Soviet
submarine technology and production.
   The news of the possible sub cuts came as Navy officials
defended the Pentagon's submarine program and its anti-submarine
warfare technology, which have come under intense scrutiny since an
indepenent study last month warned that recent major advances in
submarine quieting by the Soviets have rendered traditional
detection methods close to obsolete.
   Following the hearing, Rowland sent a telegram to Cheney urging
him to retain the Los Angeles class submarines.
   ``These two 688 submarines are state-of-art and are needed to
assure U.S. qualitative superiority over Soviet submarines force.
Cutting two 688s from budget makes little sense in view of Soviet
(anti-submarine warfare) advances,'' Rowland wrote.
</TEXT>
