<FIRST>u a AM-CrackBait 1stLd-Writethru a0650 04-18 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Bait, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0650,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Office Makes Own Crack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The sheriff's ...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
previous use of homemade crack by sheriff's department.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the crack cocaine sold on
Broward County streets was processed not in dark labs in
crime-ridden neighborhoods, but on the seventh floor of the county
courthouse.
   The sheriff's office has been turning cocaine into the purified,
smokable form because it can't get enough to supply undercover
officers setting up street sweeps to arrest buyers.
   Defense attorneys say that, at best, the sheriff's office is
ethically wrong to make crack, also known as rock.
   A spokesman for Broward Sheriff Nick Navarro, who seems to
thrive on publicity and controversy, said Tuesday the sheriff was
pleased with the operation's results.
   ``With all this publicity, I suppose all the attorneys will be
keenly aware of it,'' said spokesman Jim Leljedal. ``We believe our
cases will stand up.''
   Although the sheriff's office had believed it was the first in
the nation to make its own crack, the Polk County sheriff's
department last June produced 11 ounces of crack cocaine for
undercover use.
   ``I've never heard of that in my whole life before,'' said Con
Dougherty, spokesman for the Drug Enforcement Administration in
Washington.
   ``We'd like to point out that none of this cocaine is going out
on the streets,'' said Leljedal, adding that besides providing
undercover officers with crack for their sweeps, the program
ensures that buyers are arrested in possession of real cocaine.
   Before going into court, the sheriff's office must prove that
the purchased material is the illegal substance, a problem because
sales of bogus crack are common, Leljedal said.
   He also rejected suggestions of entrapment, saying: ``These are
people who went out on the street to buy crack. They're addicts.''
   Some attorneys have different views.
   ``I think there's something sick about this whole system where
the police make the product, sell the product and arrest people for
buying the product,'' Broward Public Defender Alan Schreiber told
the Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel in a story published Tuesday.
   The sheriff's chemist, who has made enough crack to sell for a
total $20,000 on the street, said it makes his job easier because
the drug usually stays inside cellophane bags during the sale and
arrest, so he can identify it without having to analyze it
chemically before going into court.
   Chemist Randy Hilliard uses impounded cocaine to refine into
crack, and made his first batch in February from 2.2 pounds of
seized cocaine. He noted that use of confiscated drugs for sting
operations isn't unusual.
   The sheriff's office made 2,300 crack-related arrests in the
first three months of this year. Leljedal didn't have precise
figures for 1988 arrests, but Navarro _ who also heads a statewide
anti-crack task force _ has said his anti-crack operations have
been a national model.
   Navarro's department is featured in the Fox TV network's
real-life series ``Cops'' and allowed Geraldo Rivera to participate
in an undercover operation for a television special, and his
prediliction for getting on the local evening news led a Miami
Herald columnist to dub the show ``Nick at Nite.''
   Navarro, re-elected by a landslide last November to a second
four-year term, says his diligent pursuit of crack has strong
community support.
   ``I can tell you, you ask the father or mother of any kid who's
on crack cocaine if they have any reservations and see what they
tell you. They have none,'' Navarro said of his latest move.
   Navarro twice has been ordered into court by judges who
threatened him with contempt citations. Most recently, a federal
judge complained about his use of tents to house overflow inmates.
Other critics have said the crack sweeps overburden courts and
jails and do little to provide a lasting solution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HoffmanMemorial 2ndLd-Writethru a0677 04-18 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoffman Memorial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0677,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial for Abbie Hoffman To Begin With Peace March</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Hoffman death ruled a suicide;
Picks up 4th graf, `In the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends famous and obscure are headed to
this industrial city to mourn native son Abbie Hoffman, whose
memorial service Wednesday starts with a peace march in the city
where his activism began.
   Hoffman, 52, was found dead on April 12 at his home in New Hope,
Pa., and his body has been cremated. A coroner said Tuesday that
Hoffman committed suicide by swallowing the drug phenobarbitl mixed
with alcohol.
   But his brother, Jack Hoffman, insisted that the death was
accidental.
   ``I just think he took a little too many and he took a good slug
of booze,'' he said. ``My brother had a very strong love and
affection for me and he wouldn't have left me alone like this.''
   The residue of about 150 pills and alcohol were found in his
system.
   ``Abbie, as many of you know, was somewhat careless with pills
and we always warned him about this kind of thing,'' said Jack
Hoffman, who managed his brother's finances.
   In the past week, newspapers have editorialized about Hoffman's
antics, such as burning money at the New York Stock Exchange and
naming his book ``Steal This Book.''
   Vandals last weekend spray-painted ``steal this courthouse'' on
a building where he was tried with Amy Carter, daughter of former
President Carter, for their arrests during a 1986 anti-CIA
demonstration.
   His family has been flooded with letters, telegrams and
condolence calls from entertainers, the Carter family, even foreign
embassies, his brother said. ``I'm not going to say which,'' he
said. ``Let's just say some of our NATO friends.''
   In keeping with Hoffman's career, his family has planned a noon
peace march Wednesday from his mother's house to Temple Emanuel,
which he attended as a child and where a memorial service will be
held.
   ``I want it to be a celebration,'' Hoffman said. ``I want
everybody to be singing and swinging and swaying.''
   Folk singer Pete Seeger volunteered to lead the march and sing
protest songs, he said.
   Jack Hoffman said his brother died nearly broke, despite his
book contracts and success on the lecture circuit. ``He gave just
about everything away,'' he said. ``He didn't die with a Rolex. He
died with a full heart.''
   Besides his brother and mother, Hoffman leaves a sister,
Phyllis; three children from his two marriages; and his long-time
companion, Johanna Lawrenson. Hoffman's ashes were given to Ms.
Lawrenson, his brother said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
