<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Teachers     04-18 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Teachers,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Continue Strike For Higher Pay, Against Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The education secretary summoned leaders of a
dissident teachers movement and the government-backed union Tuesday
in an attempt to resolve a teacher's strike for higher pay and the
removal of corrupt union chiefs.
   Defying government warning, thousands of Mexico's public school
teachers cut classes for a second day to push for a 100 percent pay
increase and greater democracy in their union, which with 1.1
million members is the largest in Mexico and one of the biggest in
Latin America.
   Before dawn, Education Secretary Manuel Bartlett summoned
leaders of the National Education Workers' Coordinate, a dissident
group within the National Education Workers Union, and the
government-backed union leadership, a strike activist said on
condition of anonymity.
   The coordinate has rejected a government offer to increase pay
by 10 percent and benefits by 18 percent. Teachers earn about
$147.50 a month after taxes.
   Bartlett warned on national television late Monday that striking
teachers could face disciplinary action if they didn't return to
their jobs.
   He said teachers in the federal school system will receive a net
salary increase of 20 percent once an umbrella 10 percent increase
for state and federal teachers goes into efect in May.
   ``To attend to the teachers' demands above what is now possible
would mean a serious financial mess for the economic course of the
country,'' the department said in an advertisement published
Tuesday in Mexico City newspapers.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari acknowledges that teachers
are badly underpaid, but says his hard-pressed government cannot
afford to double salaries.
   ``This is a fight for dignity. This is a fight against hunger,''
said Maria del Carmen Moctezuma, 45, as she sat inside the empty
Victor Maria Flores primary school she directs. ``We support the
strike and won't abandon the fight to improve our economic
condition,'' she said.
   Silvestre Gomez Sotelo, a 42-year-old teacher at the school,
called the government's wage offer ``a slap in the face.''
   ``I invite the education secretary to try living on our
salary,'' Gomez said.
   The dissidents claimed the support of about 500,000 of Mexico's
1.1 million public school teachers when the walkout began Monday.
The figure was not confirmed by the Education Department.
   ``Our movement is a success. Today we expect the solidarity of
90 percent of teachers across the country,'' coordinate leader
Leonardo Gonzalez Monter said in a telephone interview.
   Gonzalez said about 3 million students in Mexico City and the
southern states of Chiapas and Oaxaca skipped classes Tuesday.
   According to government figures, about 25.4 million students are
in the national public school system at all levels. Private schools
were not affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
