<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugAmnesty     04-18 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Amnesty,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Offers Drug Users a Deal, Turn in a Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SNOW HILL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a limited time only, drug users in
Maryland's Worcester County can avoid prosecution by kicking the
habit and turning in their suppliers.
   An ad running in several weekly newspapers offers amnesty from
prosecution until May 15 and includes a phone number to the
county's special narcotics team. The ads first appeared last
Wednesday and Thursday.
   ``On Friday, we got so many phone calls we had to advise the
people who were calling to call back this week because we couldn't
process them all,'' State's Attorney B. Randall Coates said Tuesday.
   Coates, who signed the ad, wouldn't say how many people tried to
take advantage, but said it was substantially more than a dozen.
   When drug users call, authorities question them to decide
whether they are qualified for the program. Those who are are asked
to arrange a drug purchase from their dealer with an undercover
officer present, Coates said.
   ``Once we have that, we arrest the seller and give immunity to
the user,'' Coates said. The immunity is only good for the last
known drug violation that has gone unprosecuted.
   Users will be referred to the county's drug program.
   The offer does not does not apply to drug dealers, smugglers or
drug-operation financiers, the ad says. However,those offenders can
also make a deal by cooperating with authorities.
   Coates said the amnesty idea has proven effective for collecting
revenue from tax cheaters in Maryland and elsewhere, so he decided
to try it to help curb the drug trade.
   ``The purpose of the ad is to give those who do have a problem,
and want help, the opportunity to come forward and get the help
they need,'' he said.
   ``The other purpose of the ad is to make it clear to those who
are selling or smuggling in this county ... that we are serious
about prosecuting them and in fact, they cannot trust anybody, let
alone law enforcement.
   ``We are hoping they will not want to deal in Worcester County
because they can get turned in by the people they are selling to,''
Coates said. ``It's a psychological war as well as a prosecution
war.''
   Worcester, on the lower Eastern Shore, contains Ocean City,
Maryland's most popular resort. Ocean City's off-season population
of about 5,000 regularly swells to 300,000 on summer weekends,
providing another incentive for getting local dealers off the
streets before the vacation season begins.
   State Attorney General J. Joseph Curran called the program ``a
novel idea.''
   ``What it's doing is making people in the drug network nervous
and that's good from a law enforcement standpoint,'' Curran said.
``And it's letting them know that after May 15, nothing will be
tolerated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
