<HEAD>Cuban MiG-21 Crashes into Houses; Pilot Killed, Six Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, identifying pilot, UPDATING number hurt. No
pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban air force MiG-21 jet fighter on a
training mission crashed into three houses in Holguin, eastern
Cuba, on Tuesday, killing the pilot and injuring six people on the
ground, Cuban news reports said.
   The Soviet-made, single-seat jet crashed near a public school at
9 a.m. in the Loma de la Cruz working-class neighborhood,
destroying one house and badly damaging at least two, the Cuban
news agency Prensa Latina quoted airport officials as saying.
Holguin lies 475 miles east of Havana, the capital.
   Prensa Latina, monitored in Mexico City, identified the pilot as
Lt. Rafael Varona Nieves, 22. It said at least one civilian was in
intensive care with burns.
   The report gave no indication as to why the jet crashed. Prensa
Latina quoted a witness as saying the plane was flying ``like it
was riding a wave, moving constantly at low altitude with its
lights on'' just before it hit.
