<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     04-18 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dogs Search Roadsides For Missing Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police dogs began searching woods and
fields bordering 25 miles of road Tuesday for the bodies of two
young women missing and feared to be the victims of a serial killer.
   The six dogs found nothing but will continue the search
Wednesday, said Jim Martin, spokesman for the Bristol County
district attorney's office.
   Since July, police have found the bodies of eight women, ranging
in age from 25 to 36, near this port city 40 miles southwest of
Boston.
   Martin said the dogs were covering new ground as well as
rechecking areas where the other bodies were found.
   Missing are Christina Monteiro, 20, last seen in May, and Sandra
Botelho, 25, who disappeared in August.
   ``The waiting for the families is very tough. If they are out
there, I want to find them and get it over with for them,'' said
the search coordinator, Connecticut State Trooper Andrew Rebmann.
   The dogs, which found the remains of three of the eight victims,
are on loan from police forces in this state as well as
Connecticut, New Hampshire and Maine.
   The bodies were found within a 10-mile radius, most of them
along three highways. All the victims were known drug users, many
of them prostitutes, and some of the women knew each other from
dealings in New Bedford's seamy Weld Square district, police said.
   Police began getting reports last May from families looking for
the missing women, but it was only in November, after three bodies
had been found, that investigators decided the disappearances and
slayings might be related.
   Investigators believe one person, or a group working together,
killed the women.
   There have been no arrests but Martin says police have four
suspects.
</TEXT>
