<FIRST>r a AM-ChristianScienceTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0714 04-18 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christian Science Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0714,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Convict Parents For Not Getting Medical Aid For Child</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 3-5, beginning ``The six ...,'' with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with no sentencing date, freed on recognizance, defense comment, no comment
from jurors, background on Christian Scientists on trial.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury convicted a Christian Science
couple of murder and child abuse Tuesday in the death of their
7-year-old daughter for relying on spiritual practitioners to cure
her diabetes.
   William Hermanson, 42, and his wife Christine, 38, were charged
with third-degree murder and felony child abuse. Their daughter,
Amy, died of diabetes in 1986 after the couple tried to heal her
with prayer instead of medical treatment.
   The Hermansons face three to seven years in prison under state
sentencing guidelines. Sarasota Circuit Judge Stephen Dakan set no
sentencing date and released the Hermansons on their own
recognizance.
   ``We were disappointed and surprised,'' defense attorney Charles
Arnold said after the six-member jury deliberated three hours. ``We
will be filing motions for a new trial.''
   Jurors refused to comment as they filed silently from the
courthouse.
   Christian Science doctrine relies on prayer and spiritual
practitioners rather than on medicine to heal. However, there are
no church sanctions for followers who seek medical aid and a
Christian Science nurse who tended Amy testified that when she saw
prayer wasn't working she urged a spiritual healer to summon an
ambulance.
   The Hermansons were the first Christian Scientists in 20 years
prosecuted in the United States for denying a child medical care
for religious reasons, church representatives said. Five other
religious exemption cases are pending, three in California, one
each in Arizona and Massachusetts.
   Last week, with the jury out of the room, a state witness
testified both parents had sought medical treatment for themselves,
but not for their daughter.
   The jury never heard that testimony because the judge upheld a
defense objection that prosecutors withheld the information from
opposing attorneys before trial, violating rules of discovery.
   During the weeklong trial, defense laywers claimed the couple
were legitimately practicing the tenets of their religion, a right
they said was protected under Florida law. The defense called no
witnesses, however.
   A 1975 state law protects parents who withhold medical treatment
from their sick children if they are ``legitimately practicing''
their religious beliefs.
   Prosecutors said the case was about the child's rights, not the
parents' religious rights. Amy was sick for weeks and her parents
let her die without any medical attention, the state said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
