<HEAD>Nine Yugoslav Soldiers Go On Trial For Hostile Activity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine soldiers, said to belong to a
banned Albanian separatist organization, went on trial on charges
of trying to burn down the military academy in Belgrade last
August, the state Tanjug news agency reported Tuesday.
   It said the military prosecutor's office filed charges saying
the nine hoped the blaze would spread from one building in the
complex ``to other facilities and cause great damage.'' It did not
say when the trial began.
   Only a small fire broke out in the hall, and that blaze was
quickly extinguished, with minor damage reported.
   The nine include five ethnic Albanians, three Croats and a
Slovene, said the liberal Slovenian Mladina youth weekly.
   The nine could face a maximum prison term of 15 years if
convicted.
   Also on Tuesday, Bosnia's leadership charged that Nenad
Kecmanovic, a leading candidate for the republic's representative
on Yugoslavia's collective federal presidency, passed sensitive
information to unidentified foreign intelligence agents.
   But Kecmanovic, dean of Sarajevo University in Bosnia's capital,
accused party conservatives in the republic of plotting with state
security police to discredit him for his liberal political views.
   Last week, the Bosnian legislature failed to elect either of two
official candidates for Yugoslavia's nine-man presidency after
Kecmanovic, heavily favored to win the vote, unexpectedly announced
his withdrawal from the race.
   In a letter published Monday by Belgrade's Borba newspaper,
Kecmanovic said he had to withdraw and accused the state security
service and the republic's leadership of conspiring to block his
election by falsely accusing him of having secret contacts with
foreign diplomats.
