<FIRST>r i AM-NorthKorea-US     04-18 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Korea-US,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Says US Sent Spy Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea accused the United States of ``aerial
espionage'' flights by U-2 high-altitude reconnaissance planes
Tuesday.
   A broadcast by the Korean Central News Agency, monitored in
Tokyo, said: ``The United States let U-2 strategic reconnaissance
plan fly ... along the military demarcation line at about 9:00 a.m.
this morning (Tuesday) to commit aerial espionage against the
northern half of Korea.''
   ``Such espionage was conducted 15 times in April,'' the report
said, claiming that U.S. reconnaissance flights had spied on North
Korea 85 times recently.
   KCNA also accused the United States of using an E-3A AWACS plane
in South Korea ``to spy on the ... northern half of Korea.''
   An AWACS (airborne warning and control system) plane is used to
detect and track aircraft hundreds of miles away.
   The United States has about 42,000 troops based in South Korea
under a defense treaty. The communist North and capitalist South
have been discussing ways to ease tensions on the peninsula,
divided since 1945.
</TEXT>
