<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill-Exxon     04-18 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill-Exxon,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman Defends Exxon; Says Cleanup Plan Feasible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 6th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Exxon Corp. on Tuesday angrily
defended the company's response to the Alaska oil spill and blamed
delays in the cleanup on indecisive regulatory agencies.
   ``The most damaging that's being said about us is that we've
delayed it, we're very slow to respond, and so forth. That's
absolutely not true,'' Lawrence G. Rawl said at a news conference.
   Rawl said the plan to clean up Prince William Sound and 305
miles of shoreline, announced by the company Monday, had been
approved by all necessary agencies. The Exxon Valdez ran aground
March 24, spilling 10 million gallons of crude oil in the nation's
worst oil spill.
   Exxon promised to have most of the beaches and rocks clean by
mid-September.
   Some officials, including Adm. Paul Yost, head of the Coast
Guard, have expressed skepticism that the cleanup can be
accomplished that rapidly.
   ``What does he want us to do, put in a deadline next year so
that he can say it's too damn late, that deadline you got in
there?'' Rawl said, adding, ``You're damned if you do and you're
damned if you don't.''
   The cleanup will involve at least 4,000 workers who must contend
with high tides and rocky shores in hard-to-get-to places.
   ``Logistical problems are horrendous,'' Rawl said. ``These are
not meant as excuses, I just want you to know that you just can't
cover this place up as if you had a sand beach somewhere.''
   ``Now I'm not going to tell you that if you go up there a year
from now you won't find some black places on some rocks,'' Rawl
said, ``but we're going to make every effort to get it off. I am
telling you that a year from now the toxicity will be eliminated.''
   Yost, who left Tuesday for Washington to brief President Bush,
declined to comment on Rawl's outburst but said he was glad Rawls
felt confident the cleanup could be accomplished.
   ``I'm on his side,'' Yost said. ``I say let's give him a shot at
it.''
   He repeated his reservations about whether Exxon could beat
Alaska's notorious weather and brief summer and get the beaches
cleaned by winter.
   But he said there was ``nothing personal'' in his reservations.
   Rawl repeatedly defended Exxon's reaction to the spill, saying
contingency plans were foiled by a lack of decisive action by the
Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation and the Coast Guard.
   He said Exxon had enough oil dispersant on hand to begin
spraying March 25, about 30 hours after the spill, and was awaiting
approval from the state and the Coast Guard.
   Records Exxon filed with the state after the accident said
controlling the Valdez spill would have required 500,000 gallons of
dispersant. When the tanker hit the reef, according to earlier
reports, Exxon had only 3,795 gallons on hand, and just 110,000 six
days later.
   ``I'm not trying to say we're not responsible,'' Rawl said. ``It
was our ship, we spilled the oil, we intend to clean it up and we
intend to do it promptly.''
</TEXT>
