<FIRST>r w AM-Cheney-NATO     04-18 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-NATO,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Leaves for Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney departed
Washington Tuesday evening on his first overseas trip since
assuming office, bound for a meeting of North Atlantic Treaty
Organization defense ministers in Brussels.
   Cheney, who became the nation's 17th defense secretary last
month, planned to provide NATO's Nuclear Planning Group with a
status report on the Bush administration's on-going review of
strategic security issues, as well as an update on problems at U.S.
government nuclear weapons plants.
   Aides said Cheney also looked forward to discussions about
modernization of the short-range nuclear missiles now deployed in
Europe, but did not expect any final decisions to be made on that
issue. The secretary is planning a number of get-acquainted
``bilateral'' discussions with individual counterparts, the aides
added.
   Cheney, now in the midst of slashing the fiscal 1990 budget to
comply with a White House-congressional compromise, will return
immediately to Washington on Thursday evening, according to the
Pentagon.
</TEXT>
