<FIRST>r a AM-Fusion     04-18 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fusion Researcher Says Much Work Lies Ahead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for Salt Lake City-dated story listed on the News Advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first researcher to obtain room
temperature fusion offered his services Tuesday to one of the
nation's top nuclear laboratories in hopes of getting support for
his research in return.
   University of Utah professor Stanley Pons said that in helping
Los Alamos National Laboratory scientists to duplicate his fusion
experiments, he could gain their collaboration on future research.
   Los Alamos thus far has been unable to confirm the results that
Pons and his British colleague, Martin Fleischmnann, obtained last
month at the University of Utah.
   ``I don't think there can be any collaboration until they start
getting a result. And so it's my determination now to make sure
that they do,'' Pons said.
   Pons said Monday he had sustained a controlled fusion reaction
more than 800 hours in a small flask containing ``heavy'' water,
which contains the isotope deuterium, and a palladium electrode. He
said recent tests produced roughly eight times the energy consumed.
   Pons told a news conference that the results he and Fleischmann
obtained had been partly verified by more than 60 university and
private laboratories around the world.
   In Stanford, Calif., on Tuesday, Stanford University professor
Robert Huggins said that in trying to duplicate the Utah work he
had determined that the energy produced may have been caused by
fusion and did not come from a chemical reaction, as some other
scientists have speculated.
   Pons, who left Tuesday without a commitment from Los Alamos,
said he was able to find one possible reason why scientists here
had been unable to duplicate his experiment. The palladium
electrodes they used are not in the same form as the rods he used
in Utah, Pons said.
   Pons said Los Alamos has sophisticated spectrometers and other
precise measuring devices that could be useful in confirming the
results of his research.
   ``One of the purposes in coming down was to see if there is
equipment that I could use that would lead to confirmation or more
substantiation of some of the new experiments that we are doing,''
he said.
   Pons said his research may open the door to practical
application of nuclear fusion, in which tremendous amounts of
energy are released when the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse.
   Scientists in the past had been unable to fuse atoms except at
temperatures in the millions of degrees.
   Nuclear power plants produce energy through fission, in which
atoms are split. The process requires radioactive fuel and
generates large amounts of radioactive waste; fusion does not.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0231 </DOCNO>
