<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Sentencing     04-18 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Sentencing,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Ugandan Official Sentenced to Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official in former president
Milton Obote's ruling party was convicted of five counts of murder
Tuesday and sentenced to death.
   Uganda's High Court ound Haji Musa Ssebirumbi, 47, guilty of
joining six soldiers in the 1981 beating deaths of a policeman and
four residents of the village of Kikandwa.
   The village is about 40 miles north of Kampala in an area known
as the Luwero Triangle, where thousands of people thought unloyal
to Obote were killed by government soldiers and paramilitary groups
between 1981 and 1985.
   Ssebirumbi was a member of the Central Executive Committee of
Obote's ruling Uganda People's Congress and a prominent businessmen
in Kampala. Obote was overthrown in 1985 and Sseibirumbi was
arrested two years later.
