<DOCNO> AP890418-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Egypt     04-18 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Egypt,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Official Says Egypt Accepts Election Idea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Foreign Ministry official said Tuesday after
returning from Cairo that Egypt accepts the idea of elections in
the occupied territories proposed by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Foreign Ministry Director-General Reuven Merhav said Egyptian
Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel Meguid and other Egyptian officials
reacted positively to Shamir's plan for elections to choose
representatives with whom Israel could negotiate Palestinian
autonomy.
   ``They accept, rather than support, the principle of
elections,'' said Merhav, who returned Monday from a four-day visit
to Egypt. ``I made it very clear the only way to get things moving
was through elections ... I think at this stage the principle was
accepted.''
   Merhav said the Egyptians raised no conditions for their support
and did not allude to statements by President Hosni Mubarak that
the vote should be held under international supervision.
   Nor did the Egyptians refer to the insistence of the Palestine
Liberation Organization that Israel withdraw from the occupied
territories prior to balloting, he said.
   ``There was no talk of international supervision. This was not
in the cards at all,'' Merhav told reporters. ``The (issue of the)
PLO also was not raised.''
   On Sunday, during Merhav's visit, Egyptian officials criticized
Israel's handing of the 16-month Palestinian uprising and demanded
a positive Israeli response to the PLO's revised stand recognizing
Israel's right to exist.
   The officials made no formal statement on Shamir's election
plan. PLO chief Yasser Arafat has demanded Israeli withdrawal and
international supervision as conditions for accepting elections.
   Shamir proposed his plan at a meeting with President Bush last
week. It essentially mirrors the 1978 U.S.-sponsored Camp David
accords, rejected by the Palestinians because they promise only
self-rule under Israeli control.
   Both Shamir's plan and Camp David call for later negotiations on
the final status of the Gaza Strip and West Bank, occupied by
Israel since the 1967 Middle East war.
   The one change in Shamir's plan is the offer to hold elections
to choose Palestinian represenatives to negotiate an interim
settlement with Israel. Previous Israeli proposals called for
elections only after an autonomy agreement was worked out.
</TEXT>
