<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LottoFever     04-18 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotto Fever,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Winner of Record Jackpot Comes Forward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sisters who kidded each other about getting
rich were revealed Tuesday as the very wealthy holders of one of
four winning tickets from a world-record $69.9 million Lotto
jackpot.
   Linda and Barbara Lambert will share almost $17.5 million. They
join two family clans announced as winners of two other tickets
Monday, Illinois State Lottery officials said.
   The identity of the fourth winner has not been revealed.
   At a news conference, the Lamberts described their feelings when
the lottery was drawn Saturday night.
   ``She called me and said, `We won,''' Linda said. ``By the third
time she said it, I knew she wasn't kidding.''
   Linda Lambert, 39, is a high school biology teacher and lives in
Forest Lake, northwest of Chicago.
   Her sister, who would say only that she was the older of the
two, lives in Chicago and is a solid-waste program manager for the
federal Environmental Protection Agency.
   Linda Lambert said she and her sister played Lotto regularly and
once joked about opening a business ``slinging pizzas'' if they
ever won. She said she plans to use her share of the money to write
children's books, but has no immediate plans to quit her job.
   She said she kept her good fortune a secret from co-workers
Monday.
   ``It was torture, but it was also a lot of fun because everybody
was telling lottery stories,'' she said.
   The sisters bought 37 Lotto tickets last week. The winning
ticket was among 15 Barbara Lambert bought at a newsstand in a
Chicago Transit Authority train station on the Northwest Side.
   ``I went back and told the owner, `I heard you sold the winning
ticket,' and he said, `Yeah, and I'll bet you got it.'
   ``He didn't believe me so I told him I'd bet him $50,000,''
Barbara said. ``Eventually, we settled on a lunch bet.''
   One of the other winning tickets was bought by MaryAnn Dixon,
37, on behalf of herself, husband Daniel and 10-month-old daughter,
Kate, as well as her parents _ Louis and Mary Matlosz of Elizabeth,
N.J. _ and two brothers and a sister and their families in New
Jersey.
   The other drawing winner, Ron Miller, 36, who is married and has
a 10-year-old daughter, plans to split his share with brother
Scott, 29, of Chandler, Ariz., and a brother in Stafford, Texas.
   The final figure for the jackpot, boosted by four winner-less
drawings and a frenzy of ticket-buying last week, was $69,940,000,
said Lottery Director Sharon Sharp.
   The winners beat odds of 12.9 million-to-1 to pick the six
winning numbers from 1 to 54: 3, 14, 32, 40, 46 and 54.
</TEXT>
