<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 2ndLd-Writethru a0809 04-18 1054</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0809,1076</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil On The Beach At Seward After Tar Knocks Out Skimmer Pumps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, ``In Boston ...,'' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
further Yost comments; picks up 11th graf pvs, `A sizeable ...' SUBS 22nd
graf, `In Washington ...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with notice of lawsuits
from environmental groups, picks up 23rd graf pvs, ``Every oil ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taffylike tar mixed with seaweed was
scoured off a beach Tuesday at the end of spectacular Resurrection
Bay near Seward, the first town outside Prince William Sound to
suffer oil on its shores.
   High tides and southerly wind off the Gulf of Alaska pushed the
crude oil up the fjordlike channel, where two Coast Guard
oil-skimming ships were out of action because the goo gummed up
their pumps, Deputy Seward City Manager Darryl Schaefermeyer said.
   ``We put protective booming up around the critical (salmon)
spawning streams in the bay four weeks ago,'' Schaefermeyer said.
``But as far as the rest of the bay there was no effective way of
booming it all off.''
   The Coast Guard reported fresh sightings of oil on remote
beaches on the Kenai Peninsula. A Valdez center for cleaning
oil-fouled birds said at least 1,850 birds had died from the spill,
along with 328 sea otters. The center has cleaned and released 22
birds.
   Resurrection Bay, with a channel 600 feet deep, is about 125 air
miles from where the tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24,
dumping more than 10 million gallons of Alaska crude oil into
Prince William Sound.
   Adm. Paul Yost, the Coast Guard chief, approved Exxon's cleanup
plan for the sound Monday, but expressed reservations about whether
it could succeed.
   Lawrence Rawl, chairman of Exxon Corp., reacted angrily Tuesday.
At a news conference in New York, he said he was confident that
most of the beaches and rocks would be clean by mid-September.
   ``Now I'm not going to tell you that if you go up there a year
from now you won't find some black places on some rocks, but we're
going to make every effort to get it off,'' he said. ``I am telling
you that a year from now the toxicity will be eliminated.''
   Yost, before leaving for Washington on Tuesday to brief
President Bush, said he believed Exxon's cleanup plan was a good
start.
   ``Exxon is committed to doing this. I say let's give him (Rawl)
a shot at it,'' he said.
   But he said he still had reservations that Exxon could clean the
beaches by winter, and added that if efforts lagged, he would force
the company to throw more people and gear into the task.
   Yost gave Exxon until May 1 to complete a cleanup plan for
outside the sheltered sound, where the work is likely to be even
harder along the wild Gulf of Alaska coast.
   In Boston, Massachusetts state Sen. Carol Amick said she was
organizing a one-day boycott throughout New England on May 2 to
protest Exxon's ``failure to respond'' to the environmental
disaster.
   A sizeable but undetermined amount of oil has seeped out of the
sound and into the gulf, where currents carried it southwest along
the Kenai Peninsula. A weekend storm pushed oil north onto hundreds
of miles of rocky beaches and far up the bays and inlets, including
Resurrection Bay.
   Huge swells along the exposed coast will often prevent boats or
crews from working close to the beach, said Peter Fitzmaurice,
chief ranger at Kenai Fjords National Park, which stretches from
Seward southwest along most of the southern coast of the peninsula.
   ``They can work the inner bays, but if a big swell comes in,
there's no way they'll be able to work near the rocks,'' he said.
   Farther southwest near the end of the peninsula, skimming
operations have been on hold for several days because of waves up
to 12 feet. experts say he ships are designed to work in waves of
no more than five feet.
   A huge Soviet oil skimmer able to process far more oil in much
heavier seas than skimmers now available is scheduled to arrive
Thursday in Seward.
   ``Everyone has some pretty high hopes for this Russian ship,''
Schaefermeyer said. ``It's pretty big, 430 feet, and it apparently
has the capacity for getting far down into the water to get at some
of the stuff you can't see.''
   The state ferry Aurora, carrying 20 skiffs on a cleanup mission
since early this month, was greeted by a balloon-carrying crowd as
it returned to Valdez for six hours to resupply.
   The skiffs round up oil with floating booms, then tow it to a
barge for disposal by a ``super-sucker'' vacuum hose. Workers said
the technique had been used to remove 200,000 gallons of oil from
the water.
   Coast Guard aircraft reported oil washing ashore all along the
Kenai Peninsula headlands, and spotters saw ``significant shoreline
impact'' at Lone, Perry and Culross islands in Prince William
Sound, the Coast Guard said.
   The Coast Guard sent three skimmers to Perry Island but
operations stalled because pumps were unable to remove the
now-tarlike oil from the skimmers.
   Exxon said it had recovered 1.13 million gallons of oil _ about
11 percent of the amount spilled.
   Meantime, Exxon and the oil pipeline consortium Alyeska were
given 90 days warning Tuesday that environmental groups intend to
sue them to ensure cleanup of America's worst oil spill.
   The Sierra Club, Wilderness Society and Audubon Society were
joined by an array of local, state and national organizations in
serving the notice, which is required under federal resource
conservation law.
   In Washington, Energy Secretary James D. Watkins said Tuesday
that the spill has blackened the image of the oil industry.
   ``Every oil company will have to confront the images created by
the spill,'' Watkins said in a speech to the National Petroleum
Council, a group of private energy officials that advises the
energy secretary on policy issues.
   He said his department would try to persuade Congress and the
public that the spill was an aberration that should not halt future
oil development in Alaska. Watkins said his department will
continue to lobby for legislation permitting oil companies to
explore for oil in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
