<DOCNO> AP890418-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-U-2Records     04-18 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-U-2 Records,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>U-2C Spy Plane Sets Flight Records Before Being Retired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's last remaining
U-2C spy plane, which photographed clandestine missiles in Cuba and
military bases in the Soviet Union, set eight records Tuesday on
one of its last flights.
   The plane, commonly called simply a U-2, is being retired and
put on display after 34 years of service.
   It was the second day the once-supersecret surveillance plane
made special flights from this desert base 60 miles north of Los
Angeles to try and set new records before being retired.
   Lockheed test pilot Ron Williams, 54, shattered existing
altitude records in the plane's weight class by about 40 percent,
according to Lockheed spokesman Nick Durutta.
   The records include reaching an altitude of 72,720 without a
payload and in horizontal flight. It also climbed to various
altitudes faster than previous record holders.
   The aircraft had previously flown at such altitudes but the
marks were not verified. The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and the Federation Aeronautique International must
still confirm Tuesday's records.
   Lockheed reported that on Monday the plane soared to 73,700 feet
in 12 minutes and 13 seconds, shattering by more than 20,000 feet
the previous altitude record for a plane in its weight class.
   ``There's only one U-2C in existence that is still flying,''
said Maj. Susan Randle of Strategic Air Command Headquarters at
Offutt Air Force Base in Nebraska.
   The last U-2C will be flown to Warner-Robbins Air Force Base in
Georgia on April 26 to be put on display.
   The Air Force will continue to fly the updated U-2R model built
in 1981.
   Because of the craft's top-secret nature the military has never
confirmed the exact number built in 1955 by Lockheed at its
top-secret ``skunk works'' plant, but it has been estimated at 57.
   It was a U-2C that brought back the photographic proof during
the Cuban missile crisis of 1962 that the Soviets had installed
missiles in that island country just off the coast of Florida.
   It was also a U-2C that the late Francis Gary Powers was
piloting over the Soviet Union when it was shot down in 1960. His
capture helped chill the Cold War even more as Soviet Premier
Nikita Khruschev canceled a summit meeting with President Dwight
Eisenhower.
   More recently, U-2s were used to record the eruptions of Mount
St. Helens and to provide information to firefighters battling last
summer's blazes in Yellowstone National Park.
   The plane, a forerunner of the stealth fighter, was designed by
Lockheed to fly undetected nearly 14 miles above the Earth. Several
were shot down on missions, and many crashed in flight because the
planes were so tricky to fly due to their thin wings. The Air Force
loaned several to NASA-Ames Research Laboratories at Moffett Field,
near San Francisco.
   The plane's days became numbered with the advent of satellites
and a new generation of spy planes, including the SR-71 Blackbird.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890418-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--US-ChemicalWeapons     04-18 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--US-Chemical Weapons,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Increasing Problems In Verifying Ban On Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States said Tuesday that it is becoming
more difficult to monitor compliance with a proposed
chemical-weapons ban because of greater sophistication in the
chemical industry.
   Ambassador Max L. Friedersdorf, addressing the 40-nation
Conference on Disarmament, said determining that there are no
hidden stocks of chemical weapons and no secret production
facilities remain ``our most formidable challenge.''
   He said the challenge is becoming more difficult because of the
trend in the chemical industry to produce multipurpose facilities
that can easily be converted to manufacture chemical-weapon agents.
   Measures to prevent cheating are one of the main issues that
have prevented an agreement on a treaty to ban the use, production
and stockpiling of chemical weapons. The negotiations are now in
their 21st year.
</TEXT>
