<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Cheney-MX     04-18 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-MX,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post: Cheney Backs Rail MX</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Richard Cheney has told
President Bush that he favors building a railroad-based version of
the MX nuclear missile and scrapping the planned Midgetman missile,
The Washington Post reported.
   Cheney made his views known in a meeting Tuesday afternoon at
the White House before leaving for a NATO meeting in Europe, the
newspaper reported in its Wednesday editions.
   But a White House source who declined to be named said no
decision was made at the meeting, which was called as the next step
in the long fight over whether to build a rail-based version of the
10-warhead MX or up to 500 of the single-warhead Midgetman.
   No timetable has been set for making a decison, said the source,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Both weapons are designed as successors to the Minuteman, which
has formed the heart of the nation's land-based atomic missile
force for two decades. The Pentagon has also built 50 MX weapons
for deployment in silos in Nebraska and Wyoming.
   If Cheney favors the rail-based MX over the Midgetman, he would
be taking the position long favored by the Air Force. Service
officials have proposed creating 25 trains, each with two MX
missiles aboard, and keeping them on western military reservations,
to be moved out onto civilian tracks in time of crisis.
   The Midgetman has chiefly been supported by Democrats, who
control Congress.
   Cheney is scheduled to appear before Congress next week to
unveil Bush's plans for amending the Pentagon budget proposed
earlier this year by then-President Reagan. Bush has to approve $10
billion worth of budget cuts to meet lowered spending targets.
</TEXT>
