<SECOND>AM-Chile-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0824,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs blackout Santiago, report 2 killed more than 100 arrests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with two reported killed, blackout
in Santiago. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions blacked out most of Santiago
Tuesday night, and police said two men were killed while trying to
place a bomb at a utility tower after a national strike turned into
a day of street battles.
   Chile's largest labor federation had called the national strike
to protest the military government's banishment of two union
leaders into internal exile. Government officials and business
organizations called the strike a failure.
   Police used tear gas and water cannons to disperse groups of
strikers and their supporters in Santiago and other cities, and
more than 100 people were arrested.
   Those disorders tapered off at dusk, but after nighfall the
violence spread to the slums ringing Santiago. Demonstrators
blocked street with burning barricades, and gunshots and explosions
were heard.
   Police said security forces in Santiago intercepted two men
attempting to place an explosive device at a utility tower and
opened fire, killing both suspects.
   Most of Santiago, with a population of 4.5 million, was blacked
out at about 9:30 p.m., and police blamed the power failure on
bombings of several electric-line pylons. Within a half hour power
had been restored to some secions of the capital.
   The Interior Ministry said 138 people were arrested throughout
the country, including 84 in Santiago, during the day. No report
was issued on the later violence.
   At dusk the streets in downtown Santiago were virtually
deserted, the air thick with tear gas. Public transportation came
to a standstill as bus owners withdrew their vehicles after several
were damaged.
   ``What strike?'' Interior Minister Carlos Caceres said when
reporters asked about the walkout called by the United Workers
Central, which claims 300,000 members in Chile's labor force of 4.5
million.
   He said the situation was ``near normal throughout the country.
Workers attended their jobs normally and schools were also
funcioning normally.''
   The minister and other officials acknowledged public transport
was severely curtailed in the morning and attributed it to fear by
drivers of attacks on themselves and their vehicles.
   Diego Olivares, acting president of the labor federation, said
thousands of workers stayed home and many others went to their jobs
late. Osvaldo Verdugo, president of the National School Teachers
Association, said more than half the students in Santiago did not
attend school.
   Olivares' federation called the strike to protest the continued
banishment to small provincial towns of its president, Manuel
Bustos, and vice president, Arturo Martinez. Both were sentenced
last September to 541 days of internal exile for calling a strike
in 1987.
   Independent reports confirmed little absenteeism at most
industries and factories, but some industries were idled by lack of
electric power.
   Parts of Santiago also had been blacked out by bombings early
Tuesday, and Caceres said those attacks ``confirm what the
government said, that the real aim of this strike was to promote
violence and terrorism.''
   The government power company said seven power pylons were
destroyed ``by terrorists'' in the bombings Tuesday morning.
   There was no immediate report on the damage from the Tuesday
night attacks.
   A police report on the bombings early Tuesday said at least
eight explosions in Santiago wounded two men and damaged a bank,
telephone company office bus terminal and municipal building.
</TEXT>
