<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to back
a plan to close 86 military bases and scale back five more despite
complaints that the move will not save as much as advocates had
promised.
   By a vote of 381-43, the House rejected a resolution to
disapprove the recommendations of the Commission on Base
Realignment and Closure, giving the green light for Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney to follow through on the panel's proposals
beginning in January.
   ``It is incumbent upon all of us to make sure this base closing
list is implemented,'' the chairman of the House Armed Services
Chairman, Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said moments before the vote.
   The commission's recommendations affect a total of 145 domestic
military installations by closing some, reducing the operations of
others and changing the missions of additional bases.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC captured its fourth straight television
season Tuesday, winning by the largest margin in 32 years with a
little help from ``The Cosby Show,'' ``Cheers,'' ``A Different
World'' and ``The Golden Girls.''
   NBC won all 30 weeks of the September to April season, the first
time any network has done so since 1963-64, and claimed three of
the four most popular series, according to A.C. Nielsen Co.
end-of-the-year ratings.
   The network's margin of victory, 24 percent, was the
second-largest in Nielsen history, the network said.
   Boosted by its working-class situation comedy ``Roseanne,'' the
season's highest-rated new series and No. 2 overall, ABC finished
in second place. CBS, saddled by the aging serials ``Dallas,'' tied
for No. 30, ``Knots Landing,'' tied for 28th, and ``Falcon Crest,''
tied at No. 54, came in last among the three networks for the
second year in a row.
