<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-TV-Wiesenthal ADV19   04-18 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV-Wiesenthal, ADV 19,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, April 19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wiesenthal Sees Movie As Continuation of Life's Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AP on TV-Kingsley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Simon Wiesenthal stood among 40 naked,
shivering men as a Nazi officer stepped down the line, shooting
each man in the temple and sending them toppling into the stone
quarry below.
   Two men away from being shot, Wiesenthal was reprieved. A
messenger ran up and said his services were needed to paint a sign
honoring Adolf Hitler's birthday.
   Wiesenthal dedicated his survival to the dead, documenting the
Nazi atrocities and hunting down some 6,000 Nazis over the past 40
years so they could be brought to trial.
   The story of his life, powerfully portrayed by Oscar-winning
British actor Ben Kingsley, is told in ``Murderers Among Us: The
Simon Wiesenthal Story,'' a Home Box Office production premiering
Sunday on the pay-cable channel.
   ``The message in the movie is justice, not revenge,''
Wiesenthal, 80, said after seeing the three-hour film at a preview
here. ``I am one of the witnesses. After I am gone, the movie will
survive.''
   Was the movie true-to-life? ``This is not a case of fact being
stronger than fiction,'' he said in an interview. ``It was all
fact, even the dramatization.''
   Kingsley, 54, best-known for his Oscar-winning performance as
the pacifist Indian leader Gandhi, bears a strong likeness to
Wiesenthal in his younger years. ``We were born on the same date,
Dec. 31. Maybe that's why he was totally in my skin. He's a
brilliant actor,'' said Wiesenthal, who spent time with Kingsley
during filming in Hungary.
   When Wiesenthal first walked onto a set depicting the Mauthausen
concentration camp where he was held, he wept. ``It was so strong,
I couldn't help crying,'' he said.
   More than 40 years ago, when U.S. troops rolled into Mauthausen,
they found a beaten Wiesenthal, half-starved. ``It's OK, you're
alive,'' says an American major, played by Craig T. Nelson in the
movie, as he cradles Wiesenthal in his arms. ``Yes, but why?''
Wiesenthal asks.
   The major convinces Wiesenthal to help him set up a war-crimes
unit that could use his photographic memory of the Nazis who ran
the camp.
   Wiesenthal is reunited with his wife, Cyla, whom he had thought
must have died during their six-year separation. A daughter is
born. When the U.S. war-crimes unit is sent home, Wiesenthal asks
for its files and moves his family to Vienna to set up his
now-famous documentation center.
   His wife _ played by Dutch actress Renee Soutendijk _ wants only
to forget. He cannot. ``We must never forget or it will happen
again,'' he tells her.
   After a crank caller threatens to kidnap their daughter and his
wife demands that he move the family away from Vienna's persistent
manifestations of anti-Semitism, Wiesenthal says: ``I have to do
this. I survived.''
   Guilt at his survival translates into recurring nightmares. The
most persistent is based on a true experience: Wiesenthal is told
that his mother has been rounded up by the Gestapo and put on a
train for transportation to a death camp.
   He is working at the train station at that time, shortly before
he, too, is taken away, and he goes running along the rails
frantically banging against the doors of the locked box cars
shouting. ``Mrs. Wiesenthal! Mrs. Wiesenthal!''
   He hears wailing and screaming from inside the cars, the
engineer stokes the furnace, and the train chugs off taking his
mother to the gas chambers.
   ``I swear, I swear, I swear,'' he shouts as he falls to the
ground and vows to find her killers.
   But it's not revenge he is seeking, Wiesenthal tells his
teen-age daughter. ``You musn't hate, you musn't blame them all.''
   Not even when an Austrian court acquits Franz Murer, an Austrian
officer known as the ``Butcher of Vilna'' for his atrocities at the
Vilna ghetto; not even when he tracks down a Nazi who tied two Jews
together so he could shoot one in the mouth and prove to a
colleague that the bullet would pierce the skull of the other man;
not even when Nazi sympathizers firebomb his apartment with his
wife and daughter inside.
   ``When I go to heaven and meet the 6 million'' who perished in
the Nazi Holocaust, Wiesenthal said, ``I want to tell them I hunted
down their killers. I didn't kill them, because we're better than
they are. We believe in justice.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, April 19</NOTE>
