<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   04-18 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Clean and Sober'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated
R)
   
   Michael Keaton, a genuinely funny comic actor who never really
hit his stride in film comedies, emerges as a dramatic actor of
astonishing power in ``Clean and Sober,'' an excellent movie about
the wasting disease that doesn't lend itself to the last act in
opera.
   This is one of those movies that everybody avoided because all
the critics everyone really detests were crazy about it and
Keaton's poor taste in scripts had eroded one's good opinion of him.
   ``Johnny Dangerously,'' ``Mr. Mom,'' ``The Squeeze'' and their
ilk probably cost Keaton an Academy Award nomination for his fine
work in ``Clean and Sober'' as a real estate broker up to his ears
in debt and up to his nose in cocaine.
   Our hero wakes up one morning with a comatose girl in his bed.
So to dodge the cops, he chugs a couple of beers and checks into a
drug rehabilitation clinic.
   Kathy Baker does a fine job as the troubled woman he meets in
``detox,'' Morgan Freeman is excellent as the ex-addict rehab
counselor and the brilliant M. Emmet Walsh plays the
alcoholic-addict who tries to help our hero get straight.
   Keaton is in superb touch with his character throughout, playing
his part with an honest simplicity that is genuine and affecting.
   Screenwriter Tod Carroll can be faulted for taking a
conventional approach to the subject, but avoids the cliches for a
messier truth. Director Glenn Gordon Caron (of TV's
``Moonlighting'') faultlessly handles the material.
   Each generation of Hollywood filmmakers seems to rediscover
addiction as a mirror of the human soul. That's how we got ``Lost
Weekend,'' ``The Man With the Golden Arm,'' ``The Days of Wine and
Roses'' and other less distinguished films. ``Clean and Sober'' is
one for the '80s, and one of the best.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Cannibal Women in the Avocado Jungle of Death'' (Paramount
Home Video. VHS, $79.95; Beta, $29.95. Rated PG-13)
   
   There's an imaginary jungle stretching from Bakersfield, Calif.,
to the Mexican border. This is where all the avocados grow. It also
is where the ancient Amazon commune of man-eating piranha women
live, as well as the dreaded barracuda women.
   If you can buy all of that, then you'll have no trouble with
``Cannibal Women in the Avocado Jungle of Death.'' Or maybe you
will, because the movie is stupid and silly no matter how you look
at it.
   It takes a stab at some sort of backwards humor about feminism
and male chauvinism. But it's merely pretentious and not very funny.
   Adrienne Barbeau plays a talk show anthropolgist whose lines
read like something out of junior high school. When she's fencing
with Margo Hunt (Shannon Tweed), a feminism instructor, she
congratulates herself on her good form and says, ``I learned in the
ancient weaponry course at Berkeley.''
   Later, when she throws herself into a seething piranha pit, she
says, ``You don't know how degrading it is to be on the David
Letterman Show! I can't go back to that!''
   The acting is as wooden as the actors.
   Bad jokes abound. So do misadventures as Margo, Bunny (Karen
Mistral) and Jim (Bill Maher), a clumsy Indiana Jones-type, enter
the jungle to save the Free World's supply of avocados, and the
pickers, from the voracious females.
   But there's a happy ending. The bad guys are defeated, and the
piranha women and the barracuda women unite and live happily ever
after in the jungle, protected as a primitive culture.
   Oh, in case you need to know: The prime difference between the
two groups is that the piranhas ``tear their men into strips like
beef jerky and eat them with guacamole dip,'' while the barrcudas
insist on clam dip.
   Running time is an eternal 90 minutes.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
