<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   04-18 0986</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,1023</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Symphony No. 29 in A major, K. 201; Symphony No. 39 in E flat
major, K. 543; Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Herbert
Von Karajan (Deutsche Grammaphon)
   
   One way to take your Mozart is like coffee _ light and sweet.
Herbert von Karajan tends more towards dark, no sugar in this
recording of two Mozart symphonies: No. 29, one of the composer's
first great symphonies, and No. 39, from the final troika of
masterpieces.
   What a marvelous, sleek machine the Berlin Philharmonic is. Like
a lustrous Mercedes-Benz sedan, it glides through symphonies. The
orchestra's character is that it needs no character, because its
sheer sound is so perfect. Karajan, the aging potentate of European
music, brings slow tempos, some beautiful effects and a weighty
intensity that occasionally borders on the plodding.
   The A major symphony, written by the 17-year-old Mozart, has one
of the most marvelous openings of his symphonies, an inviting,
mysterious murmur in the strings. The andante is a serenade, played
lovingly by the Berlin strings. Karajan elicits an appropriately
courtly dance quality to the third movement menuetto. The orchestra
brings clarity and spirit to the churning final allegro con spirito.
   The highlight of the disc comes in the adagio introduction of
the E flat symphony. Karajan and his forces are at their best,
bringing an expansiveness and tautness to this grandiose, operatic
section. The clarinets, which take the place of oboes in this
symphony, have some lovely melodies. In loud passionate passages of
the second movement, Karajan sometimes errs on the side of the
plodding when trying to sound intense. In another section,
successive woodwind entrances sound beautiful but aimless.
   On the basis of the second movement, it's no surprise that the
minuet sounds a little relentless. The jaunty final allegro lacks a
little in jaunt. Fast passages are clean but lifeless.
   This disc is a thing of beauty, but for listeners who want more
interesting recent Mozart symphonic issues, consider recordings by
Sir Charles Mackerras and the Prague Chamber Orcehstra on Telarc.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Raw &amp; The Cooked'' (MCA) _ Fine Young Cannibals
   
   There are dozens and dozens of bands out there making
nondescript, electronic pop music. Some of it's pleasant enough but
most fades quickly from memory.
   Those bands don't have a voice. What sets Fine Young Cannibals
apart is a Gift _ lead singer Roland Gift, to be precise.
   Roland Gift is the vocalist ex-English Beat members Andy Cox
(guitars) and David Steele (keyboards and bass) found singing for a
British R&amp;B band in a London pub. Together, they formed Fine Young
Cannibals in 1985.
   On ``The Raw &amp; The Cooked,'' Fine Young Cannibals' second album,
Gift shifts from breathy falsetto to raw, wrenching yells to a
lower register that sounds as if his throat is lined with oak.
   The result is a remarkable vocal performance not heard since the
death of Otis Redding _ to whom Gift is often compared.
   ``The Raw &amp; The Cooked'' is, above all, a fun record. You can
dance to the bright guitar hook of ``She Drives Me Crazy,'' while
the hit ``Good Thing'' and another tune, ``It's OK (It's Alright)''
are both R&amp;B numbers made to move you.
   There's straight, guitar-based rock 'n' roll on ``Don't Look
Back,'' which showcases Andy Cox's ringing style, reminiscent of
early Beatles or Byrds.
   But back to the Gift. Two songs, if played back to back,
demonstrate his incredible vocal range.
   ``I'm Not the Man I Used to Be'' is a gripping ballad that finds
Gift pleading with a woman to stay with him even though he's weak.
And on ``As Hard As It Is,'' Gift takes his voice way down low to
show strength in the face of adversity.
   Fine Young Cannibals is a fine young band with a possibly great
lead singer. The tunes are catchy and intelligent, if a bit
over-electronic.
   If only the group had a drummer instead of a drum machine to put
a floor under it all _ but who's complaining?
   
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Sunshine on Leith'' (Chrysalis) _ The Proclaimers
   
   Garage rock meets Celtic folk music in an Edinburgh pub and the
result is this jaunty album from The Proclaimers. Twin brothers
Charlie and Craig Reid have written a collection of songs that
would sound best live in a crowded, smoky tavern.
   The simple arrangements and spare production of this record come
close to capturing that sound. Nothing artificial here _ or at
least it sounds as though each song might have been recorded in one
take.
   The politics of frustration are heard in ``What Do You Do'' and
``Cap in Hand'' (``I can't understand why we let someone else rule
our land''). But the more common theme is love conquering sorrow
(``Then I Met You,'' ``I'm on My Way,'' ``Oh Jean''). And ``Come on
Nature'' is a delightfully honest expression of sexual desire (``I
just want to spend some time being boy to the girl'').
   The Reid brothers and their band have made good use of varied
influences, including a touch of American country. But a distinctly
Scottish sound comes through, not only in their accents, but in the
stomping beat of many of their songs. And as ``Oh Jean'' builds to
its finish, the words ``I love her I love her'' are sung over and
over like the drone note of a bagpipe.
   The lyrics are unsophisticated, sometimes even trite, the vocals
rough and throaty. The tables and chairs are of bare wood, the
floor is grimy and the light is bad. Faded photographs and flags
hang from the... Well, you get the picture.
   _ By Dan Murphy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
