<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Owens Adv28-30   04-18 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Owens, Adv 28-30,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 28-30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions April 28-30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Buck Owens And Ringo Starr Team Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resurgent country music star Buck Owens
says ``doodling around'' with former Beatle Ringo Starr was a
milestone of his long career.
   Owens, the former grinning co-host of the ``Hee Haw'' syndicated
TV show, and Starr recently recorded a duet of the song ``Act
Naturally.'' Both had separately released the song in the 1960s.
   ``I've never had so much fun in all my life,'' the 59-year-old
Owens said about his recording session with Starr in London at the
Abbey Road Studios, where the Beatles recorded often.
   ``I'd been out of music for a while and so had he,'' Owens said.
``He played me a little bit of drums. `Doodling around' we called
it. He's very talented.''
   The much anticipated record will probably be released this
summer.
   ``How many people get a chance to sing with Ringo Starr?'' Owens
mused as he reflected on his career upswing.
   The duet marked another achievement in a rebounding career for
Owens, who left ``Hee Haw'' in 1986 after 17 years on the country
music comedy show.
   In the past year, he re-emerged as a recording artist after
about 10 years away from the studio to concentrate on his business
interests. He and rising country star Dwight Yoakam teamed up on
the No. 1 country hit, ``Streets of Bakersfield.''
   The song added to Owens' long list of honky-tonk hits, including
``I've Got a Tiger by the Tail,'' ``Together Again,'' ``My Heart
Skips a Beat,'' ``Love's Gonna Live Here,'' ``Gonna Have You,''
``Buckaroo,'' ``Only You'' and ``Before You Go.''
   As a songwriter, he composed ``Crying Time'' which was a hit by
Ray Charles.
   In April, in honor of Owens' many contributions to country
music, the Academy of Country Music gave him its Pioneer Award.
   Owens, in keeping with his return to the stage, said he'll
probably show up on ``Hee Haw'' again. ``I left a lot of friends
there,'' he said in an interview.
   ``I loved doing it. It was lots of fun.''
   He quit for much the same reason he ceased his recording career
in 1979: too much exposure.
   ``I felt that doing the same show for that long might be like
being married to the same woman too long,'' he said.
   A fateful meeting in Owens' office in Bakersfield, Calif., led
to his return to the recording scene. Yoakam showed up one day and
he and Owens hit it off immediately.
   ``When I first saw him, I saw a rebel,'' Owens recalled. ``I saw
in him a freshness, an absolute attitude of `I'm going to play my
music my way.' He has great charisma and he could be the next big
superstar.
   ``He could be able to sell as many records as George Strait or
Randy Travis or some of the others.
   ``It's been brewing, this rage toward more traditional country
music. You began to see the tip of the cowboy hat and then the
hurricane came: Highway 101, the Desert Rose Band, Rodney Crowell
and all these people bringing good pickin' and attracting young
concert goers.''
   ``I guess I missed it (cutting records) more than I thought I
would. I remember my wife saying, `Get something to do or you're
going to kill us all.''
   So he teamed up with Yoakam and also released the solo album
``Hog Dog.'' He began scheduling concert appearances where his
famous red, white and blue guitar could be seen in public again.
Then the duet with Starr materialized.
   Owens described the ``Act Naturally'' duet as ``his version and
my version and our version and a little surprise or two along the
way. He gives a little Texas-type yell. I guess you'd call it
country rock.
   ``Ringo sings it better than ever. His voice is much broader
than it was when he was with the Beatles,'' he said. ``He was very
friendly and posed for pictures with anybody who asked. He was
about the most approachable famous person I've ever met.
   ``I'm thinking about how best the record can be received. I
don't want to gimmick it up.
   ``I've got a good feeling about the song. We did one song only,
but we talked about other things. We might do another track and may
do a video.''
   Owens said Starr has a keen sense of humor and would be a good
guest on ``Hee Haw.''
   ``He'd fit right in.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 28-30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
