<DOCNO> AP890418-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-KodakProducts Bjt   04-18 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kodak Products, Bjt,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Introduces Two Throwaway Cameras, New Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. introduced two new
disposable 35mm cameras today, one that can be used underwater and
another that has a special wide-angle lens to better capture scenic
views and city skylines.
   The company also showed off three new 35mm films and said it is
in the process of changing the packaging on its 200-speed Kodacolor
Gold film to include the words ``multi-purpose.''
   The packaging change was not related to the April 5 introduction
of OneFilm by Polaroid Corp., said Wilbur Prezzano, Kodak's general
manager of photographic products.
   OneFilm, Polaroid's line of 200-speed conventional film, is
touted by the company as the ideal all-purpose film for people who
are confused or tired of trying to figure out what film to buy.
   ``If this were an average day, there would be 100 million
pictures taken around the world, color negative pictures, taken
across a wide spectrum of lighting conditions, by different types
of people, different knowledges,'' Prezzano said Monday. ``To think
that those 100 million pictures would be best served by one product
... is incorrect.''
   He said the packaging change and the new products are part of a
continuing effort by Kodak to divide the overall photographic
market by selling products designed for specific uses or for
specific groups.
   ``I think that's part of a general trend in worldwide
manufacturing,'' said Eugene Glazer, a stock analyst for Dean
Witter Reynolds in New York. ``The days of coming up with new
products that are as homogenous as possible seem to be coming to an
end. Certainly, we are seeing that in photography.''
   Even Polaroid, which seemingly bucked the niche trend with its
one-size-fits-all new film, believes it's participating in
pigeonholing the world's amateur photographers.
   ``We see OneFilm as a niche product too. It just happens to be
the largest and most underdeveloped niche,'' said Alan Verch, a
spokesman for the Cambridge, Mass.-based company.
   Kodak's new cameras, while only having limited uses, are
nonetheless quite novel.
   The ``Stretch'' camera, which has a list price of $12.95,
produces unusual long and narrow prints, 3{ by 10 inches, with a
wide-angle 25mm lens. It can capture about one-third more area than
standard ``point-and-shoot'' 35mm cameras.
   It's for use outdoors only and comes loaded with a 12-exposure
roll of 200-speed Kodacolor Gold film.
   The ``Stretch'' camera will be available in Europe this summer.
A similar model also will be sold in Japan. The ``Stretch'' will be
available in the United States later this year.
   Kodak's other new camera, the ``Weekend 35,'' can take
photographs up to 12 feet underwater and comes loaded with a roll
of 24-exposure Kodacolor Gold 400-speed film.
   It's retail price is $13.95. Kodak will begin selling it in U.S.
coastal areas in late June.
   Disposable cameras have been sold in Japan for several years,
where they are a fast-growing product. Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd. of
Japan and Kodak introduced disposable models in this country in
1987. The models are aimed at tourists who neglect to bring their
cameras along on vacation. Kodak's new cameras are designed to
broaden the appeal of disposable models.
   Glazer said that these and other ``niche'' cameras _ Kodak also
has cameras designed for children and for teen-agers _ are going to
play a key role in the photographic industry in coming years.
   ``Each one, taken separately, is relatively unimportant, but in
combination, in total, I think they'll be extremely important.''
   But Michael Ellman, an analyst at Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co., said
he's not convinced that niche cameras are the wave of the future
because most people use one or two cameras; they don't want to rely
on all different kinds.
   The three new 35mm films Kodak introduced are:
   _A 125-speed Ektar film. Ektar is Kodak's premium film designed
for the advanced amateur photographer. Previously, it was only
available in 25-speed and 1000-speed.
   _A 1600-speed Kodacolor Gold film. This brings a very high speed
to Kodak's all-purpose color negative film.
   _An improved Kodacolor Gold 400-speed film with finer grain and
more accurate color.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
