<FIRST>r f PM-ConsolidatedGold     04-18 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consolidated Gold,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minorco Loses Another Round in Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa-linked Minorco S.A., the free
world's largest gold concern, has lost another round in its bid to
acquire the No. 2 gold producer Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   A federal judge in Manhattan on Monday refused to modify an
order barring Minorco from acquiring more Gold Fields stock.
   The decision by U.S. District Judge Michael B. Mukasey continues
a preliminary injunction he issued last October.
   Gold Fields has significant gold mining holdings in South
Africa, Australia and the United States, including 90 percent of
Newmont Gold, the largest gold producer in the country.
   Last fall, Minorco, a Luxembourg corporation largely controlled
by two South African concerns, Anglo American Corp. of South Africa
and De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., launched a $4.9 billion
hostile takeover bid _ since upped to $6 billion _ for Consolidated
Gold Fields.
   But Gold Fields, a British concern, resisted and filed an
antitrust action in New York, claiming that a takeover could result
in Minorco's ``dominating the strategically important world gold
market.''
   ``This court enjoined the takeover because the resulting
combination would control 32.3 percent of the non-communist world
gold market,'' Mukasey said in a 45-page opinion issued Monday.
   Minorco, through its various holdings, is the largest gold
producer in the West, accounting for 20.3 percent of all
production. Gold Fields, with about a 12 percent share, is the
second-largest, according to court papers.
   Mukasey's injunction also prevents Minorco from selling its Gold
Fields holdings to other entities within the South African
conglomerate without court approval.
   Minorco sought to modify the injunction, allowing it to complete
its acquisition of Gold Fields while promising to sell off certain
U.S., Australian and South African assets within a year to resolve
antitrust allegations made by Gold Fields.
   But Mukasey rejected that bid saying there was no guarantee that
Anglo and DeBeers wouldn't eventually repurchase the divested
concerns because South African laws enable companies there ``to
conceal the source of their overseas investments in order to avoid
the effects of anti-apartheid laws.''
   Last month, a federal appeals court upheld Mukasey's preliminary
injunction on antitrust grounds and ordered him to consider whether
the takeover bid violates U.S. securities laws.
   In Monday's ruling, however, Mukasey rejected Gold Fields'
claims that Minorco had failed to fully disclose its South African
interests in violation of U.S. securities laws.
   Gold Fields sought to widen the scope of the injunction by
claiming Minorco violated the anti-fraud provisions of U.S.
securities laws, for allegedly ``making and false and misleading
statements'' about how much control South African corporations and
individuals have over it.
   Gold Fields claimed the Oppenheimer family of South Africa
indirectly controls Minorco, Anglo American and DeBeers and that
the stigma of South Africa's apartheid racial policy could make it
difficult to conduct business in some countries.
   But Mukasey found those claims were only part of a delaying
tactic to push Minorco's offer past its April 26 deadline, which
under British law would bar it from renewing its bid for more than
a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
