<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest 1stLd-Writethru f0006 04-18 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0006,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>NWA Board Decides To Explore Alternatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Davis announcement of financing details, add
analyst comment and edit, INSERTS 14 new grafs after 4th graf pvs, `But
NWA ... Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Gov. Rudy Perpich...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' parent company may begin
negotiating with suitors but may also consider restructuring moves
including the acquisition of another company or liquidation of the
airline, its board has decided.
   ``All interested parties will be given a fair chance to
demonstrate their ability to consummate a transaction,'' NWA Inc.
said in a statement Monday announcing that its board of directors
had given permission to management to negotiate with interested
buyers, including billionaire oilman Marvin Davis.
   ``Non-public information would be provided to qualified third
parties who execute an acceptable confidentiality agreement,'' NWA
said.
   But NWA repeated its contention that Davis' $2.7 billion,
$90-a-share bid is inadequate, and said it would give strong
preference to ``all-cash, fully financed bids.''
   Meanwhile, Davis announced in a statement released early today
how he would finance his bid for the nation's fourth-largest
airline.
   The financing package totals approximately $3.3 billion and
would be used for the acquisition of NWA and to refinance, as
necessary, NWA's existing senior debt, according to the statement.
   Citicorp North America Inc. and Citibank, N.A., would provide
$2.4 billion of senior debt, of which Citibank has committed to
lend $500 million and would syndicate the balance with a group of
other major banks, the statement said.
   Also, Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. would raise
$600 million of subordinated debt.
   Approximately $300 million for the acquisition would be
contributed in the form of equity by a Davis family investment
partnership.
   In addition, Citibank would provide a $250 million back-up
revolving line of credit to be available to supplement NWA's
working capital, the statement said.
   ``We believe this is a very strong financing package,'' Davis
said. ``With this financing package, no sales of any strategic
assets will be required to meet the company's financial obligations.
   ``In fact, we would expect _ and could comfortably finance _ the
expansion of NWA's passenger capacity by over 30 percent over the
next six years.''
   State officials have fought Davis' takeover effort because they
fear that Davis would have to sell part of NWA to finance the deal.
   Northwest and state officials could not be reached immediately
to comment on Davis' financing package.
   NWA's statement, stressing that no decisions have been made,
also noted possible restructuring moves including the acquisition
of another company, a partial or complete liquidation of the
airline, a repurchase of shares, a special dividend to
shareholders, or a sale of equity to third parties.
   Analysts said the board's announcement accomplishes several
things.
   Dick Warden, an analyst with IDS Financial Services Inc., said
it could flush out other potential bidders.
   ``Maybe they're saying, `Is there anyone out there who's
serious? If not, let's get back to the business of running an
airline,' '' Warden said.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich, who has led efforts to stop Davis from buying
NWA, said the announcement indicated Northwest officials were
``just protecting their flank'' against stockholder discontent.
   Perpich, who met with Davis during the weekend in San Francisco,
said he's convinced that Davis is determined to continue with his
bid to buy the airline. which has its headquarters in this
Minneapolis suburb.
   ``Davis has been at this for quite some time, over a year, and
it isn't just a lark for him,'' Perpich said. ``He's real and
determined.''
   The governor said he would ask legislative leaders today for
quick action on a legislative package unveiled Friday that aims to
protect workers, consumers and the state if Northwest is taken over.
   Two other investment groups also have been identified as
possible suitors for the airline but have not publicly stated their
intentions.
</TEXT>
