<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     04-18 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Short-term Interest Rates Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in the regular weekly auction to the lowest level
in two months.
   On Monday, the Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.57 percent, down
from 8.71 percent last week.
   Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 8.59 percent, down from 8.78 percent last week.
   The rates were the lowest since Feb. 21, when three-month bills
sold for 8.51 percent and six-month bills averaged 8.50 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.88 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,783.40 and and 9.11 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,565.70.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 9.48
percent last week after averaging 9.47 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
