<FIRST>u f PM-HousingStarts 1stLd-Writethru f0026 04-18 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0026,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Fell 5.4 Percent in March</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The 5.4, to change level to 1.4 million sted
1.39 million due to rounding. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction, suffering under the
impact of rising mortgage rates, fell 5.4 percent in March as work
on single-family homes slowed to the weakest pace in more than four
years, the government said today.
   The housing report by the Commerce Department was likely to
intensify fears that the economy is in danger of toppling into a
new recession. Housing, because it is so sensitive to rising
interest rates, is often a harbinger of troubles in other sectors
of the economy.
   The report said applications for building permits, a good
indicator of future activity, plunged by 13.7 percent in March, the
biggest monthly drop since a 14 percent decline in October 1981, in
the early stages of the last recession.
   The 5.4 percent decline in construction of new homes and
apartments was the second monthly decrease, following a 12 percent
drop in February. It left construction work at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.4 million units last month as work on
both single-family homes and apartment buildings weakened.
   Construction of single-family homes dropped below the 1 million
mark to an annual rate of 994,000 units, the slowest pace since
January 1985.
   Starts of multi-family units fell 8.8 percent to an annual rate
of 403,000 units.
   Econommists have blamed rising mortgage rates for the housing
slowdown. Fixed-rate mortgages are now averaging 11.11 percent, up
by almost one full percentaage point from a year ago, according to
a national survey by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   The Federal Reserve over the past year has been pushing interest
rates higher in an effort to dampen inflationary pressures. But
President Bush and various members of Congress have expressed fears
that the Fed may be in danger of overdoing the credit-tightening. A
growing number of economists have started to predict that a new
recession is likely to begin by late this year or early in 1990.
   The weakness in March was led by a steep 34.1 percent drop in
construction activity in the Northeast, a region which until
recently had been experiencing a building boom triggered by
improving fortunes of high-technology industries in the area.
   But in March, Northeast construction starts fell to an annual
rate of 149,000 units, the slowest building pace in the region
since September 1983.
   Starts of new homes and apartments were off 5.2 percent in the
South, dropping to an annual rate of 546,000 units while starts in
the West dropped by 1 percent to a rate of 395,000 units.
   The Midwest was the only region of the country to enjoy an
increase in activity, with housing construction climbing by 10.4
percent to an annual rate of 307,000 units.
   The 13.7 percent decline in building permits in March followed a
6.1 percent fall in February and left permits at an annual rate of
1.22 million units, the slowest pace since October 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
