<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     04-18 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0366</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices opened sharply higher in brisk
trading today, influenced by government reports on consumer prices
and housing starts.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials surged 21.26 points to
2,359.05 after a half-hour of trading at 10 a.m. EDT.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by about 15 to 4 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 810 issues up, 220 down and 448 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 35.26 million shares.
   The Labor Department reported today that the Consumer Price
Index jumped 0.5 percent in March, fueled by higher costs for food
and energy. That followed rises of 0.6 percent in January and 0.4
percent in February and put the annual inflation rate at 6.1
percent, higher than the 4.4 percent increase in 1988.
   Analysts said the March figure was in line with market
expectations and fit in with other economic data in recent weeks
indicating that inflationary pressures may be easing and that the
economy may be growing at a slower pace.
   ``The bond market is acting very well and the stock market is
following suit,'' said John Burnett, senior vice president,
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   Although inflation is still running at a rate many consider too
high for long-run equilibrium, ``the perception is that maybe we're
at or getting near a peak in interest rates,'' Burnett said.
   In a second report the Commerce Department said that housing
starts fell 5.4 percent last month, pressured by rising mortgage
rates.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.15 to 170.20.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index jumped
1.08 to 337.30.
   On Monday, the market finished narrowly mixed as investors
awaited the consumer price report. The Dow Jones industrial average
closed 0.73 point higher at 2,337.79.
   Declining issues barely edged out advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 762 issues down, 697 up and 521 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 128.54 million shares, one of the
slowest trading days of the year, down from 169.78 million in
Friday's session.
</TEXT>
