<FIRST>r f PM-Fairchild-Carlyle     04-18 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairchild-Carlyle,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fairchild Enters Into Talks With Suitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fairchild Industries Inc. has decided to
begin negotiations with the Carlyle Group for a possible purchase
of the company, the aerospace electronics company announced today.
   Carlyle, a Washington-based investment partnership, on April 12
offered $17 per share for all outstanding common shares.
   At a meeting Monday, the Fairchild board appointed a special
committee of outside directors to consider the proposal and other,
unspecified matters. The board acted on the measure, before the
Carlyle offer expired at 6 p.m., Fairchild spokeswoman Deborah
Tucker said today.
   Carlyle originally offered $15.50 per share and boosted its
offer to $16.30. The Fairchild board, however, rejected both offers.
   In a prepared statement on April 12, Carlyle indicated that
discussions had been held with Fairchild's financial advisors.
Carlyle owns about 14.8 percent of Fairchild's stock.
   The proposed purchase price is 72 percent over the closing
market price per share on July 25, the date when Carlyle acquired
its first Fairchild stock.
   Fairchild stock closed Monday on the New York Stock Exchange at
$15.75.
   Security National Bank has agreed to provide $330 million to
finance the deal, according to Carlyle. The outstanding common
stock is worth about $250 million, but costs associated with the
deal would probably push the total cost of the deal up to about
$400 million, according to Stephen Norris, a managing director of
Carlyle.
   In a prepared statement today, Carlyle said is was pleased with
the announcement and planned no further public comment at this time.
   Norris has stated that Carlyle has no intention of breaking up
the company.
   Fairchild's annual meeting is scheduled for April 26.
</TEXT>
