<DOCNO> AP890418-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Pickens     04-18 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Pickens,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Says No Hostile Intent in Koito Stock Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporate takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens
Jr. arrived in Japan Tuesday after denying any hostile intent in
his purchase of the largest block of shares in Koito Manufacturing
Co., a Japanese auto parts maker.
   ``There was nothing hostile about it. We're not trying to take
over Koito,'' Pickens said in an interview broadcast Tuesday by the
Japan Broadcasting Corp.
   Pickens also called the purchase of stock a ``test case'' for
access to the Japanese market by American investors, and said he
was traveling to Japan to explain the move to Koito management.
   As of March 31, Pickens held 32.4 million shares, or 20.2
percent, of Koito stock. Koito is a major supplier of lighting
systems to Toyota Motor Corp., which owns 19.1 percent of its
shares, and to Nissan Motor Corp., which owns 5.95 percent.
   ``We evaluated the situation and felt that Koito was a company
that was one of the best in its business worldwide,'' Pickens said
in the interview, conducted before his departure from the United
States. ``We thought it was a good investment.''
   Pickens warned that public sentiment in the United States would
turn against Japan if it does not allow access for American
investors.
   ``Japanese are making a big mistake when they don't invite
Americans into Japan as America has invited the Japanese in,''
Pickens said. He said his investment was ``a test case to see what
the attitude is toward an American investor in Japan.''
   Many Japanese analysts have looked at Pickens' purchase as a
possible ``greenmail'' attempt. In greenmail, a hostile corporate
suitor makes profits when his stock is purchased at a premium by
another shareholder friendly to the company.
   Hostile takeovers are still relatively rare in Japan.
   Japanese news reports have said the Finance Ministry is
investigating possible irregularities in Pickens' acquisition of
the shares, including incomplete or tardy disclosures to
authorities regarding the purchase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
