<FIRST>r f PM-C&amp;SShareholders 1stLd-Writethru f0017 04-18 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-C&amp;S Shareholders, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0017,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>C&amp;S Shareholders Meet For First Time Since NCNB's Takeover Attempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with action at meeting. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Lynn Easley
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens and Southern Corp. Chairman Bennett A.
Brown, addressing shareholders today, painted takeover suitor NCNB
Corp. as an institution more concerned with making a name for
itself than with sound banking practices.
   Brown urged the shareholders to support the C&amp;S board in its
rejection of NCNB's $2.4 billion stock transfer offer.
   ``Let me put it bluntly. NCNB cannot afford C&amp;S,'' Brown said to
loud applause.
   Brown repeatedly referred to NCNB's recent acquisition of a 20
percent stake in First RepublicBank Corp. of Texas, now called NCNB
Texas, saying it was an example of NCNB's risk-taking approach.
That acquisition came after the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
picked NCNB to manage the ailing Texas bank.
   ``It (NCNB) is managed with the purpose of making a name for
itself among the world's largest banking institutions,'' Brown
said. ``That's not our mission.''
   Brown said shareholders would benefit more from C&amp;S'
``risk-averse'' approach to banking, which he said provided more
sustained growth.
   ``Neither the initial offer nor the street-rumored offers come
close to reflecting the value of the C&amp;S franchise. The fact is
that C&amp;S is already performing in a manner that produces reliable
long-term value for our shareholders,'' he said.
   He was given a standing ovation when he concluded his address.
   Later, Brown was asked by a shareholder whether he would
consider putting the NCNB proposal to a shareholders' vote. Brown
said he would not.
   ``It is the board of directors' responsibility. Shareholders can
vote to elect or replace the board,'' Brown said.
   Today's annual meeting in Atlanta was the first gathering of C&amp;S
shareholders since North Carolina-based NCNB Inc. made an
unsolicited bid last month to acquire the Atlanta-based banking
company.
   Though matters pertaining directly to the NCNB bid were not on
the agenda, the proposed takeover drew much attention to the
meeting and had been expected to dominate discussion.
   In official business, the shareholders approved a measure that
would authorize the board to consider the effect any acquisition
would have on C&amp;S employees, customers, suppliers, creditors and
communities where the bank does business. The vote count was not
immediately available.
   C&amp;S spokesman Scott Scredon said 16 states now require company
boards of directors to take the broad view in deciding whether to
agree to a takeover, but Georgia law gives companies the option of
whether to go beyond shareholder interest.
   Lynn Easley, spokeswoman for NCNB in Charlotte, N.C., said
Monday the company did not plan to have a representative attend
today's meeting in Atlanta.
   NCNB last month offered to merge with C&amp;S under a stock transfer
at the time valued at $2.4 billion. The C&amp;S board April 3 rejected
the offer, saying it was inadequate and not in the best interest of
the shareholders.
   Despite repeated requests from NCNB Chairman Hugh L. McColl Jr.,
C&amp;S officials have refused to meet with NCNB to discuss the offer
further. McColl has said all aspects of the deal are negotiable,
though he said NCNB will not make a cash offer.
   In a letter Monday to Brown, McColl said NCNB would make a
``substantial price increase'' in the proposal if C&amp;S would agree
to a face-to-face meeting.
   Last week, the two companies engaged in an increasingly heated
exchange of statements, in which C&amp;S said the takeover bid was
senseless and riddled with regulatory hurdles, and NCNB accused C&amp;S
of waging a disinformation campaign.
   McColl, in a visit to Atlanta last week, said C&amp;S shareholders
should decide whether to accept the offer. He did not specify how
he intended to get the issue to a shareholder vote.
</TEXT>
