<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Slip On Rain, Wetter Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell slightly
this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade following overnight
showers in the Midwest and a National Weather Service forecast for
more rain early next week.
   Corn and soybean prices had risen sharply Monday on dry-weather
fears fueled by private forecasters' long-range predictions for
little rain and rising temperatures in the Corn Belt.
   But scattered showers in the region last night and this morning
dampened the bullish enthusiasm, as did the National Weather
Service's latest 6-to-10-day outlook, which was issued after
Monday's close.
   Nevertheless, analysts said the National Weather Service's track
record so far this spring has been spotty.
   ``Their 6-to-10-day forecasts have been consistently wrong,''
said analyst Susan Leighty of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was } cents to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.09 a bushel; corn was 2 cents to
3\ cents lower with May at $2.74} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cents lower with May at $1.97} a bushel; soybeans were 2} cents to
5 cents lower with May at $7.44{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .48 cent higher with June at 71.80
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .52 cent higher with
April at 76.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to .20
cent higher with April at 40.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to .18 cent higher with May at 33.80 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Monday.
</TEXT>
