<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GeorgiaPower     04-18 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia Power,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Investigating Georgia Power Tax Accounting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tax accounting practices at Georgia Power Co.,
already under investigation by a federal grand jury, are being
reviewed by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The federal agency began its own investigation last month,
according to papers filed with the SEC. The probe includes Georgia
Power and its parent firm, the Southern Co.
   The U.S. Justice Department last year began investigating
alleged tax fraud at the utility after a Georgia Power accountant
provided the Internal Revenue Service with information regarding
possible violations of federal law in the method by which spare
parts were accounted for in financial documents. A grand jury in
Atlanta currently is hearing testimony in that investigation.
   An attorney for the Southern Co. said the SEC activity was a
``natural outgrowth'' of the Justice Department probe.
   The SEC is looking at how the utility holding company handled
the disclosure of financial and tax accounting in proxy statements,
reports, documents and other securities materials submitted to the
SEC and investors, according to Southern.
   Ronald L. Crawford, assistant regional commissioner for the SEC
in Atlanta, said agency policy prohibited comment on investigations.
   Southern is the parent firm of Georgia Power, Alabama Power,
Gulf Power, Mississippi Power and Savannah Electric.
   Thomas J. Hartland, an attorney representing Southern, said the
company was not surprised by the SEC investigation, though the
federal agency did not formally notify the company.
   ``We would have been surprised had the SEC not undertaken this
kind of fact-finding in administering the Holding Company Act and
securities laws,'' Hartland said.
   The Southern Co. did not mention the SEC investigation in its
recent annual report to stockholders, but a company spokesman said
the report already had been printed when the company learned of the
probe.
   The investigation was noted in the financial statement that
publicly owned companies must file annually with the SEC.
</TEXT>
