<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-DealBlocked 1stLd-Writethru f0082 04-18 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deal Blocked, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0082,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Blocks Japanese Deal To Buy NJ Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS dateline to Washington sted New York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has temporarily
blocked a Japanese company from buying a U.S. manufacturer involved
in nuclear weapons production, the Energy Department said today
   Tokuyama Soda Co. of Tokyo, a major producer of chlorine and
caustic soda, is seeking to buy General Ceramics of Haskell, N.J.,
a $30 million-a-year ceramics manufacturer, for $59 million.
   Douglas Elmets, an Energy Department spokesman, said the General
Ceramics sales was being blocked and, ``We're speaking with them to
resolve the situation.''
   Elmets said he could provide no other details.
   The New York Times reported today that the Energy Department
objected to the deal because of classified work that General
Ceramics is doing for the department's Y-12 plant in Oak Ridge,
Tenn., which makes parts for the U.S. nuclear weapons program.
   The Times said it was the first time a foreign acquisition has
been stopped since enactment of legislation in August that
empowered the president to halt investments that endanger national
security.
   Among General Ceramics' products are beryllium ceramics, which
are used in electronic circuits that are components of the nuclear
weapons thought to be made at the plant, the newspaper said.
   The new law under which the Bush administration stopped the
acquisition established a clear and public procedure for review and
gives the administration the power to go to court to block such
deals.
   The review of the deal was conducted by the Committee on Foreign
Investment in the United States, which is comprised of
representatives of the treasury, state, commerce, defense, justice
and energy departments and the Office of the U.S. trade
representative.
   The Times reported that General Ceramics is holding discussions
with the government and with Tokuyama to resolve the issues raised
by the administration.
   General Ceramics said in a statement that Tokuyama Soda
``expects to proceed with the proposed transaction if and when
arrangements satisfactory to the government have been worked out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
