<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   04-18 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed strongly higher Tuesday as the
release of favorable U.S. economic statistics helped to ease the
market's fears about inflation.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 19.7 points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,074.4. The index rose as
much as 23.3 points at mid-afternoon. At its lowest, the index was
up 0.7 point at the opening.
   Volume was moderate, with 530.8 million shares changing hands,
up from Monday's light 469.4 million shares.
   Shares moved up tentatively through the morning but then took
off following news that U.S. consumer prices for March rose 0.5
percent, slightly better than market expectations, and that U.S.
housing starts unexpectedly dropped 5.4 percent for the month.
   The reports were doubly effective at reassuring the market,
coming after Friday's spate of favorable economic news that also
sent the market higher.
   The latest economic figures, signaling a slowing of the U.S.
economy and a consequent reduction in inflationary pressures, also
gave a sharp boost to prices on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones
industrial average was up nearly 30 points at the time of the
London close.
   The numbers ``gave the market some short-term satisfaction.
People's perceptions of interest rates and inflation have moved
into the background,'' one trader said.
</TEXT>
