<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Brokers     04-18 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokers,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Morgan Stanley, Bear Stearns Show Income Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Wall Street investment firms Tuesday
reported sharp drops in quarterly earnings, with profits down 18
percent at Morgan Stanley Group Inc. and 22 percent at Bear Stearns
Cos.
   Morgan Stanley reported net income of $81.1 million, or $2.02
per share, for the quarter ended March 31, compared with $98.6
million, or $2.55 a share, in the same 1988 quarter.
   The firm reported revenue of $1.24 billion, a 5 percent rise
from $975 million in the first quarter of last year, primarily due
to a 48 percent increase in interest and dividend revenue.
   Bear Stearns reported quarterly earnings of $41.1 million, or 47
cents a share, compared with $52.4 million, or 59 cents a share
last year. The drop came despite a 26 percent rise in revenue to
$624 million from $494 million in the same 1988 period.
   The earnings declines come during a weak business environment on
Wall Street.
   Morgan Stanley reported a heavy drop in revenue from trading,
down to $196 million from $239 million, and investments, which
plunged to $572,000 from $4.7 million.
   Morgan Stanley executives said in a statement that ``difficult
conditions'' in debt markets were offset by high financial advisory
revenues; international equities sales and trading; and foreign
exchange and commodities business.
   The firm reported total capital of $2.5 billion.
   Bear Stearns, the holding company for the investment banking and
brokerage firm Bear Stearns &amp; Co., did not break down its earnings
statement. It reported total capital of $1.4 billion.
</TEXT>
