<SECOND>BC-Maxwell-Jerusalem Post,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishing Magnate Seeking Control of Jerusalem Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper and publishing magnate Robert Maxwell is
trying to buy a controlling interest in the English-language
Jerusalem Post Daily, his office said Tuesday.
   ``We can confirm that a report we have seen from Jerusalem is
correct but we are not making a statement about it,'' said Judy
Welsh, a press officer for Maxwell, chairman of Mirror Group
Newspapers Ltd.
   London's Financial Times business daily said Maxwell appeared
likely to secure 55 percent of the Jerusalem Post in a joint bid
with Charles Bronfman, head of the Claridge investment group based
in Montreal, Canada.
   The report quoted Maxwell as saying if the joint bid was
successful he would be the managing partner.
   The Financial Times said the 55 percent stake was marketed by
Koor Industries, which it described as Israel's largest industrial
group.
   The Jerusalem Post also publishes a weekly international edition
that claims to have 170,000 subscribers worldwide.
   Maxwell last year bought a stake in the publishers of the Tel
Aviv-based Hebrew newspaper, Ma'ariv.
