<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-18 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0425</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices continued rising in active trading
today, after two government reports helped ease market fears about
inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 37.39 to 2,375.18
at 2 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator had gained 28.78 points at
midday.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by about 13 to 5 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 1,034 issues up, 398 down and 485
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 153.24 million shares.
   The Labor Department reported today that consumer prices, as
measured by the Consumer Price Index, jumped 0.5 percent in March,
fueled by higher costs for food and energy. That followed rises of
0.6 percent in January and 0.4 percent in February and put the
annual inflation rate at 6.1 percent, higher than the 4.4 percent
increase in 1988.
   ``People were expecting the numbers to be worse,'' said Thomas
Walsh, head of equity trading for Nikko Securities International.
``It's not a great number but the street is viewing it as an OK
number and it has stimulated buy interest.''
   Analysts said the March figure was in line with market
expectations and fit in with other economic data in recent weeks
suggesting that inflationary pressures may be subsiding.
   Although inflation is still running at a rate many consider too
high for long-run stability, ``the perception is that maybe we're
at or getting near a peak in interest rates,'' said John Burnett,
senior vice president at the investment firm of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette.
   A second report by the Commerce Department that housing starts
fell 5.4 percent and building permits plunged by 13.7 percent last
month was taken as further evidence that the economy is slowing and
that it could lead to lower inflation, observers said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 2 points to 171.05.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index advanced
2.20 to 338.42.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Northwest Airlines was
up 6} to 97 after its parent company announced Monday that it might
sell the nation's fourth-largest airline, amid takeover threats
from billionaire oilman Marvin Davis.
   AT&amp;T was up ~ at 33[, Exxon had gained 1[ to 43\ and General
Electric was up 1[ to 48\.
   K Mart was down 1\ to 38, RJR Nabisco had dropped ] to 85\ and
Ramada was off } at 11].
