<FIRST>r f AM-Fairchild-Carlyle     04-18 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fairchild-Carlyle,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fairchild To Hold Talks With Suitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fairchild Industries Inc. said Tuesday it
will negotiate with suitor The Carlyle Group, which has offered to
buy the aerospace communications company in a deal worth about $400
million.
   Fairchild's board Monday appointed a special committee of
outside directors that asked the company's legal and financial
advisers to start discussions with Carlyle, a Washington-based
investment partnership that is offering $17 a share.
   In addition, the committee authorized advisers to hold
discussions with ``any other interested parties and continue to
explore other approaches designed to maximize stockholder values,''
the company said in a statement.
   Fairchild has rejected offers by Carlyle of $15.50 and $16.30
per share. The latest offer expired Monday. Carlyle owns about 14.8
percent of Fairchild's stock.
   The proposed purchase price is 72 percent over the closing
market price per share on July 25, when Carlyle first acquired
Fairchild stock.
   The outstanding common stock is worth about $250 million, but
costs associated with the deal would probably push the total cost
of the deal up to about $400 million, said Stephen Norris, a
Carlyle managing director.
   Carlyle said in a statement Tuesday it was pleased with the
announcement to hold talks about the deal but did not elaborate.
   Fairchild's annual meeting is set for April 26.
   Carlyle, founded two years ago, has pursued a series of friendly
takeovers and last year acquired Oakite Products Inc., a New Jersey
chemical company, in partnership with the French bank Paribas.
   Carlyle also made an unsolicited offer for Chi Chi's Inc., a
Louisville, Ky., restaurant chain. Chi Chi's was acquired by
another company and Carlyle profited on its investment.
</TEXT>
