<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Retreat On Rain Forecast, Yeutter Comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade on a forecast for rain
in the Corn Belt and signs that the United States is becoming
stingier with its wheat exports.
   The National Weather Service, in a forecast issued late Monday,
predicted average to above-average rainfall in the Midwest early
next week, an outlook that prompted modest selling of corn and
soybean futures.
   Many private meteorologists continued to predict dry weather,
though, which limited the declines.
   Wheat futures prices dipped after an Agriculture Department
official said the agency had suspended its grain export subsidy
program, which has been a major channel for large wheat sales to
the Soviet Union and China.
   But Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter later said the
announcement was in error and that the USDA had made no decision to
suspend the program, despite relatively low stock levels of wheat
and dry-weather damage to the ripening winter wheat crop.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.07 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.75\ a bushel; oats were { cent to
2 cents lower with May at $1.98{ a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents
lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $7.48 a bushel.
