<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BankBid     04-18 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Bid,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citizens and Southern Affirms Rejection of NCNB Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens and Southern Corp. on Tuesday reaffirmed
its rejection of a $2.4 billion hostile takeover bid by NCNB Corp.,
saying both companies should ``get back to the business of
banking.''
   C&amp;S's board of directors voted unanimously against the offer
shortly after Chairman Bennett A. Brown told shareholders that
NCNB, a Charolotte, N.C.-based banking company, was interested only
in gambling on risky expansions.
   ``We will continue to fight all the way,'' he said. ``We have
better staying power.''
   In a statement issued later, Brown said the board sent a letter
to NCNB's board explaining the rejection and ``suggesting that both
of these institutions get back to the business of banking and avoid
further distraction and expense.''
   Brown urged shareholders to support the C&amp;S board in its April 3
rejection of NCNB's stock transfer offer made last month, saying
NCNB stock might be overvalued. The board Tuesday simply reaffirmed
its earlier vote.
   ``Let me put it bluntly. NCNB cannot afford C&amp;S,'' Brown said to
loud applause.
   ``Let's get beyond all the recent speculation on Wall Street and
in the press and face reality,'' he said. ``The NCNB offer makes no
sense. It would be bad for C&amp;S, bad for our shareholders, and bad
for our employees, customers and the communities we serve.''
   Despite repeated requests from NCNB Chairman Hugh L. McColl Jr.,
C&amp;S has refused to discuss the offer further. McColl has said all
aspects of the deal are negotiable, but that NCNB will not make a
cash offer.
   In a letter Monday to Brown, McColl said NCNB would make a
``substantial price increase'' in the proposal if C&amp;S agrees to a
face-to-face meeting.
   Brown said NCNB's recent acquisition of a 20 percent stake in
First RepublicBank Corp. of Texas, now called NCNB Texas, was an
example of NCNB's high risk-taking approach. That acquisition came
after the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. picked NCNB to manage the
ailing Texas bank.
   ``NCNB has no financial flexibility,'' Brown said. ``Its
management has invited us to gamble on both Texas and taxes. I will
tell you it is of very questionable value at best.''
   The North Carolina bank, he said, cannot put up cash for the
acquisition, ``so they have no way of protecting the value that our
shareholders would expect in a stock transaction.''
   NCNB spokeswoman Ginny Mackin said the company had no immediate
comment Tuesday's developments. NCNB said it did not have a
representative at the meeting.
   When asked by a shareholder, Brown said he would not consider
putting the NCNB proposal to a shareholders' vote. ``It is the
board of directors' responsibility. Shareholders can vote to elect
or replace the board,'' Brown said.
   Also Tuesday, C&amp;S employees bought a full-page ad in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution addressed to shareholders. It said the
employees stand with management against the NCNB offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
