<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Banks     04-18 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Banks,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Big Banks Report Profit Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Five of the nation's largest bank holding companies _ Citicorp,
Bankers Trust Corp., Wells Fargo &amp; Co., Continental Bank Corp. and
Mellon Bank Corp. _ reported an increase Tuesday in their
first-quarter profit over a year ago.
   Meanwhile, Beverly Hills, Calif.-based Great Western Financial
Corp., one of the biggest U.S. thrift companies, had flat earnings.
Its net income totaled $57.2 million, or 45 cents a share, vs.
$56.1 million and 45 cents in 1988.
   Citicorp, the nation's largest banking concern, based in New
York, said net income for the three months ended March 31 soared 48
percent to $529 million, or $1.52 a share, from $358 million, or
$1.01 a share, in 1988. The latest quarter included a $77 million
gain from the sale of a building in Tokyo.
   Bankers Trust, based in New York, said it netted $164.3 million,
or $2.02 a share, up 30 percent from last year's earnings of $126.0
million, or $1.61 per share.
   Wells Fargo, based in San Francisco, had a profit of $141.5
million, or $2.56 per share, an 18 percent rise over net income of
$120.4 million, or $2.15 per share, in 1988.
   Continental Bank, located in Chicago, said it earned $76
million, or $1.23 per share, up 10 percent from $69 million, or
$1.10, in 1988. The 1989 quarter included a $17 million gain from
the sale of real estate while last year's quarter included a $15
million gain from a pension settlement.
   Pittsburgh-based Mellon Bank said its profit more than tripled
to $77 million, or $1.67 per share, from $25 million, or 65 cents
per share, in 1988.
   Citicorp said strength in core businesses such as consumer
banking and in its investment banking sector more than offset weak
foreign exchange markets and a rise in expenses.
   Net interest income rose 8 percent to $1.8 billion from $1.7
billion, while overall revenue, including non-interest income,
jumped 14 percent to $3.5 billion from $3.04 billion.
   Total expenses were up 7 percent to $2.6 billion from $2.4
billion. That included a 27 percent increase in its provision for
possible credit losses to $358 million from $283 million.
   Bankers Trust said it's improvement in quarterly income resulted
mainly from increased non-interest revenue, although that was
partially offset by a higher loan-loss provision.
   Non-interest revenue totaled $485.4 million for the first
quarter, up 47 percent over $154.6 million a year ago, while
non-interest expenses was up 23 percent to $437.5 million. Net
interest income remained unchanged at $238 million.
   During the quarter Bankers Trust's loan-loss provision rose to
$35 million from $10 million.
   Wells Fargo said its net interest income totaled $544 million
for the quarter, compared with $478.6 million a year ago.
Non-interest income rose 19 percent to $185.4 million from $156.2
million last year.
   Non-interest expense totaled $386.5 million, up from $371.6
million a year ago. The increase was due primarily to the ongoing
expenses of Barclays Bank of California, which was acquired in the
second quarter.
   The provision for loan losses in the first quarter was $100
million, compared with $75 million in the quarter of 1988.
   Continental Bank said its latest results were the best for a
first quarter, with all its business sectors showing strength. It
said total revenue rose 7 percent to $292 million. Expenses
declined from a year ago, reflecting a corporate restructuring that
included employee cuts.
   The provision for loan losses totaled $19 million, compared to
$10 million a year ago.
   Mellon's quarterly net interest income reached $212 million, up
11 percent, from $190 million in the 1988. Its non-interest income
also rose, to $212 milion from $190 million. Total operating
expenses fell 15 percent to $283 million from $298 million.
</TEXT>
