<FIRST>u f AM-EasternPilots Bjt   04-18 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Pilots, Bjt,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikebound Carrier Highlights Flying Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trying to overcome skepticism about its rebuilding
plans, strike-crippled Eastern Airlines enrolled more pilot
recruits and Tuesday ran full-page ads featuring pilots who have
crossed the picket lines.
   ``We're building a better, stronger, more unified airline and we
are as proud as ever to wear the Eastern uniform,'' said ads with a
photo of three veteran pilots and a list of nearly 200 other
pilots. They ran in the New York Times, Washington Post and the
Miami Herald and will run again next week, said company spokesman
Robin Matell.
   Matell also said Eastern this week began six-week training
courses for 79 new pilots. Two previous classes of 34 each will
complete training in mid- and late-May, the company said.
   ``Many of them rank with the caliber of pilot flying for Eastern
many years,'' said Frank Causey, Eastern's vice president for
flight operations.
   Pilots union spokesman Ron Cole scoffed at Eastern's claims,
saying they're part of ``a publicity blitz they've got on right
now'' to try to bolster the parent Texas Air's claim that Eastern
won't be sold and is being rebuilt as a smaller, efficient carrier.
   ``This is a misguided attempt to show the bankruptcy court and
the pilots that Mr. Lorenzo's downsizing effort is working. It
hasn't worked before and it isn't working now,'' Cole said.
   Company hopes of overcoming the March 4 Machinists union strike
were undercut when 3,400 of the 3,600 pilots honored Machinists
picket lines. Without the pilots, Eastern has been stuck at just
over 100 flights a day, or 10 percent of its pre-strike schedule.
   The company claims it can rebuild without the unions, but many
industry analysts have expressed doubts that Eastern could come
back generating enough revenues to satisfy creditors. Texas Air
said assets will be sold to raise cash, but the unions continue to
hope for a buyer to rescue Eastern, which is in Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization.
   Cole said company officials have been calling striking pilots at
home in hopes of luring them back to work and sent a videotape to
the pilots' homes. He said retired Eastern pilots, other Eastern
employees who have pilots' licenses and even disabled pilots have
been called. Even one fired pilot was called, Cole claimed.
   Matell said a company pilots communications committee has been
keeping up contacts with pilots. He said the committee has gone
through pilots' lists making calls and may have unknowingly called
disabled pilots. Matell noted that pilots must pass physical
examinations before flying again.
   Causey said the newly recruited pilots have an average 15{ years
of flying experience, with military, corporate or commuter airline
experience common and even some pilots from major carriers.
   The Air Line Pilots Association has said there is an
industrywide shortage of experienced pilots and Cole said Eastern
is offering a misleading appraisal of its recruits.
   Those participating in the ad campaign see it differently.
   ``I was flabbergasted at my fellow pilots, that so many chose to
buy the ALPA line about Frank Lorenzo,'' said Paul Richardson, a
26-year Eastern pilot. ``For me, it was a non-decision. Eastern's
been very good to me, as it has to all pilots.''
   The flying pilots said they've had few problems with strikers,
other than placards shoved in front of their cars and other minor
incidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
