<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     04-18 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Closes Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices finished sharply higher today after
two economic reports helped ease market fears about inflation.
   The market shot up at the opening kicked off by active program
trading that soon led to a broad-based rally.
   The rally followed a surge in the bond market after news that
housing starts were down dramatically and consumer prices rose less
than expected in March.
   Analysts said the two reports helped ease concerns about rising
inflation and provided further evidence that the economy slowed
last month.
   The Commerce Department reported that housing starts fell 5.4
percent in March while applications for building permits plunged
13.7 percent.
   Consumer prices jumped 0.5 percent last month, slightly below
market expectations of about 0.6 percent, according to a report
from the Labor Department.
   ``The number was not better than epected but within
expectations,'' said Jack Garry, equity analyst with Butcher &amp;
Singer Inc. ``It gave people the impetus to get out there and buy.''
   The March Consumer Price Index pushed the annual inflation rate
to 6.1 percent, higher than the 4.4 percent increase in 1988.
Consumer prices rose 0.6 percent in January and 0.4 percent in
February.
   ``The market is still concerned about inflation but the figures
were encouraging,'' Garry said.
   Analysts said the sharp decline in housing starts, spurred by
rising mortgage rates, also increased the likelihood that the
Federal Reserve would not continue raising interest rates and might
even move to lower rates.
   ``Clearly the economy is slowing and clearly the Fed may have to
ease monetary policy,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at
First Albany Corp.
</TEXT>
