<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-18 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude, Gasoline Prices Push Ahead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil and gasoline futures prices rose again
Tuesday, driven higher by buying due to supply considerations and
technical market factors. Wholesale home heating oil prices pulled
back.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, West Texas Intermediate,
increased 29 cents to settle at $21.51 per 42-gallon barrel. The
contract had gained 93 cents in the two previous sessions.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
unleaded gasoline for May delivery spurted 1.78 cents to 73.86
cents a gallon, after rising 2.06 cents and 1.21 cents on Monday
and Friday, respectively.
   The near-month crude and gasoline contracts are now trading at
the highest levels since January 1986.
   May wholesale home heating oil, which rose 0.85 cent Monday,
skidded 1 cent and settled at 52.76 cents a gallon.
   Several considerations motivated energy brokers to buy Tuesday,
said Mary L. Haskins, a vice president at Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc.
   Traders bought partly to adjust their holdings before the May
crude contract expires on Thursday. A widespread expectation that
weekly industry statistics due late Tuesday would show a
significant reduction in petroleum stocks also encouraged buying as
did a report that output from an oil platform in the North Sea was
disrupted due to a leak.
   Continuing speculation that supplies will be unusually tight
this spring and summer has lent a bullish tone to the energy
markets lately, particularly in the past three weeks since an Exxon
oil tanker accidentally spilled 10 million gallons of oil in
Valdez, Alaska.
</TEXT>
