<FIRST>u f AM-KodakProducts Bjt   04-18 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak Products, Bjt,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Introduces Two Disposable Cameras, New Film</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disposable camera craze will be
coming to a beach and scenic lookout near you very soon thanks to
Eastman Kodak Co.
   The company introduced two throw-away 35mm cameras Tuesday, one
that can be used underwater and another that has a special
wide-angle lens to better capture panoramic views and group shots.
   Both cameras come already loaded with a roll of film and cost
under $15.
   ``With lower prices, added quality and versatility, cameras are
becoming personalized,'' said Wilbur Prezzano, general manager of
photographic products for Kodak.
   Disposable cameras, which are basically cardboard and plastic
wrapped around a roll of film, are used once and taken to a
photofinisher, who removes the film and throws away the camera.
   They were first introduced in Japan several years ago and have
become quite popular there. Both Kodak and Fuji Photo Film Co.
introduced disposable models in the United States in 1987.
   Initially, the disposable cameras were designed for sale to
tourists who may have forgotten their cameras and wanted some
vacation photos. But the two new cameras introduced by Kodak are
designed to broaden that appeal.
   ``These cameras are basically creating new picture opportunities
and bringing more people into photography and that's good,'' said
Mark Obenzinger, a stock analyst with Wood, Gundy &amp; Co. in New York.
   Obenzinger said 9 million disposable cameras will be sold
worldwide this year according to industry estimates. Next year,
that number is expected to reach 15 million.
   Although that's still a small amount, considering that Kodak
estimates there are currently 330 million regular, or
non-disposable, cameras in use around the world, the fast growth
rate has attracted the photo giant's eye.
   That means Kodak will be introducing more disposable cameras in
the future, Prezzano said.
   ``We will continue to brainstorm and ... get feedback from
consumers as to what their needs are. The only limit is the number
of good ideas people come up with,'' he said.
   The two new cameras are:
   _The ``Stretch'' camera, which has a list price of $12.95. It
produces unusual long and narrow prints, 3{ by 10 inches, with a
wide-angle lens. It can capture about one-third more area than
standard ``point-and-shoot'' 35mm cameras.
   It's for use outdoors only and comes loaded with a roll of
200-speed Kodacolor Gold film.
   The ``Stretch'' camera will be available in Europe this summer.
A similar model will also be sold in Japan. The ``Stretch'' will be
available in the United States later this year.
   _The ``Weekend 35'' camera, which can take photographs up to 12
feet underwater and comes loaded with a roll of 24-exposure
Kodacolor Gold 400-speed film.
   Its retail price is $13.95. Kodak will begin selling it along
U.S. coastal areas in late June.
   Kodak also said Tuesday it plans to change the packaging on its
200-speed Kodacolor Gold 35mm film to include the words
``Multi-purpose film'' on the box.
   Analysts said this in response to the introduction two weeks ago
of OneFilm by Polaroid Corp., which company officials touted as a
kind of one-size-fits-all film for consumers who were confused
about what film to buy.
   Kodak also introduced three new 35mm films: a 125-speed film to
round out its new Ektar line for advanced amateur photographers; a
1600-speed Kodacolor Gold color negative film to bring high speed
to its regular line of film; and an improved 400-speed Kodacolor
Gold.
</TEXT>
