<FIRST>u f AM-Ramada     04-18 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ramada,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ramada Agrees to Sell Hotel Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc. will pare down to a gambling
operation and lose its name after completing an agreement to sell
its 825 hotels and motels to New World Development Co. of Hong Kong
for $540 million, Ramada announced Tuesday.
   In turn, Prime Motor Inns of Fairfield, N.J., will pay an
undisclosed sum to New World to operate as franchisor of roughly
600 hotels and motels in the United States that are under the
Ramada and Rodeway names.
   The sale of the hotel group will reduce Ramada's holdings to
three casinos in Nevada and one in Atlantic City, N.J. The Ramada
name will belong to New World, and the gaming company will continue
its headquarters in Phoenix under a new name, which has not been
selected, Cole said.
   Ramada announced March 24 that it had agreed to sell its Marie
Callender Pie Shops restaurant business. That sale for undisclosed
terms will be completed by the end of the month, Cole said.
   Cole said he expected completion of the restructuring within two
to three months.
   Shareholders in Ramada will get $7 a share in cash and
one-quarter share in a new company formed to own and operate
Ramada's present gaming business.
   The transaction is a major step in Ramada's restructuring plan,
begun last October, company Chairman Richard Snell said.
   ``New World and Prime are making a major commitment to achieve
success for the 800-plus hotels in the Ramada and Rodeway
systems,'' Snell said in a prepared release. ``The present Ramada
Inc. shareholders will benefit from their investment with cash and
a continuing interest in the new gaming company.''
   The hotel group has more than 144,000 rooms under the Ramada
Inns, Ramada Hotels, Rodeway Inns and Renaissance Hotels banners.
Prime Motor Inns will not act as franchisor for the Renaissance
Hotels or any overseas Ramada properties.
   Cole said the new company had no immediate plans to purchase
other casinos. Its four properties will be TropWorld Casino and
Entertainment Resort in Atlantic City, Tropicana Resort and Casino
in Las Vegas, Ramada Express Hotel Casino Laughlin, Nev., and
Eddie's Fabulous 50's Casino in Reno.
   He said the new company would employ about 10,000 people. Ramada
currently employs about 20,000 _ half in its gaming operations,
5,600 in the hotel group, and about 3,400 in the restaurant
business.
   Studies last year persuaded the directing board that gaming was
the way to profitability.
   The company lost $5.1 million last year, but Cole said the new
smaller company expected to return to profitability.
   Last year Ramada got $477 million in revenue from casino
operations and $244 million from hotels and motels. It had income
from continuing operations from casinos of $40 million and
operating income from hotels and motels of $15 million.
   Cole announced a preliminary estimate of first-quarter results
showing revenues of $124 million and operating losses of $19
million. Ramada had sales of $101.9 million and a $364,000
operating loss in the year-earlier quarter.
</TEXT>
