<FIRST>u f AM-Bush-Farmers 1stLd-Writethru   04-18 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Farmers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speedup in Crop Payments Announced to Help Farmers Recover from Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 17, bgng ``Asked if,'' to refer to current drought
in winter wheat belt; adds four grafs on export subsidy program. Also moved
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday announced a speedup
in crop payments to help farmers recover from last summer's drought
but said that ``perilous budget-deficit times'' will mean cuts in
other farm programs.
   Speaking on a radio interview program from the Agriculture
Department, Bush said he was authorizing the acceleration of
price-support payments ``to provide some extra money to farmers
early in the crop year.''
   ``We're listening. We are with the American farmer in these
tough times,'' Bush said.
   He said the move would mean about $850 million in early payments
for wheat, feed-grain, rice and cotton farmers.
   The step also helps budget writers meet deficit-reduction
targets for 1990 by shifting the $850 million out of fiscal 1990,
which begins on Oct. 1, and into the current fiscal year.
   Bush, putting on headphones in a small broadcast booth in the
Agriculture Department, answered questions from agricultural
broadcasters for about 15 minutes. The program was sent out over
the agency's agricultural radio network.
   The president also announced creation of a working group on
rural development to be headed by Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter. He said the group would evaluate existing federal
rural-development programs and make recommendations.
   ``Events such as last year's drought reinforce the need to
develop and diversify the rural economy in the years ahead,'' Bush
said.
   The price announcement made by Bush makes an additional 10
percent available to farmers in so-called advance-deficiency
payments.
   These are advances farmers can draw from the government at the
start of a crop season against later payments.
   Tuesday's action raised from the current 40 percent to 50
percent the size of advance payments wheat and feed-grain farmers
can collect, and from 30 percent to 40 percent the share rice and
cotton farmers can collect in advance.
   The advances are against anticipated government support
subsidies to help farmers recover the difference between market
prices and federally set target prices.
   One interviewer asked Bush how he reconciled heavy cuts in farm
programs under the budget compromise recently negotiated by the
White House and congressional leaders with his campaign vow not to
balance the budget on farmer's back.
   ``We are in perilous budget-deficit times. We've got to get the
deficit down. And the best thing we can do to help the American
farmer is to get these interest rates down. And the best way to do
that is to make the tough decision on the spending side of our
budget,'' he said.
   ``Now, having said that, I feel that farmers are (for) fair
play,'' Bush added.
   ``Yes, `ag' is taking a hit. But so is a wide array of programs
across the board,'' he said.
   Asked if the speedup in payments would be the sum total of
federal help for producers who are being hurt by the drought
currently gripping Kansas and much of the winter wheat area, Bush
said: ``This should not be viewed as the definitive answer. We hope
it is something that will help the farm family.''
   Yeutter, who appeared with Bush on the program, added: ``Clearly
we don't have an open spigot that just spits out federal dollars in
any situation today. But we'll be as sympathetic and as
accommodative as we can be within rather severe budgetary
restraints.''
   Asked about reports that the government's program to subsidize
exports of wheat and other farm commodities is being scuttled,
Yeutter said no such plan is in the works. However, as he has
previously, Yeutter said the USDA's Export Enhancement Program, or
EEP, will come under review.
   But no EEP allocations currently in effect will be curtailed, he
said. The program provides subsidies to private exporters for the
sale of designated commodities to specific countries at reduced
prices. The object is to make U.S. products competitive with other
foreign suppliers, notably the European Economic Community.
   ``All that is at issue at the moment is any future allocations
that might be made'' under the EEP, he said. Those will be
considered on a case-by-case basis ``primarily because of our
stocks (of grain) condition and the weather conditions that now
prevail.''
   But Yeutter stressed that ``this is not to suggest that we're
going to put any kind of moratorium on the EEP program ... we
haven't made that kind of decision.''
</TEXT>
