<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Phone     04-18 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Phone,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Earnings Rise 15 Percent; MCI Up 121 Percent; SW Bell Up 9.2
Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone companies reported higher earnings Tuesday, with gains
of 121 percent at MCI Communications Corp., 15 percent at GTE Corp.
and 9.2 percent at Southwestern Bell Corp.
   MCI, the Washington-based long-distance company, said its
earnings rose to a record $128 million, or 51 cents a share, from
$58 million or 20 cents a share a year earlier. Revenue rose 33
percent to $1.5 billion from $1.13 billion a year earlier.
   Bert C. Roberts Jr., MCI's president and chief operating
officer, attributed the success to increased traffic that more than
offset a rate cut. MCI signed data-networking contracts during the
quarter with such companies as Chrysler Corp. and Cray Research
Inc., Roberts said.
   GTE said its earnings rose to $329 million, or 97 cents a share,
from $286 million, or 84 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 5 percent to $4.1 billion from $3.9 billion a year earlier.
   Local telephone service, the company's major business, gained 7
percent in revenue to $3 billion. It said operating income rose
only fractionally to $689 million because of rate actions by
regulators in California and Texas.
   St. Louis-based Southwestern Bell said its net income for the
first quarter rose to $238.8 million, or 79 cents a share, compared
with earnings of $218.7 million, or 73 cents a share, in the first
quarter of last year. Revenue rose 2.9 percent to $2.1 billion from
$2 billion in 1988.
   Southwestern Bell Chairman Zane Barnes said the improvement was
tied to to the region's economic recovery.
</TEXT>
