<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-18 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palladium Futures Plunge Again On Fusion Skepticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Palladium futures prices plummeted the permitted daily limit for
the second straight session Tuesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange amid growing skepticism about the market impact of recent
nuclear fusion research.
   Other precious metals prices also declined, largely in reaction
to government reports that showed weaker inflation than many
observers had expected.
   On other markets, gasoline futures surged while other petroleum
futures were mixed; grain and soybean futures retreated; and
livestock and meat were mixed.
   Palladium settled $3.35 to $9 lower with the contract for
delivery in June at $165.65 a troy ounce. The daily price limit was
expanded to $9 from $6 following Monday's limit decline.
   The spot price of palladium on the New York Merc fell to $165 a
troy ounce, $20 below the 8-year high reached last Thursday on
speculation that demand for the white metal would explode in the
wake of a startling fusion experiment at the University of Utah.
   In that project, scientists used both palladium and platinum as
components in an experiment in which they claimed to have recreated
in a jar of water the nuclear reaction that powers the sun and
stars.
   Palladium and platinum futures prices fell sharply Monday
following weekend news reports that the Utah finding was unlikely
to stir significant new demand for the metals.
   More speculators bailed out or took profits on Tuesday, despite
Utah chemistry professor B. Stanley Pons' announcement that more
than 60 university and private laboratories had at least partially
verified the results obtained by him and his research partner,
Martin Fleischmann of the University of Southampton, England.
   ``No one's really sure what are the practical applications and
how long it will take for it to reallly absorb into the market,''
said Jack Barbanel, director of futures trading with Gruntal &amp; Co.,
a New York brokerage house.
   Platinum futures prices also fell, but much more modestly than
palladium and more in line with gold, which slipped in reaction to
the Labor Department's report of a lower-than-expected 0.5 percent
rise in consumer prices in March.
   Platinum settled $2.20 to $2.70 lower on the New York Merc with
July at $548.50 a troy ounce. On New York's Commodity Exchange,
gold settled $2.70 to $3.50 lower with June at $387.40 a troy
ounce; silver was 5 cents to 7.9 cents lower with May at $5.78 a
troy ounce.
   Gasoline futures continued their strong advance on the New York
Merc on expectations that the American Petroleum Institute's weekly
survey would show a drop in U.S. gasoline supplies.
   Indeed, the API reported after the close that gasoline stocks
fell by 2.1 million barrels last week. Crude oil stocks were down
5.7 million barrels and distillate stocks increased by 516,000
barrels.
   In Tuesday's trading, West Texas Intermediate crude settled 3
cents lower to 29 cents higher with May at $21.51 a barrel; heating
oil was .21 cent to 1 cent lower with May at 52.76 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .90 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with May
at 73.86 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade on a forecast for rain in the Corn Belt and
signs that the United States is becoming stingier with its wheat
exports.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 3\ cents lower with May at $4.07 a
bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.75{ a
bushel; oats were } cent to 1{ cents lower with May at $1.98\ a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents lower to 1\ cents higher with May at
$7.48{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures finished narrowly mixed in choppy,
lackluster trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent lower to .28 cent higher with June
at 71.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .27 cent
higher with May at 76.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with June at 46.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .30 cent lower to .60 cent higher with May at
33.30 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
