<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Computers     04-18 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Computers,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Computer Reports 29 Percent Profit Drop; Lotus Off 71 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. reported a 29 percent drop in its quarterly
profit Tuesday, while Lotus Development Corp. said its earnings
fell 71 percent.
   Apple, the personal computer giant based in Cupertino, Calif.,
said earnings in its second fiscal quarter were hurt by previously
announced problems with high-cost computer memory chips.
   Apple's net income fell to $56.4 million from $79.7 million
while earnings per share were 44 cents compared to 61 cents for the
second quarter of 1988.
   Net sales were $1.25 billion, a 44 percent increase over the net
sales of $867 million a year ago.
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, Apple said its
profit slipped to $196.8 million, or $1.54 per share, from $201
million, or $1.53 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $2.65
billion from $1.91 billion.
   John Sculley, Apple's chairman and chief executive, said the
problem of an oversupply of chips bought at peak prices ``is now
substantially behind us.''
   International sales accounted for 40 percent of total revenues
during the second quarter. The figure was 38 percent in the second
quarter last year.
   ``Macintosh sales continue to record strong gains around the
world,'' said Sculley.
   In January, the company, fresh from a 16 percent profit jump in
the first quarter, said it expected earnings to drop significantly.
Analysts predicted earnings per share would fall to 35 cents to 45
cents.
   The purchase of the 1 million-bit memory chips was made at a
time when prices were high because of a worldwide shortage of the
memory chip. Apple then increased its prices on the more expensive
models of its Macintosh system, a move that hurt sales when
customers favored less expensive systems.
   In an effort to rekindle sales, Apple cut the prices on its
higher-priced Macintosh models.
   ``We are well on our way to surpassing $5 billion in revenues
this fiscal year,'' Sculley said today. ``As we enter the second
half of fiscal 1989, we are experiencing strong demand for our
Macintosh products, particularly our two newest computers, the
SE-30 and the IIcx.''
   Lotus, the Cambridge, Mass.-based maker of personal computer
software, said first-quarter earnings fell to $5.3 million, or 13
cents a share, from $18.3 million, or 40 cents a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose to $120 million from $117.3 million a year
earlier.
   Lotus hit a setback last fall when it announced that the newest
version of the spreadsheet program Lotus 1-2-3, the engine that has
driven growth since 1983, was projected to be shipped in the second
quarter of 1989 instead of the end of 1988 as planned.
   Company officials said Tuesday that Release 3 of 1-2-3, a
three-dimensional spreadsheet, is being tested and is on schedule
for June shipment.
   ``First-quarter revenues came in as expected and we're
encouraged by a number of trends,'' said Jim Manzi, Lotus president.
</TEXT>
