<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-18 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Lower In Europe; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Tuesday in reaction to an
inflation report that helped stocks and bonds. Gold prices also
fell.
   The Labor Department said consumer prices rose 0.5 percent in
March, which was in line with expectations and diminished concern
that the Federal Reserve would tighten credit to slow the economy
and quell inflation.
   Tight credit is bad for the stock and bond markets but it helps
the dollar by encouraging foreign investors to buy dollars to take
advantage of high U.S. interest rates.
   The government report confirmed that inflation has reached a
higher plateau but nonetheless did not indicate inflation as severe
as some had predicted.
   ``It was just another indication to the interest-rate players
that perhaps the Fed can sit back for the time being without
forcing rates higher,'' said Scott Horwitz, a senior trader at the
Bank of Boston in New York.
   Friday's news that the March producer price index rose only 0.4
percent had already signaled the slowdown.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7185 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7095 Monday. The
pound also rose against the dollar in New York, to $1.7164 from
$1.7133.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.27 Japanese yen to a closing 132.10 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 131.48 yen. In New York, the
dollar fell to 131.40 yen from 132.16.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8525 West German marks, down from 1.8605; 1.6270
Swiss francs, down from 1.6405; 1.1863 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1850; 6.2710 French francs, down from 6.3005; and 1,360.13
Italian lire, down from 1,366.35.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.8528 West German marks, down from 1.8565; 1.6283 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6385; 6.2750 French francs, down from 6.2825; 2.0935
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0953; 1,366.95 Italian lire, up from
1,364.00; 1.1848 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1855.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell 6 cents to close at a bid $386.68 a troy
ounce.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $383.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $385.00 bid late Monday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold
fell to close at a bid $384.00 compared with $384.50 bid late
Monday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold fell to $383.50 an
ounce from $386.20 Monday. Later, Republic National Bank of New
York said gold bullion was bid at $383.10 an ounce as of 4 p.m.
EDT, down from $385.30 late Monday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market to a late bid
price of $5.78 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $5.80. On the
New York Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $5.763
an ounce from $5.811 on Monday.
</TEXT>
