<FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Shoreham-IRS     04-18 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham-IRS,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Rules LILCO May Deduct Shoreham Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has ruled that
Long Island Lighting Co. can write off losses it would sustain as a
result of a plan to scrap the Shoreham nuclear power plant, utility
officials said Tuesday.
   The decision will allow LILCO to write off some $2.8 billion in
losses it anticipates if it wins approval of a deal to sell
Shoreham to the state, which would then dismantle it, LILCO
spokesman Jim Lois said.
   The IRS's latest ruling confirmed its Sept. 15 decision to allow
LILCO to write off losses from an earlier plan to dismantle
Shoreham, he said. That plan, which had required approval of the
state Legislature, fell apart when lawmakers declined to vote and
the deal expired.
   But New York Gov. Mario Cuomo and LILCO reached a new settlement
earlier this year which did not require legislative approval. The
new agreement, which would sell Shoreham to the state for $1 in
exchange for a decade of annual rate increases of up to 5 percent,
is one step away from approval.
   ``I guess what (the IRS) did is they reviewed the new settlement
agreement, realized it's fundamentally the same for tax purposes as
the agreement of 1988, and have isued a letter ruling that we
received today confirming our entitlement to a tax writeoff,'' Lois
said.
   The IRS ruling came one day after the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission staff reported that the embattled $5.5 billion plant
meets all federal safety requirements and is ``operationally
ready.'' NRC Chairman Lando Zech tentatively set a vote on the
full-power license for Thursday and all indications are the license
will be granted.
   However, the action may be largely symbolic. Under the latest
shutdown plan, LILCO has agreed not to put the license to use until
its shareholders vote on the negotiated settlement. That vote must
take place on or before June 15, and LILCO Chairman William J.
Catacosinos told the NRC Monday that the utility's board will
recommend that shareholders approve the deal.
   LILCO and the state would then seek to have Shoreham's license
transferred to the Long Island Power Authority and the New York
Power Authority would oversee decommissioning and dismantling of
the plant.
   However, the Department of Energy has said it would attempt to
block transfer of the license, although a DOE spokesman said Monday
that strategy was still being worked out.
</TEXT>
