<FIRST>r f BC-US-KoreaTrade     04-18 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-US-Korea Trade,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Minister Begins High-Level Meetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's minister of trade and industry
began a series of meetings with top U.S. officials Monday about the
two countries' booming trade and U.S. irritation over Korea's
multibillion-dollar surplus with America.
   Minister Han Seung-soo's visit was regarded as part of Seoul's
efforts to persuade the Bush administration not to target South
Korea under a new U.S. law authorizing sanctions against countries
with persistent surpluses regarded as the result of trade practices
harmful to American business.
   Han met Monday with Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, U.S.
Trade Representative Carla Hills and officials of the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce. He was Mosbacher's dinner guest. The minister also met
Edward Derwinski, secretary of veterans affairs, whose past
relations with Korea were aired during Derwinski's confirmation
process.
   Meetings were scheduled Tuesday with Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter and influential
Democratic Congressmen Dan Rostenkowski and Sam Gibbons.
   Han planned more Washington meetings Wednesday followed by a
visit to New York to address the Asia Society and meet former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger.
   His visit was preceded by the announcement last week of
purchases of more than $1.5 billion worth of U.S. jetliners by
Korean-based carriers.
   Two-way U.S.-South Korean trade is about $35 billion a year,
with last year's U.S. deficit $8.6 billion.
   Korea boosted purchases of American products 45 percent last
year and is second only to Japan in purchase of U.S. foodstuffs. It
is the sixth-largest overall buyer of American products.
</TEXT>
