<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Polaroid     04-18 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Polaroid,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Up 82.4 Percent Despite Takeover Fight Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. said Tuesday its
first-quarter profit climbed 82.4 percent despite the sizeable
costs of a bitter eight-month battle to stave off a takeover
attempt.
   Net earnings were $25.9 million, or 29 cents per share, for the
first quarter compared with $14.2 million, or 23 cents a share, in
the first quarter of 1988.
   First-quarter revenue rose 7.8 percent to $442.3 million from
$410.1 million a year earlier.
   The latest results include $38.5 million in expenses involved in
fighting off Shamrock Holdings Inc.'s hostile bid.
   Those expenses included $20 million reimbursement for a portion
of Shamrock's expenses stemming from the litigation and tender
offer and $18.5 million in its own legal, investment banking and
other expenses.
   Operating profits nearly tripled to $73.4 million from $26.2
million in the same period in 1988.
   I. MacAllister Booth, Polaroid president and chief executive,
said the first quarter profits resulted from changes made in the
cost structure, manufacturing operations and work force at the
company.
   ``Expanding consumer, business and industrial instant film usage
is a key element in our overall strategy,'' said Booth. ``...This
redirection of our marketing efforts has enabled us to spend
marketing dollars more efficiently, reducing marketing expenses
while, at the same time, allowing us to target the distinct heavy
film user groups in each of our businesses.''
</TEXT>
