<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Lockheed     04-18 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Lockheed,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Profit Down 43 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. said Tuesday its first
quarter profit plummeted 43 percent, due primarily to the
completion of a major Air Force cargo plane order and an increase
in its effective tax rate.
   Net earnings, which included discontinued operations, were $62
million, or $1.04 per share, compared with $114 million, or $1.84
per share, for the same period of 1988.
   Sales for the first quarter totaled $2 billion, down from
revenue of $2.4 billion in the first quarter of 1988.
   Lockheed Chairman Daniel M. Tellep said the downturn was in line
with company expectations noted in an April 4 reorganization
announcement.
   Tellep blamed the earnings decline primarily on completion of
the 50-plane C-5B cargo jet production program and an increase in
the effective tax rate.
   Adjustments of about $10 million for cost increases on two
aircraft modification programs and the timing of C-130 transport
deliveries also contributed to the downturn in revenues and program
profits, he said.
   The aerospace company delivered four C-130s in the first three
months of 1989 compared with 10 of the aircraft during the same
period a year ago. Tellep stressed that C-130 deliveries for all of
1989 were expected to be comparable to the 36 delivered last year.
</TEXT>
